<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Aims To Change Local Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Building on his pledge to strip federal  
money from poor performing schools, George W. Bush said Monday that 
he would redefine the role of the federal government in education 
to ``essentially pass power back from Washington, D.C., to local 
jurisdictions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate said he would encourage  
local governments to develop strong systems to ensure that schools 
are held accountable if their students are not learning. 
</P>
<P>
	He planned to detail his plan in New York City on Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	In the first installment of his education package, Bush last  
month outlined plans to take federal funds from the worst-scoring 
schools and transfer the approximately $1,500 per pupil in federal 
funds to parents for use toward educational alternatives, such as 
private schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we spend federal money and find children in failed  
schools, I will free the parents from failures, so that their 
children are not left behind,'' he said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Touring upstate New York for the first time as a candidate, the  
Republican presidential front-runner said he was heartened by an 
outpouring of support, which began with a $250,000 boost to his $56 
million campaign treasury at a fund-raising breakfast in Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush raised about $200,000 more at a $1,000-a-plate luncheon in  
Rochester, where he also visited a center for troubled teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important for our young to hear that drugs will destroy  
you,'' he told the youngsters. ``It's important to make right 
choices in order to be able to access the American dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush scheduled a third fund-raising event in Syracuse later in  
the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent independent polls have shown Bush running close to Vice  
President Al Gore in New York and trailing former New Jersey 
Democratic Sen. Bill Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've got a good chance here. It's a tough state, I'm  
under no illusions,'' he said. ``There's no question it's going to 
be a tough campaign here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York Gov. George Pataki accompanied Bush throughout the day.  
The Texas governor deflected questions about Pataki's chances of 
making the GOP ticket as the vice presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little premature for someone who hasn't earned his  
party's nomination to be speculating on the vice presidency,'' Bush 
said. ``I've got a lot of work to do. George Pataki is a good 
friend. He has done a great job as the governor of New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said his goal for the country heading into the next century  
is ``prosperity with a purpose,'' possible by cutting taxes, 
reducing regulations and embracing free trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must be prosperous to keep the peace,'' he said, promising  
to rebuild the military. ``This is still a world of madmen and 
missiles and terror.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Prosperity isn't a given. Prosperity doesn't just happen,''  
Bush told about 200 supporters at the Buffalo breakfast. He charged 
that members of the current administration talk as if they invented 
prosperity. But they ``no more invented prosperity than they 
invented the Internet,'' he said in a swipe at Vice President Al 
Gore, who has said he helped create the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Clinton drove President Bush, the Texas governor's father,  
from office in 1992 in part by stressing the nation's economic 
downturn. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also said he would encourage people to get involved in  
mentoring and drug programs as a step toward welfare reform, later 
elaborating on the theme during a stop at Mount Olive Baptist 
Church in Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government can hand out money but it cannot put hope in  
their hearts or a sense of purpose in their lives,'' he said. 
``This is found in churches, synagogues and charities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In head-to-head matchups, a Zogby International poll released  
Monday showed Gore and Bush in a dead heat. Bradley had a slight 
lead over Bush. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
