<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. Teacher Drug-Testing Upheld </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today let Knox County,  
Tenn., school officials require drug testing of everyone offered a 
teaching job. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away a teachers group's  
argument that such tests are unconstitutional if officials do not 
suspect the tested individual of using drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug-testing program adopted in 1994 by the Knox County  
Board of Education requires everyone offered a job considered 
``safety sensitive'' to undergo urinalysis drug testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Jobs considered safety sensitive include teachers, principals  
and assistant principals, teacher aides, school secretaries and bus 
drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	The policy was challenged in federal court by the Knox County  
Education Association, an organization of teachers, principals and 
other professional school employees. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge threw out the suspicionless testing requirement  
after finding that there was no documented evidence of a drug abuse 
problem among teachers and that teaching is not heavily regulated 
for safety reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed that ruling last  
year. The appeals court said that even without evidence of a drug 
problem among teachers, drug testing is justified by the ``unique 
role'' teachers play in school children's lives. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers and principals are ``front-line observers in providing  
for a safe school environment,'' the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	In past rulings, the Supreme Court has said the government can  
allow drug testing of customs agents and railroad employees 
involved in serious accidents. The justices also have let public 
schools require student athletes to undergo drug testing. 
</P>
<P>
	But in 1997, the justices ruled that states cannot force  
political candidates to take drug tests merely to demonstrate the 
government's commitment to the war on drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, the teachers group's lawyers said  
the drug testing at issue was so broad that taking cough syrup 
could lead to a positive result. 
</P>
<P>
	Suspicionless drug testing must be shown to be ``an effective  
and credible means of addressing a real and urgent need, rather 
than merely a symbolic step,'' the appeal contended. 
</P>
<P>
	The school board's lawyers urged the court to reject the appeal,  
saying evidence of drug use by teachers is not necessary to justify 
a drug-testing plan. Teachers must stay alert to ensure student 
safety, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Knox County Education Association vs. Knox County  
Board of Education, 98-1799. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
