<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 08:25:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indian Kashmir Has Voting Disrupted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANANTNAG, India (AP) -- Making good their threat to disrupt polls  
in Kashmir, separatist militants triggered four explosions during 
voting today, injuring 18 security force personnel and two polling 
agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine police officers were injured when rebels fired a rocket at  
a polling center in Pulwama, 20 miles south of the regional 
capital, Srinagar, an hour before polls opened this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Frightened residents did not venture out of their homes until  
several hours later, and then only a trickle came to vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more explosions in nearby areas injured nine other police  
and two polling agents who were supervising voting. Another 
explosion near a polling booth damaged it, but injured no one. 
</P>
<P>
	The monthlong general elections ended for most of the country on  
Sunday, and major exit polls declared that the coalition of Prime 
Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee would return to power with a stable 
majority. 
</P>
<P>
	But the vote had been postponed in Anantnag because the local  
candidate of Vajpayee's party was assassinated a week before the 
original Sept. 18 polling day. 
</P>
<P>
	Separatist militants have successfully called general strikes  
and poll boycotts on each day that Kashmir has been scheduled to 
vote for a new Indian national parliament. The rebels say elections 
do not give them the right of self determination that is their key 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of separatist groups have been fighting for a decade for  
Kashmir's independence or merger with neighboring Pakistan. More 
than 25,000 people have been killed since the fighting began in 
1989 in India's only Muslim majority region. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thousands of people have shed their blood for the freedom  
struggle. We don't want their sacrifice to go in vain so I didn't 
vote,'' said Ghulam Ahmad Tantaray, 60, a farmer harvesting his 
rice crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting also took place today in nine constituencies in the  
eastern state of Bihar, in areas where flooding had postponed the 
scheduled balloting, or vote rigging had taken place. 
</P>
<P>
	Repolling or delayed voting is also scheduled in some states on  
Tuesday, Wednesday and Oct. 28. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen candidates were seeking local or national office in the  
Anantnag district and 994 polling booths were set up to serve 
800,000 eligible voters. 
</P>
<P>
	But most of the polls were empty, with election workers sitting  
idly as the violence and the boycott call kept most voters indoors. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldiers, reservists and special police patrolled the deserted  
roads, stood guard at empty crossroads in the towns and set up 
machine-gun positions in rice fields, where the crops harvested on 
Sunday lay piled in the paddies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
