<DOCNO> APW19991004.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 18:10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hatch: McCain Bill Would Hurt GOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Sen. Orrin Hatch said Monday that a  
campaign finance reform effort by fellow Republican senator and 
rival presidential candidate John McCain would starve the GOP of 
money for elections. 
</P>
<P>
	A bill by McCain that is pending in Congress would ban the  
unlimited ``soft money'' contributions that corporations and other 
organizations make to political parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the money we use to get out the vote,'' Hatch, of Utah,  
told about 40 people at the Commonwealth Club of California. 
``Literally, it would be the disarmament -- the unilateral 
disarmament -- of the Republican Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He claimed the bill would allow traditionally liberal interests  
such as labor unions and environmental groups to send unlimited 
sums of money to the Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the bill would ban union, corporate and individual  
``soft money'' donations to political parties. Independent 
expenditures by unions or corporations for such things as political 
advertisements would be permitted. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no consensus on which party would suffer more under the  
bill by McCain, R-Ariz., and Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis. McCain says 
it would hurt Democratic fund-raising efforts at least as much as 
the GOP's, because both parties get roughly the same proportion of 
corporate contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch also argued that the bill would restrict ``legitimate''  
First Amendment rights. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he asked listeners to envision a president  
``who really doesn't owe anybody anything,'' because he hasn't been 
influenced by campaign donors. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch has raised more than $1 million this year, but the figure  
is dwarfed by the more than $56 million collected by GOP 
presidential front-runner George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch also said he would support efforts to limit the influence  
of political donations by requiring daily disclosure on the 
Internet of all such contributions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
