<DOCNO> APW19991004.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 00:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astros Have More Time at Astrodome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The building that brought the world AstroTurf  
will have at least one more baseball game. 
</P>
<P>
	But even as the Houston Astros earned themselves one more game  
at the Astrodome with a 9-4 victory over the Los Angeles Dodgers on 
Sunday, the team and the fans still said goodbye to the ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros finished their 35th and final season inside the dome  
in front of Nolan Ryan and other team greats by clinching their 
third straight NL Central title and a playoff berth. 
</P>
<P>
	They'll play either the Cincinnati Reds or the New York Mets for  
the first two games of a best-of-5 series, and then return to the 
Dome for Game 3 on Friday and a fourth game later, if necessary. 
The Mets were scheduled to play the Reds today at Cinergy Field to 
determine the NL wild-card winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's crucial game was sandwiched between celebrations  
honoring the more than three decades of indoor Astros baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Astros manager Larry Dierker, an 18-year-old rising prospect  
with Houston when the stadium opened, threw out the ceremonial 
first pitch to thunderous applause from 52,033 fans. Sunday's 
attendance made it five straight with 50,000 fans or more, a club 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Immediately afterward, I don't think it hits you. But as the  
evening progresses, I think it rose on you,'' Dierker said. ``I 
wouldn't be surprised if I don't shed a tear before the night is 
over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Country singer Charley Pride delivered a low-key rendition of  
``The Star-Spangled Banner,'' and then the Astros turned to the 
business of keeping their season -- and baseball in the Astrodome -- 
alive for another day. The Astros coasted to the victory, but there 
was still suspense in the last inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Powell withstood hundreds of flashbulbs through two batters  
as he tried to get the final out. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans rose to their feet as Mark Grudzielanek stepped to the  
plate, but he singled to score Dave Hansen and make it 9-4. 
</P>
<P>
	With the count 3-2, Powell struck out Raul Mondesi, closing the  
last regular-season game at the Astrodome under a shower of red, 
white and blue confetti. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was teary-eyed when it was over because I loved this  
place,'' said Michelle Christopher, who said she has been to dozens 
of Astros games and even the bizarre bloodless bullfights held at 
the Astrodome on Feb. 4, 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the crowd stayed for postgame ceremonies, which Craig  
Biggio started early with a tradition from the world of auto 
racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Biggio, a large cigar clenched in his teeth, and winning pitcher  
Mike Hampton rode a victory lap atop a Harley-Davidson. Soon, the 
entire sweat-drenched team ran a victory lap on foot and traded 
high-fives with fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This being the last regular season game here made it all  
pretty sweet. The fans were awesome,'' Biggio said. ``The people 
here in the Dome deserve this one too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Astros announcer Gene Elston introduced the opening day  
roster from 1965, the year the Astrodome opened, and then some 
three dozen former and present Astros players voted by fans to the 
all-time Astros team took the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan, a Hall of Famer who pitched his fifth career no-hitter in  
the Astrodome, drew the biggest applause as he was introduced. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the squad was Mike Scott, who on Sept. 25, 1986, pitched  
the only no-hitter ever to decide a division title. Powered by 
Scott's pitching, the Astros captured the NL West with a 2-0 
victory over the San Francisco Giants on that date. 
</P>
<P>
	Fan favorite Jose Cruz, now a first base coach for the Astros,  
drew what sounded like boos as fans greeted him with ``Cruuuz.'' 
Current stars Biggio and Jeff Bagwell also were announced as part 
of the all-time team. 
</P>
<P>
	To close the night, country star Willie Nelson sang, ``Turn Out  
the Lights, the Party's Over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the famed exploding scoreboard has been gone for 11 years  
-- removed to make way for 10,000 extra seats at the request of the 
since-departed NFL Houston Oilers -- the massive ``Diamond Vision'' 
TV screens played a facsimile of the original scoreboard's salute 
to home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	The massive bull snorted fire from his nostrils and the cowboy  
shot his six-gun one last time. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
