<DOCNO> APW19991004.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 20:35:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Johnson Seeks End to Playoff Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Great pitching, little support. Randy Johnson's  
postseason experiences are a lot like his season with Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	His major league-record five consecutive playoff losses, like  
his 17-9 record this year, hardly reflect how well he has pitched. 
So Johnson sees no need to defend himself as he prepares to pitch 
in Arizona's opener Tuesday night against the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at the postseason, I've pitched pretty well,''  
Johnson said Monday. ``It's not like I've been a total flop. People 
just look at the numbers and they want wins, and that's all I want. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than probably anybody in the clubhouse on the day I  
pitch, that's all I want to do is win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until New York beat Cincinnati 5-0 in the wild card playoff game  
Monday night, the Diamondbacks didn't know whether they'd be facing 
the Mets or Houston. Arizona won seven of nine against New York, 
but Diamondbacks manager Buck Showalter downplayed the 
regular-season record. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're as talented a club as there is in our league,''  
Showalter said. ``They've got great depth. It's a well put-together 
club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson pitched against the Mets once, a 10-1 victory that  
capped a three-game sweep in New York May 30, part of a slump that 
led to the firing of three of manager Bobby Valentine's coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson is 2-5 in postseason play with a 3.10 ERA. Last year,  
when he was traded to Houston from Seattle in midseason, he was 
looked upon as the pennant-clincher for the Astros. 
</P>
<P>
	But he was 0-2 against San Diego in the first round. In the  
series opener, he gave up two runs in eight innings but lost 2-1 to 
the Padres' Kevin Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot is riding on that first game,'' Johnson said. ``I can  
only go out and pitch as good as I can pitch. I've lost some close 
games. I feel I pitched extremely well last year in Game 1 and we 
lost. Did I choke? I don't think I did. I tip my hat to Kevin 
Brown. He pitched better than I did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One more loss would give Johnson sole possession of a postseason  
record he surely doesn't want. Right now, his five straight losses 
ties the mark set by Joe Bush from 1914-23 and tied by Doyle 
Alexander from 1972-87. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson is as ready as he could be to try to end that streak. He  
is coming off a season in which he struck out a career-best 364, 
fourth-most in baseball history. He pitched a career-high 271 2-3 
innings and led the NL with a 2.48 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel I'm coming off the best year of my career and I want to  
take that into the postseason and be extremely focused,'' Johnson 
said. ``Much like the regular season, I'll lay it all on the 
line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter remembers Johnson's playoff successes well. With  
Seattle, Johnson beat Showalter's New York Yankees twice, once as a 
starter and once as a reliever, in the first round of the 1995 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot better having him on your side,'' Showalter said,  
``but it's not a prerequisite for success. Randy has been a losing 
pitcher sometimes this year, and just about all of them 
undeservingly. This time of year you're facing some real good 
competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks have to avoid the kind of offensive slumps that  
often have plagued them with Johnson on the mound. In one 
incredible four-game stretch when Johnson was at his best, Arizona 
failed to score a single run. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're going to win this series, we're going to have to get  
guys in from third base with less than two outs,'' Matt Williams 
said. ``We're going to have to limit our mistakes as much as we 
can, take advantage of the mistakes the other team makes and we're 
going to have to pitch well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter said Monday that Brian Anderson would start Game 4  
Saturday. Anderson (8-2) was 6-0 in his last nine starts and got 
the nod over Andy Benes (13-12), who will be a long reliever in the 
bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been pitching real well. I think he's earned that,''  
Showalter said. ``We think he gives us the best opportunity right 
now to win a baseball game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, Johnson and Omar Daal -- who starts Game 3 Wednesday,  
gives Arizona three leftys in its four-man playoff rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Left off the roster was Armando Reynoso (10-6), who started 27  
games this season but had been hit hard over the past month. 
</P>
<P>
	Damian Miller, who shares starting catching duties with Kelly  
Stinnett but has a hairline fracture in his right wrist, was added 
to the roster after he showed no ill effects from a workout on 
Sunday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
