<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Overall Auto Sales Up, Ford Slides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Consumers snapped up cars, trucks, minivans and  
sport utility vehicles at a blistering pace last month, pushing the 
auto industry one step closer to a record year for sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers sold about 1.4 million cars and light trucks in the  
United States last month, an increase of about 9.5 percent over 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	With a good economy and high customer rebates, industry analysts  
expect 1999 to easily break the record for yearly sales of 16.1 
million set in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor Co. was the exception; Ford sales were off 2 percent  
last month. The No. 2 automaker said Monday that sales of its Ford, 
Lincoln and Mercury cars were down 5 percent, mostly because of 
fewer sales to rental and business fleets. 
</P>
<P>
	Only three car models -- the Ford Mustang, the Ford Crown  
Victoria and the Mercury Grand Marquis -- posted year-to-year sales 
increases. While the Lincoln LS sedan and Navigator sport utility 
vehicle sold well, other Lincoln models had steep declines, leading 
to a 6.5 percent drop for the brand. 
</P>
<P>
	Trucks sales were off less than 1 percent, a decline the company  
said was due in part to switching some production from Ranger 
pickups to new models of the Ford Explorer sport utility vehicle. 
For the year, Ford's sales are up 5 percent, excluding Jaguar and 
Volvo. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Richard Hilgert of Fahnestock &AMP; Co. said Ford also  
picked up several truck buyers in 1998 who might have otherwise 
bought from General Motors Corp. At the time, GM was still 
recovering from a strike that shut down most production, and was 
beginning production on new truck models. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilgert also said there was a good reason behind Ford's decline  
in car sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``The overall mix of what was sold will be beneficial,'' he  
said. ``When you reduce fleet sales, you increase the share of 
profitable retail customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the month, Ford, GM and DaimlerChrysler saw sales increase 4  
percent. GM said its sales were up 8.5 percent, with a 30 percent 
gain in light truck sales offsetting a 7 percent decline in 
passenger cars. DaimlerChrysler AG said sales at its Chrysler 
division were up 7 percent, with a 5 percent gain in cars and an 
8.5 percent gain in trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	It was an even better September for foreign makes: Asian  
automakers were up 20 percent, and European brands were up 36 
percent. BMW said Monday its sales set new highs for the month and 
year so far, up 20 percent for September and 19 percent for the 
year. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
