<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High Court Looks at Campaign Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a campaign-finance dispute of potentially  
enormous importance for the 2000 elections and beyond, the Supreme 
Court is taking a new look at the strict limits imposed after the 
Watergate scandal on contributions in federal elections. 
</P>
<P>
	After hearing arguments today, the justices must decide the  
constitutionality of Missouri's contribution limits for its state 
races. Lurking in the background is what the court might say about 
limits in other states and in federal campaigns. A ruling is 
expected by late June. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Missouri limits were struck down as free-speech  
violations, the court's decision -- if grounded in the 
Constitution's First Amendment -- likely would affect campaign 
finance outside Missouri as well. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision that significantly altered campaign-finance law by  
striking down or vastly increasing the limits conceivably could 
cause serious confusion for the 2000 election campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	In a landmark 1976 decision, in a case called Buckley vs. Valeo,  
the court said free-speech rights trump any attempt to limit an 
individual candidate's spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But that decision drew a distinction between expenditures, which  
cannot be capped, and contributions, for which it upheld a $1,000 
limit for federal elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The court back then was ruling on a federal law enacted after  
the Watergate scandal of the early 1970s. At issue in the Missouri 
case is a 1994 law that imposed the same $1,000 limits on 
contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been unclear since the court granted review to an appeal  
filed by Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon last January just what 
the justices want to focus on. They chose not to tackle a related 
case that challenged the 1976 decision more directly. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court struck down Missouri's restrictions last  
year, ruling that limits that might have made sense in 1976 have 
been too eroded by inflation to withstand a new challenge. The 8th 
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals also said Missouri had not proved 
larger donations had corrupted state elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The Missouri limits had been adjusted to $1,075 but the appeals  
court's ruling left the state with no limits on contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices have received plenty of unsolicited advice from  
friend-of-the-court briefs urging a broad range of action, from 
striking down all contribution limits to imposing new strict limits 
on spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the court has come under growing criticism in scholarly  
journals for ever equating campaign spending with political speech. 
</P>
<P>
	James Bopp, representing a coalition of conservative groups such  
as the National Right to Life PAC and the National Rifle 
Association Political Victory Fund, called for removing all 
contribution limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri officials must prove ``that corruption exists or that  
the electorate has a reasonable perception of ... corruption,'' 
Bopp said. ``They can do neither.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the other end of the spectrum, Derek Cressman of the U.S.  
Public Interest Research Group said, ``It's time for the court to 
reconsider Buckley and recognize that the First Amendment was not 
intended to give a few fat cats the right to drown out the voices 
of ordinary Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Nixon vs. Shrink Missouri Government PAC, 98-963.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
