<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Suggests His Own Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VISTA, Calif. (AP) -- A drifter who murdered a third-grade boy in  
a beach restroom told jurors Monday he would kill again if given 
the chance and recommended they sentence him to death. 
</P>
<P>
	``My whole purpose in life is to help destroy your society,''  
Brandon H. Wilson told the jury. The 21-year old man spoke against 
the advice of his lawyer as jurors decide between life in prison 
without parole and execution. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthew Cecchi was killed on Nov. 14 during a family reunion at  
Oceanside Harbor. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson admitted he crept up behind the 9-year-old boy in the  
restroom, slashed his throat and stabbed him five times in the 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	In a calm, deliberate voice, Wilson told jurors he felt no  
remorse. ``I would do it again in a second if I had the chance,'' 
he said as the boy's mother, Sharon Cecchi, gasped from her 
front-row courtroom seat. ``Execute me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defense had argued that Wilson, from St. Croix Falls, Wis.,  
is a delusional manic-depressive who believed God chose him as ``an 
agent for destruction of mankind.'' Wilson said he was inspired to 
act after using LSD. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecution cited Wilson's videotaped confession two days  
after the slaying in which he made no mention of hearing God but 
said he killed for the thrill of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors deliberated less than six hours last week before  
rejecting Wilson's insanity claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday, the jury also heard tearful recollections of the boy by  
his mother, an uncle and the boy's teacher. Matthew wanted to be an 
engineer, cartoonist or architect, liked to play baseball and ride 
his bike, and wrote stories about aliens, his mother said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two jurors cried when teacher Deborah Peck described trying to  
explain the boy's death to his classmates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Third-graders always ask why and that was a question I had no  
answer for,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
