<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russians, Chechens Clash in Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian soldiers and Chechen fighters  
clashed in one village, and several Chechen towns were hit by 
airstrikes and artillery fire as the conflict spread deeper into 
the rebellious territory, military officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian forces entered Chechnya last week and have been  
advancing into the renegade republic to establish a security zone. 
At least four regions in eastern Chechnya were hit by rocket fire 
and two regions in central Chechnya were bombed over the past 24 
hours, the territory's deputy prime minister, Kazbek Makhashev, 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will destroy militants with all means at our disposal,''  
said Lt. Gen. Gennady Troshev, a senior Russian commander in the 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	In a clash Sunday in the northeastern village of Dubovskaya, two  
Russian soldiers were killed and eight were wounded, Russian 
officials said. The Chechens also claimed to have captured three 
Russian soldiers, Chechen military sources told the Interfax news 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Russian troop strength building, the Chechen fighters  
have been fortifying strongholds in an attempt to hold back the 
Russians, who have much greater fire power. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia says its aim is to establish a security cordon along the  
borders of Chechnya, though the military buildup has raised fears 
that there could be a repeat of the 1994-96 war in Chechnya that 
left tens of thousands dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chechnya will not give up a single square meter of land,''  
Chechnya's President Aslan Maskhadov told a news conference Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Maskhadov, who has been unable to restore order to Chechnya  
since winning election as president in 1997, said the Russian 
military action made it virtually impossible to disarm militants. 
</P>
<P>
	``When an ax hangs over Chechnya, I cannot disarm people,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian military claims it is targeting only suspected  
guerrilla bases and support facilities. But Maskhadov said more 
than 400 civilians have been killed and more than 1,000 have been 
injured in the air raids. He also said the territory's feeble 
economy has been further damaged, with hospitals, brick plants, oil 
refineries and an oil pipeline all hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians have moved into Chechnya with caution, unlike five  
years ago, when they stormed into the territory in an attempt to 
crush the Chechen separatists. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians have taken up positions outside two villages in  
eastern Chechnya, and are negotiating with village elders, said 
military spokesman Lt. Col. Andre Matveenko. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chechen elders are trying to prevent an attack on the  
villages, Kargalinskaya and Borozdonovskaya, but the Russians want 
all suspected rebels to surrender and then they plan to make a 
house-to-house search. 
</P>
<P>
	Refugees continued to stream out of Chechnya, with the total  
approaching 100,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin today announced the  
establishment of a government commission to deal with the refugee 
problem. Putin made the announcement after meeting with President 
Boris Yeltsin in the Kremlin, but gave no details. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Chechen refugees headed west, overwhelming the  
impoverished republic of Ingushetia, which had only 300,000 
residents prior to the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees and other international  
aid groups have been pitching in to provide food and shelter for 
the refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia began its raids on Chechnya after Muslim militants  
invaded neighboring Dagestan in August and September, seeking to 
create an Islamic state in southern Russia. The militants have also 
been blamed for bombings in Russia last month that killed about 300 
people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
