<DOCNO> APW19991004.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 08:04:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Radio City Restoration Complete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- All that glitters is gold again at Radio City  
Music Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	From its 3,000-pound gold silk curtain and scalloped sunburst  
ceiling to Depression-era artwork that has been hidden for decades 
under layers of grit and grime, the New York landmark visited by 
millions each year has been restored to its former Art Deco 
grandeur. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sparkling jewel once again,'' said Bob Russo, chairman  
of the restoration committee and general manager of Madison Square 
Garden, whose parent company Cablevision has a 25-year lease on the 
building and owns Radio City Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	The $70 million, seven-month restoration project was to be  
unveiled tonight at a benefit for the Lustgarten Foundation for 
Pancreatic Cancer. The event, which was to feature Billy Crystal, 
Ann-Margret, Sting, Tony Bennett, Ann Miller and Raquel Welch, will 
be aired on NBC on Dec. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first major renovation of the building since it opened  
Dec. 27, 1932. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers replaced all six miles of the faded neon lights on the  
hall's famous marquee, rewired 1,500 chandeliers and re-insulated 
walls to improve the acoustics. All 5,901 seats were reupholstered. 
</P>
<P>
	Once considered the largest indoor theater and most modern  
structure of its time, the hall aged badly. Burnt out ceiling 
lights went unchanged, antiques were placed in storage rather than 
repaired, carpets and seats became shabby. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1970s, the once grand lady of performance halls -- in debt  
and losing audiences with its tired formula of family movies and a 
stage show -- was nearly demolished. Saved by the wrecking ball 
after the city declared it an architectural landmark in 1979, a new 
management team was brought in and the hall slowly rebounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, nearly 2 million people visited Radio City.  
</P>
<P>
	The most Herculean effort in the restoration came in restoring  
the hall's artwork, which includes the 60-by-40 foot ``Fountain of 
Youth'' mural painted by Ezra Winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, Russo said, the work got darker as layers of  
smoke and grime built up. It was made worse when someone decided to 
coat the artwork with polyurethane, sealing in the dirt and turning 
the painting yellow. 
</P>
<P>
	Art experts, using Q-tips, tiny scalpels and cotton squares  
restored the mural that graces the staircase leading to the 
mezzanine. 
</P>
<P>
	Eileen Collins, dance captain of the hall's signature Rockettes,  
said the sight of the restored theater moved her to tears. ``When I 
saw the theater, I felt like crying; especially when I thought of 
what almost was.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 17:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rider a No-Show for Hawks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Isaiah Rider got off to shaky start with his new  
team Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rider added to his extensive resume of malfeasance when he  
failed to show up for a mandatory media gathering with the Atlanta 
Hawks, casting doubt on whether he would be on time for the first 
practice of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed but I'm not surprised,'' said Hawks general  
manager Pete Babcock, who knew he was taking a serious risk when he 
traded Steve Smith to Portland as part of a four-player deal that 
included Rider. 
</P>
<P>
	Babcock spent the weekend trying to track down Rider, who lives  
in Oakland, Calif. Finally, about 2 p.m. Monday, someone from agent 
Arn Tellem's office called to say Rider had missed a couple of 
flights and would attempt to catch one in the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	``We went into this with our eyes wide open,'' Babcock said.  
``He has a track record of these sort of things happening. We hope 
by the end of the season they will happening less frequently or not 
at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rider will be fined, but Babcock wouldn't reveal the amount. The  
player was expected to miss a team dinner Monday night and the 
two-hour bus ride to Chattanooga, Tenn., where training camp begins 
with a Tuesday morning practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is unacceptable, but I'm not making a bigger issue or a  
smaller issue out of it than I would with any other player,'' 
Babcock said. ``He'll suffer the consequences for his actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tellem's office said Monday he was traveling and unavailable.  
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old Rider has averaged 18 points per game during his  
six-year career, showing the ability to dominate at the offensive 
end and thrive in an up-tempo offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks decided he was just the kind of player they needed to  
improve their speed, quickness and creativity after ranking as the 
second worst offensive team in the NBA last season. 
</P>
<P>
	But the rest of the Rider's background provided serious cause  
for concern. He showed up late for his first pro practice with 
Minnesota in 1993 and has run afoul of either the law or the NBA 
every year since. 
</P>
<P>
	Rider has feuded with coaches. He has missed flights and  
practices. He has been suspended by the league and convicted in 
court of various offenses, including marijuana possession, assault 
and illegal possession of cellular phones. He even spent four days 
in jail for probation violation. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly before Babcock learned that Rider was not showing up,  
Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens talked optimistically about his 
relationship with the player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I concern myself with what happens from today on,'' Wilkens  
said. ``I'm not going to get caught up in last year or the year 
before. We had a talk and I told him what I expect and the 
parameters here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few minutes later, Wilkens learned that Rider already had run  
afoul of those parameters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have to wait and see,'' Wilkens said. ``I have no  
comment on this. I'm finding out at the same time you are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rider was acquired from the Blazers along with fellow shooting  
guard Jim Jackson, who did show up for the media gathering and 
plans to compete with his wayward teammate for a starting role. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know the circumstances,'' Jackson said. ``That's  
something J.R. (Rider's nickname) and management will have to work 
out. I'm here and I'm ready to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After getting swept by the New York Knicks in the second round  
of the playoffs, the Hawks underwent a major shakeup during the 
offseason. They could have as many as seven new players, which made 
Rider's absence even more disturbing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to say I'm disappointed,'' said guard Bimbo  
Coles, another new Hawk. ``The thing that worries me is we need to 
work on our chemistry and come together as a team. We need everyone 
here and he's a big part of our team.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
