<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockets Camp Full of New Faces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- With only six returning players, the Houston  
Rockets' training camp might seem more like a meet-and-greet than a 
catch-and-shoot. 
</P>
<P>
	After showing up for physicals Monday morning, the new group of  
Rockets made their debuts at media day in Houston, then departed 
for Austin, Texas. Camp starts there Tuesday, with two practices a 
day through Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week's trade of disgruntled forward Scottie Pippen to the  
Portland Trail Blazers for six players -- Stacey Augmon, Ed Gray, 
Walt Williams, Carlos Rogers, Kelvin Cato and Brian Shaw -- swelled 
the roster to 18 players with contracts plus Charles Barkley, who 
signed a one-year deal Monday. Terms were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Also joining the mix are offseason additions Shandon Anderson  
and Steve Francis. 
</P>
<P>
	While Shaw, Gray and veteran Eddie Johnson, who is expected to  
retire, were cut Monday, there are still 16 players left to compete 
for 12 roster spots -- most of whom haven't played together yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be very competitive training camp, which  
I think is healthy, but I don't want to get into just competing,'' 
coach Rudy Tomjanovich. ``There is a fine line of just competing 
and forgetting about what we're trying to accomplish. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have too many players, and we have to work on that.  
But we did the work of trying to put a team we like together and we 
are more than satisfied with what we have. Now it's time to get 
away, get secluded and get to know each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some players won't be around for long. Augmon and Rogers are  
long shots to make the team, while Thomas Hamilton, Matt Bullard, 
Don MacLean and Matt Maloney will have to fight for spots. 
</P>
<P>
	The main reason for moving camp to Austin is so the players will  
spend more time with each other and build chemistry, rather than 
going their own ways as they did when camp was held in the Houston 
area, Tomjanovich said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be for the best, because everybody will be  
learning something new. It's not going to happen overnight,'' 
rookie guard Francis said. ``It's going to take a long time for 
everybody to get to know each other's talents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tomjanovich will teach his players a retooled offense that still  
exploits the strength of Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon on the low 
post, while using some of the team's newly-acquired speed -- Francis 
and Anderson -- to work the outside and drive to the basket. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an advantage to have guys that can run and guys that can  
post up. Any team that can play both styles, that wins 
championships,'' said Olajuwon, who has won two. 
</P>
<P>
	Barkley was more succinct about the team's shift toward speed:  
``If we can't be uptempo this year, we're never going to be 
uptempo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA game in general should speed up anyway, thanks to a rule  
change inspired in part by Barkley's penchant for slowly backing 
his way to the basket. This season, a player can only back the ball 
in for five seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``They only thing the rule change did is now you're all going to  
remember me when I'm dead. Every time the referee blows the whistle 
on one of those plays, you'll all say `That's the Barkley rule,''' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomjanovich also said he is looking forward to experimenting  
with Williams and Cato, each of whom offers specific talents. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams had the fourth-best shooting percentage (43) in the NBA  
last season from 3-point range. Though Cato is considered a 
long-term project, the Rockets envision him as a backup for 
Olajuwon this year and a possible successor later. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing with Charles and playing with Hakeem is going to be  
great,'' Cato said. ``My main thing is hoping they like me as much 
as I idolized them as I grew up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for eventually replacing Olajuwon, Cato said, ``We'll get to  
that when we get to that. He's still got three or four more good 
years.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
