<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Back To School in Flood Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRINCEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- It is another landmark in North  
Carolina's long, painful attempt to return to normal after 
Hurricane Floyd: Schools are opening their doors again. 
</P>
<P>
	Volunteers worked through the weekend to get classrooms in  
hard-hit Edgecombe County ready for this morning. Floyd's 
floodwaters damaged many schools and destroyed two, including one 
in Princeville. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want the schools to be shining like a new dime. These kids  
have gone through a lot and we want them coming in knowing that 
everything is OK and that the world is still going around,'' county 
spokeswoman Diane LeFiles said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 550 children will attend other schools for the next week  
or so while temporary trailers are readied. County schools were 
closed Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tarboro, fewer than 200 people were left at the shelter at  
Tarboro High School, which also was readied for students today. It 
is the only shelter still open in the region east of Raleigh. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the cleanup resumed Sunday for residents flooded out  
of their homes nearly three weeks ago in Princeville, which was 
engulfed by the Tar River on Sept. 17. At one point, brown, 
swirling water stood 20 feet deep near the town hall. The water 
destroyed half of the town's 800 homes and wiped out 33 businesses 
and three churches. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearby, the Tar River crested Sunday about 8 feet above flood  
stage after a second round of heavy rains. 
</P>
<P>
	Only in the past few days have the town's 1,900 residents been  
able to return to view the damage. There is uncertainty about the 
future of a town built by freed slaves after the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's going to happen in Princeville? What is going to happen  
in Princeville?'' asked Dennis Westry, peering into the windows of 
his sister's house. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel in the next 18 months there will be a lot of changes.  
It really depends on how much money is coming in,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Princeville resident Jacquetta Hawkins picked through piles of  
clothes in her grandmother's house, most stained with mud and rust 
from metal hangers. She tossed most of the items onto the growing 
pile of trash, alongside ruined dressers, wallboard and mattresses. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hawkins held up a tiny outfit that had been on a plastic  
hanger. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh this one's really cute,'' she said. ``Maybe we can clean it  
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the damage, Samuel Wilkins remained positive Sunday as  
he stopped by to check on his mother's house. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to see the whole town come back,'' he said. ``I  
really hope they don't do away with this little town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a mall in Greenville was turned into a makeshift  
television studio Sunday as broadcasters aired a statewide 
telethon. The six-hour effort raised $2.2 million in promised 
donations for flood victims, said Mike Weeks, president of the 
North Carolina Association of Broadcasters. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
