<DOCNO> APW19991004.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 12:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AMD Unveils 700 Megahertz Chip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) -- Advanced Micro Devices Inc. has  
unveiled an even speedier version of its new Athlon computer chip 
in a bid to stay one step ahead of archrival and industry leader 
Intel Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	AMD said its 700 megahertz chip will operate a computer far  
better than Intel's most advanced chip on the market, the 600 
megahertz chip Intel offers for its Pentium III. 
</P>
<P>
	The chips, which are typically sold in 1,000-unit batches to  
computer makers, will sell for $849 each. AMD said IBM and Compaq 
Computer Corp. already had committed to selling the new Athlon chip 
in its speediest computers, while retailer Best Buy said it would 
immediately offer the chip through its made-to-order 
computer-selling program. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some analysts say AMD is unlikely to overtake Intel  
because that larger company typically responds to new challenges by 
slashing the prices of its older chips to spur sales. AMD in the 
past also has had production problems. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
