<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Urged To Pass FAA Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airport delays could turn into gridlock if  
Congress does not move quickly to overhaul air traffic control 
systems, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater says. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could see this system come to a chokepoint,'' Slater said  
of the rapidly expanding airline industry that in a decade is 
expected to carry 1 billion passengers a year, up 50 percent from 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate began debate Monday on long-stalled legislation to  
fund Federal Aviation Administration modernization, safety and 
operating programs. Slater and FAA Administrator Jane Garvey were 
on Capitol Hill to lobby for language in the bill that would make 
the air traffic control system operate more like a business. 
</P>
<P>
	Garvey said the Senate had made a good starting point with an  
amendment proposed by Sens. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and John D. 
Rockefeller, D-W.Va., that would create a chief operating officer 
post and an oversight board for the system. 
</P>
<P>
	Garvey and Slater said the administration ultimately wants to  
change financing so that all air traffic control revenues are used 
for the system. Also being considered is replacement of the current 
excise tax on passengers with user fees paid by airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate FAA bill, which would fund some $45 billion in  
programs over four years, is expected to have widespread support, 
as did a five-year, $59 billion measure the House passed in June. 
</P>
<P>
	But a similar Senate bill that passed last year by 92-1 never  
became law because the House and Senate could not iron out 
differences, particularly over the issue of increasing flights out 
of some of the nation's busiest airports. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Commerce Committee Chairman John McCain, R-Ariz., has  
pushed hard for lifting the ceilings on flights out of Chicago's 
O'Hare, New York's LaGuardia and Kennedy and Washington's Reagan 
National. He contends this is one way to increase competition and 
improve service to smaller communities that have suffered under 
airline deregulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Gorton-Rockefeller amendment would eliminate slot rules  
at O'Hare in 2003 and at the New York airports in 2007, with new 
slots -- a takeoff or landing -- going to new entrants or services to 
smaller communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington would get 24 new slots, 12 for service outside a  
1,250-mile ``perimeter rule'' established in 1986 to protect Dulles 
and Baltimore-Washington, the region's two long-haul airports. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from the three regions have launched strenuous  
campaigns against the flight increases, saying they pose 
environmental and safety problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Freshman Sen. Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., said he was elected in  
part because of his opposition to additional flights out of O'Hare. 
More flights into congested airports would be ``a grave mistake 
that could jeopardize the safety of our flying public in the United 
States,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A final compromise on the legislation has also been slowed by  
provisions in the House bill, championed by House Transportation 
Committee Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., that would bar Congress from 
using funds from the Aviation Trust Fund for non-aviation purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The trust fund, which takes in about $10 billion a year in  
airport user taxes, is now used for general budget programs as well 
as airport projects. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
