<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Payton Talks of Upcoming Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- All-Star point guard Gary Payton has the Seattle  
SuperSonics season figured out. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no pressure, since everyone ranks the Sonics near the  
bottom of their division. 
</P>
<P>
	Power forward Vin Baker, disgraced last year as Seattle ended  
the season 25-25 and missed the playoffs, is the go-to man. ``I'm 
not worried about Vin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton, guard Vernon Maxwell and others will bring ``attitude''  
back to the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can win, off of attitude, 35-40 games,'' Payton told  
reporters on Monday at the team's media day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics will make the playoffs.  
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, we're going to be in the playoffs so I'm not worried  
about that,'' Payton declared. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonics' training camp opens Tuesday, with the preseason opener  
against the Portland Trail Blazers on Oct. 12 and the season opener 
Nov. 2 against the Los Angeles Clippers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics are eager to put the lockout-shortened 1999 season  
behind them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a relief,'' to start again, said Baker, who began last  
season out of shape and missed much of it due to injuries. Despite 
all that, the Sonics re-signed him in August to a seven-year, $87 
million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had to live with last year all summer long, and finally  
I'm getting my opportunity to get back on track,'' the four-time 
All-Star said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to show everyone (last year) was an aberration and  
I'm going to be back on top.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't relate anything to last year, other than we learned  
some things that we needed to rectify,'' general manager Wally 
Walker said. ``We got older and slower and we couldn't compete well 
enough with the athletic teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Management gave the team a major makeover in the offseason,  
bringing back only Payton and Baker among their top players. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker said he expected this year's team to pick up the tempo.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've got a good mix; a versatile group and a bunch of  
guys who complement one another. But the fact is you never know 
until you get going,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Pacific Division and the Western Conference are both  
filled with good teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anyone in our conference that has an off-night is going to be  
in big trouble,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Paul Westphal said he was looking forward to ``have the  
season start with a normal NBA,'' with time to prepare and a full 
season of 82 games. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he doesn't have his starters set, except for Baker,  
Payton and forward Horace Grant, who was acquired from Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	Payton said he liked the position of underdog.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can't put a halo over people and say we expect to win 60  
games,'' he said. ``These guys got to get the feel. I like these 
guys. I think these guys got a lot of attitude to them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said there might be personality clashes but ``as long as we  
be a family on this court and win basketball games, that's what I'm 
happy about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton, who carried the team last season, also said he wants  
that to change. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to come and play every night, that's all I'm going  
to do,'' he said. ``I'm not a shooter. Vin is going to be the 
man.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
