<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wannstedt Easing Into Coach Roles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- He's the Dolphins assistant head coach, but Dave  
Wannstedt might better be labeled as Mr. Everything. 
</P>
<P>
	During a typical day -- sometimes a typical hour -- Wannstedt  
roams from meeting room to meeting room, practice field to practice 
field, offense to defense, even working with the special teams. 
</P>
<P>
	His is a job that lacks definition. He helps out wherever Jimmy  
Johnson, his longtime friend, needs him. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first two games, Wannstedt sat in the coaches' box for  
the first half, evaluating the game plan he helped install. Then he 
spent the second half on the sideline, working with the players. 
</P>
<P>
	Wannstedt says the transition has been easy.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a lot smoother than what I imagined or what anybody  
would have imagined,'' Wannstedt said. ``The situation was unique 
because, since Jimmy's been with the Dolphins, we would talk 
weekly, so I really felt like I had a feel for the organization. I 
felt like I had a good handle on the team, its strengths and 
weaknesses, and where we had to get better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson hired Wannstedt in January after quitting, then coming  
back to the Dolphins in the span of 24 hours, when his mother died 
and the strain of an emotional season had taken its toll. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga asked Johnson what it would take  
for him to stay, and Johnson suggested hiring Wannstedt to relieve 
some of his burden as coach and general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Wannstedt had been fired by the Chicago Bears following a 4-12  
finish in 1998. Wannstedt and Johnson, who coached together for 13 
years prior to this season, were reunited for the first time since 
1992, when they won a Super Bowl with the Dallas Cowboys. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't develop relationships like this from reading about  
them in a book or by watching a videotape on it,'' Wannstedt said. 
``There's been a lot of blood, sweat and tears that have gone into 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The duo coached through probation years at Oklahoma State and  
through undefeated and championship seasons at the University of 
Miami. They moved to the NFL and went from 1-15 to the Super Bowl 
three years later. 
</P>
<P>
	The success led to Wannstedt getting the Bears' job. It's all  
but assumed he'll get the same chance with the Dolphins once 
Johnson steps aside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think when you face adversity in any relationship, people  
have a tendency to drift apart or strengthen,'' Wannstedt said. 
``For whatever reason, I don't know why, ours has remained in tact 
and strengthened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To hear players tell it, Wannstedt's presence has solidified the  
Dolphins, as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always thought that one of Dave's biggest gifts is  
teaching,'' said defensive end Trace Armstrong, whom played for 
Wannstedt in Chicago. ``He relates well to players one-on-one. A 
lot of coaches can tell you where to line up or tell you what you 
did wrong. But the very good coaches are able to teach the position 
or teach a technique and get a guy to understand it and I think 
that's Dave's strong suit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wannstedt concedes he tends to work more with the defense, but  
that should be expected -- he primarily has spent his entire career 
as either a defensive coordinator or a defensive line coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where he's comfortable,'' linebacker Robert Jones said.  
``You can never have too many guys, especially when you have one 
with the knowledge that Coach Wannstedt has. That's a plus for us 
all the way around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a plus for Johnson, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``Dave's still going in a lot of different areas, and he's  
really making an outstanding contribution,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The full weight of the contribution might not truly be known  
until January. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 20:36:37 </DATE_TIME>
