<DOCNO> APW19991004.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 23:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Web Privacy Protection Big Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Companies are producing new software and new  
technologies at an unprecedented rate to protect the privacy of 
consumers on the Internet, but profits remain elusive. 
</P>
<P>
	These new tools help people online preserve their anonymity,  
keep credit-card numbers safe and warn them about Web sites that 
may sell their personal secrets to others. 
</P>
<P>
	Novell Inc., the $1 billion computer networking giant, planned  
to introduce its latest Web privacy tool, called ``Digital Me,'' at 
an Internet trade show in New York today. 
</P>
<P>
	A Novell executive, Mike Sheridan, told Congress this year that  
the technology will let consumers cloak themselves behind different 
profiles to control what information Internet sites collect. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Enonymous Inc. released its clever, free software  
program, which warns consumers about each Web site's privacy 
promises whenever they're asked to surrender their name, e-mail 
address and other personal information. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, a small Internet startup based in San Diego, said  
it reviewed and rated the privacy guarantees of the 10,000 most 
popular Web sites, including those by Amazon.com Inc., America 
Online Inc. and Microsoft Corp. The tool means consumers won't need 
to study the fine print on promises, which can be hard to find and 
filled with legal jargon. 
</P>
<P>
	``For consumers who don't want to go through and read a privacy  
statement, this is a really great thing for them,'' said Michelle 
Slack, an analyst for Jupiter Communications, a New York research 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The software displays warnings for those sites with weak  
guarantees. Enonymous promised to update its ratings regularly and 
review new policies at Web sites other than the top 10,000 where 
its customers spend time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to be adversarial with Web sites,'' said David  
Taylor, the company's chief executive officer. ``We want them to 
realize it's good for business to have a good privacy policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers and federal regulators have so far resisted calls for  
new national privacy laws protecting Internet users. They say these 
new products -- with names like Anonymizer, Privacy Bank, Freedom 
and Privaseek's Persona -- are laudable responses to consumer fears 
about shopping on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	A survey this year by the Pew Research Center for the People and  
the Press found that 54 percent of people expressed some anxiety 
about computers and technology being used to invade their privacy. 
Women and the elderly worried most. 
</P>
<P>
	But profits, or the lack thereof, remain the main hurdle for  
companies selling privacy products. Many Web sites earn money 
selling targeted advertising or information about its customers 
from lists of visitors -- the same behaviors that privacy tools try 
to prevent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's astonishingly difficult to make money out of privacy,''  
said Jason Catlett of Junkbusters Corp., a New Jersey-based privacy 
advocate. He cited ``an enormous economic incentive to extract 
information rather than protect it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People don't want to pay for privacy,'' Catlett said. ``It's  
like paying for clean air or clean drinking water.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If they were making money, something would probably be  
wrong,'' joked Marc Rotenberg of the Washington-based Electronic 
Privacy Information Center. ``It will be interesting to see how 
these firms focusing on privacy are making it work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Enonymous said it plans to earn money acting as an  
``infomediary,'' a growing category of companies that shield the 
identities of their customers but pass to marketing companies and 
Web sites the demographic information its customers choose to 
volunteer. 
</P>
<P>
	Those companies can then relay ads and information to specific  
types of consumers -- based on age, gender or interests -- without 
knowing their real-world identities because Enonymous acts as a 
trusted go-between. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at privacy specifically, nobody's made any money  
yet,'' allowed Abner Germanow, an Internet analyst for 
International Data Corp. ``Nobody's made tens of millions or 
hundreds of millions. But if you look at how Enonymous is planning 
on making its money, there are lots of very profitable companies 
that do similar things.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 20:44:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Said Plotting Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbia's opposition, which is  
seeking the ouster of Slobodan Milosevic, said Monday the Yugoslav 
president's government was willing to provoke bloodshed to stay in 
power. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition leader Vuk Draskovic, meanwhile, said a traffic  
collision Sunday that injured him and killed four others was ``an 
obvious assassination attempt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Let those who did this think hard about what will happen to  
them,'' Draskovic told the private Studio B TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Draskovic was traveling in a convoy of three cars when a truck  
swerved, hitting two cars in the convoy and causing one of them to 
explode. Draskovic's car went off the road, and he suffered 
scratches and bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver reportedly fled the scene of the accident, 25 miles  
southwest of Belgrade, the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a clear sign that the regime is afraid of Draskovic,''  
said his associate, Borivoje Borovic. He said police were holding a 
suspect who might be the truck driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Government and police officials could not be reached for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alliance for Change, a rival group to Draskovic's Serbian  
Renewal Movement, said Milosevic's neo-communist allies were trying 
to provoke violence during protests to trigger a state of 
emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	But a state of emergency would not ``stop the people's  
rebellion'' in Serbia, said Vladan Batic, the alliance's spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Monday, tens of thousands of Serbs took part in  
anti-Milosevic protests throughout Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Belgrade, riot police prevented several thousand opposition  
supporters from marching toward the Serb Orthodox Church 
headquarters. Chanting ``Red Bandits,'' the angry demonstrators 
turned back and marched in central Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	In the eastern Serbian town of Bor, the local branch of  
Draskovic's party joined the demonstrations. Draskovic and his 
party previously had refused to take part, saying demonstrations 
could lead to civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	Tens of thousands have protested throughout Serbia since Sept.  
21, blaming Milosevic for the country's deep economic and social 
crises. 
</P>
<P>
	Batic said he ``wouldn't rule out'' that Milosevic's regime had  
tried to assassinate Draskovic. 
</P>
<P>
	Draskovic's close aide and brother-in-law, Veselin Boskovic, was  
killed, along with chief security adviser Zvonko Osmajlic and two 
bodyguards. 
</P>
<P>
	Draskovic appeared Monday at a commemoration ceremony in the  
Belgrade City Hall. Tearful, he asked Belgraders to attend funerals 
on Tuesday and Wednesday for his four associates. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to rumors that police were targeting Draskovic, his party  
said an official who recently left Milosevic's ranks was 
``kidnapped'' last week. The official, who had worked for the 
secret police, had started working recently for Boskovic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Parallel with beating up citizens who are peacefully  
protesting against the regime, the police are starting an even more 
sinister phase of spreading fear,'' the statement said. ``We think 
people will begin to disappear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, police arrested four opposition activists in central  
Serbia on Monday, and ordered an opposition leader to appear in 
court on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vuk Obradovic was summoned after Milosevic's top aid, Deputy  
Premier Milovan Bojic, filed a lawsuit accusing Obradovic of 
ridiculing him during a rally. 
</P>
<P>
	A defiant Obradovic declared during Monday's rally that the  
regime was ``in paranoid fear.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
