<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Consumer Is Rare Breed / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The American consumer is a rare economic  
species, one worth studying and perhaps emulating by Third World 
countries as the global economy continues to develop. 
</P>
<P>
	Confidence, optimism and ambition are among America's most  
obvious characteristics. Somehow, things get better in America 
because people think they'll get better and then do something about 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	The late Professor George Katona, an immigrant who pioneered the  
study of consumers at the University of Michigan, once remarked 
that confidence and optimism differentiated Americans from 
Europeans. 
</P>
<P>
	It was three decades ago when he made the observation in an  
interview. American-style optimism has obviously spread more 
broadly since then, but the U.S. consumer still retains unique 
traits. 
</P>
<P>
	That much was confirmed by the results of two surveys released  
this week, one from the Michigan university where Katona began his 
inquiries, the other from The Conference Board and others. 
</P>
<P>
	First the Michigan survey, directed by Richard T. Curtin, who  
continues the work begun by Katona. It begins: 
</P>
<P>
	``Confidence rose in September despite the recent hikes in  
interest rates and the widely held view among consumers that 
additional rate increases will occur during the year ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consider the environment that preceded the rise in confidence:  
</P>
<P>
	Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, had his hand on  
the trigger, ready to raise interest rates again. The stock market 
was terrorized about the threat of inflation. Economists warned 
that the near-record expansion was getting weary from age. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps even more pertinent, the same economists were expressing  
the view that the jobless rate, at a 30-year low, was defying the 
economic gods, and that it or consumer prices would soon rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers stood firm. A record number judged the economy  
favorably and three-quarters of them expected the jobless rate to 
remain at its current low throughout the year ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	And, Curtin announced, ``the rise in interest rates had little  
impact on the near-record levels of favorable buying attitudes 
toward vehicles and other large purchases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Curtin: Even during the 1960s economic expansion, which  
still holds the longevity record, consumers began to lower 
expectations around the expansion's midpoint, nearly five years 
before it ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``In sharp contrast,'' he continued, ``rather than tempering  
their views after eight years of expansion, 1999 consumers became 
increasingly convinced the expansion would last another five 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody can say consumers are right or wrong; the future will  
answer that. In fact, when you consider that consumers continue to 
spend more than they earn, a mass hallucination may be at work. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, however, consumers have been right, the experts wrong.  
In some way, perhaps because they work to create their vision, they 
appear more erudite than those who pity them as irresponsible. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board survey examined the opinions of residents  
around the world on the subject of corporate social responsibility. 
Among other things, this is what the survey found: 
</P>
<P>
	Americans demand a broader role for companies. ``Only 11 percent  
think companies should only focus on making a profit, paying taxes, 
employing people and obeying all laws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What also should they focus on?  
</P>
<P>
	``Three times as many think they should also work to exceed  
lawful requirements, set higher ethical standards and help build a 
better society for all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That attitude is pronounced among Americans (and North  
Americans), several times more likely to be expressed by them than 
by people in Kazakhstan, China, Nigeria and India. 
</P>
<P>
	Extrapolating, U.S. consumers, regardless of their good fortune,  
aren't easily satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	They want more for and from themselves and their companies,  
expect more, believe they can get more and are confident that if 
they continue to work, and they intend to, their confidence will be 
rewarded. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 13:30:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hachette May Buy George Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hachette Filipacchi Magazines hopes to buy the  
Kennedy family's stake in George magazine, the political and 
lifestyle publication founded by John F. Kennedy Jr., who died in a 
July plane crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``No final agreement has been reached as yet but hopefully an  
agreement will be completed relatively soon,'' HFM spokesman Keith 
Estabrook said Monday. He declined to provide details about the 
discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview published Monday in The New York Times, the  
president and chief executive of Hachette Filipacchi Magazines, 
Jack Kliger, said Hachette planned to purchase the Kennedy family's 
stake in George over the next two weeks and invest $10 million in 
the magazine over the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Estabrook said Kliger was unavailable for comment. Calls to the  
Kennedy family were not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Hachette Filipacchi Magazines and the Kennedy family each own  
half of the magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	There had been concerns after Kennedy's death in a July 16  
airplane crash about whether the four-year-old magazine could 
survive without him. In addition to being its founder, Kennedy was 
the editor. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kliger told the Times he ``came to believe there was a  
product based on John's vision that could exist without John if we 
could find a way to continue its distinct voice, but also if we 
could fix business issues like marketing and pricing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Hachette announced it would cut George to 10 issues  
a year next year from 12 but would guarantee advertisers a larger 
circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	It also recently cut the yearly subscription price to $9.97 from  
$17.76. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting with the February 2000 issue, advertisers are being  
promised circulation of 450,000 per issue, up 12.5 percent from the 
current 400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The new circulation guarantee is higher than the nearly 405,153  
which the Audit Bureau of Circulations says George achieved in the 
first six months of this year. That was down 3.4 percent from 
419,214 a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Advertising pages have tumbled, falling 32 percent to 264 pages  
in the January-August period from 390 pages a year earlier, 
according to figures from Publishers Information Bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	Hachette publishes 28 consumer magazines including Car and  
Driver, Elle, Mirabella, Premiere and Woman's Day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 18:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clippers' Taylor Vows To Play Hard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Maurice Taylor promised Monday that the Los  
Angeles Clippers will get what they pay for, but said he definitely 
won't sign another contract with them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to be the same Maurice Taylor I was the first two  
seasons,'' the third-year forward said at the team's media day. 
``I'm just going to go out and play as hard as I can and do what I 
can to make the team win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For that, the Clippers are required to pay him $1.367 million  
this season. But Taylor, encouraged by agent David Falk, is seeking 
a six-year extension worth the NBA-maximum $70.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Clippers owner Donald T. Sterling refused to extend such an  
offer, leaving Taylor, who averaged a team-high 16.8 points with 
5.3 rebounds last season, as something of a lame-duck go-to-guy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There really wasn't any negotiation,'' Taylor said of  
Sterling's hard-line approach to the business of basketball. ``I 
don't think they showed me any loyalty. There's no way I'm going to 
re-sign here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clippers, who open training camp Tuesday at Los Angeles  
Southwest College, expect a big season from Taylor, even though 
Falk has vigorously encouraged a trade. 
</P>
<P>
	If Taylor isn't moved, the team could lose him without  
compensation next summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's hurting me or him,'' Taylor said in  
reference to Sterling's decision. ``It's business. But I do feel 
sorry for the fans. I love the fans in L.A. I love everything about 
L.A. I love my teammates, and I feel like the fans are really 
getting cheated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clippers coach Chris Ford said he doesn't think the team will  
receive anything less than Taylor's best effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a great statement that he came here in great  
shape,'' Ford, beginning his second season with the Clippers, said 
of Taylor. ``I fully expect him to have a big year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clippers' other marquee media attraction, rookie forward  
Lamar Odom, was philosophical about the possibility of playing with 
Taylor for only one season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm honored to be on the same team with Mo, but this is the  
real world,'' Odom said. ``I'm just looking forward to be a part of 
this organization and a part of this league. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been waiting my whole life for this opportunity.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
