<HEADLINE> 'Double Jeopardy' Tops Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Double Jeopardy'' held onto the top spot at  
North American theaters over the weekend, taking in $17.2 million 
and fending off three new movies, according to industry estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	The revenge drama starring Ashley Judd and Tommy Lee Jones has  
earned $47.4 million in two weeks and had only a 26 percent drop in 
ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Three Kings'' was No. 2, earning $16.3 million for the  
weekend. The Gulf War action thriller stars George Clooney, Ice 
Cube and Mark Wahlberg as American soldiers seeking a cache of 
Iraqi gold who get entangled with local rebels. Industry experts 
said it had the best chance of unseating ``Double Jeopardy,'' 
</P>
<P>
	``American Beauty'' the dark and funny depiction of suburban  
angst from Dreamworks, climbed to third place, earning $8.1 million 
despite showing in only 706 theaters. It averaged $11,473 per 
screen, by far the best among the top 10 films. 
</P>
<P>
	The film, starring Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening, explores  
issues ranging from infidelity to homophobia to mid-life crises. 
</P>
<P>
	Audiences seem to want hard-to-peg films with complicated  
themes, said film analyst Robert Bucksbaum of Reel Source Inc. 
``American Beauty'' fits that bill. Dreamworks' Jim Tharp said the 
studio is considering upping the number of theaters showing it to 
1,200 or 1,300 this week, based on the strong showing. 
</P>
<P>
	Other new films did middling business during the weekend.  
</P>
<P>
	Melissa Joan Hart's film debut, ``Drive Me Crazy,'' opened at  
No. 6, just below powerhouse supernatural thriller ``The Sixth 
Sense,'' in its ninth week. ``The Sixth Sense'' earned an estimated 
$7.2 million, and ``Crazy'' $7.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Muppet movie ``Elmo In Grouchland'' came in at No. 8 with  
$3.3 million, about what studio executives expected for a movie 
aimed at the under-10 set. And ``Mystery, Alaska,'' about a hopeful 
hockey team from the boondocks, started at No. 9 with $3.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucksbaum called the showing by ``The Sixth Sense'' phenomenal  
and said the top five films will probably stay around into the 
Christmas season. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North  
American theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc.: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Double Jeopardy,'' $17.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Three Kings,'' $16.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``American Beauty,'' $8.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Blue Streak,'' $8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``The Sixth Sense,'' $7.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Drive Me Crazy,'' $7.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``For Love of the Game,'' $3.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Elmo In Grouchland,'' $3.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Mystery, Alaska,'' $3.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``Stigmata,'' $2.3 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
