<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heinz Combining Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- H.J. Heinz Co. plans to combine its U.S. food,  
pet food and food-service businesses under the same division to 
improve distribution and attempt to gain increased bargaining power 
with retail chains. 
</P>
<P>
	The headquarters of the Star-Kist tuna and Heinz pet food brands  
will move from Newport, Ky. to Pittsburgh to the new Heinz Sales 
Co. 
</P>
<P>
	William Johnson, Heinz's chief executive officer, said at a news  
conference Monday that he expects 80 to 100 people to make the move 
from Newport, where Star-Kist employs 425. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 100 to 150 people will be hired for Heinz's new  
headquarters for U.S. operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will market flagship products such as  
ketchup, pickles, tuna and Ore-Ida potatoes alongside beans, Bagel 
Bites and Pounce Hairball Treatment for cats. Heinz also has a new 
line of frozen foods under the Boston Market name. 
</P>
<P>
	Heinz said it combined operations for faster distribution and  
development of new foods and to get bargaining power with grocery 
chains such as Albertson's, Super Valu and Kroger. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Star-Kist has been the 36th-largest supplier at  
Super Valu, and Heinz's frozen food business is 28th. But the 
combined Heinz food business would rank third at Super Valu and 
among the top five at all retail customers, executives said. 
</P>
<P>
	The grocery and food industries are jockeying with one other for  
clout, leading to industrywide consolidation, Johnson said, though 
he declined to say whether Heinz would be one of those merging. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is consolidation to be done, we want to come at it  
from a position of strength, not one of individual weakness,'' 
Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Moran, now Heinz's vice president for U.S. retail sales,  
will be president of the new division. He joined the company 18 
months ago after working at Clorox and Procter &AMP; Gamble. 
</P>
<P>
	The move replaces a ``fragmented collection of business  
fiefdoms,'' Johnson said. He expects that it will save $25 million 
a year in combined personnel, computer, financial and other 
operations at the new Pittsburgh campus. 
</P>
<P>
	The combining businesses account for $5 billion of Heinz's $9  
billion in annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Heinz closed $44 Monday, up 37 1/2 cents on the New York Stock  
Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
