<DOCNO> APW19991004.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 04:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Raymond Alf    	
</P>
<P>
	CLAREMONT, Calif. (AP) -- Raymond Alf, a teacher who inspired  
students with his unusual teaching styles and founded the Raymond 
M. Alf Museum of Paleontology, died Monday. He was 93. 
</P>
<P>
	Alf taught math and biology at Webb Schools, where he was known  
to swing from pipes to demonstrate evolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Alf, who began at Webb as a tutor in 1929, led hundreds of  
students on field trips around the western United States to collect 
fossils. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1940s, after Alf and his student had accumulated  
about 20,000 pieces -- pig skulls to alligator jaws and dinosaur 
tracks -- he began pushing for a museum. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 years later the museum bearing his name was opened on  
the Webb campus and has since drawn scores of professional 
paleontologists and educated a legion of students. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Walter Bergman    	
</P>
<P>
	GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- Walter Bergman, a civil rights  
activist and a founder of the Michigan chapter of the ACLU and the 
Michigan Federation of Teachers, died Wednesday. He was 100. 
</P>
<P>
	A member of the Freedom Riders, Bergman was among those attacked  
on Mother's Day, 1961, by Ku Klux Klan members and other vigilantes 
in Anniston, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergman was knocked to the floor, pounded with fists and stomped  
on his head, neck and shoulders. Doctors believe a stroke he 
suffered months later stemmed from the beating. He was 61 at the 
time and spent the rest of his life in a wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, the American Civil Liberties Union sued the government  
on behalf of Bergman after it was learned the FBI was aware of -- 
but did not stop -- the planned attack on the Freedom Riders. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergman, a professor at Wayne State and the University of  
Michigan, devoted himself to activism after retiring from an 
academic career in the early 1960s. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Weldon W. Case    	
</P>
<P>
	BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) -- Weldon W. Case, the former chairman and  
chief executive officer of Alltel Corp., died Thursday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Case was 14 when he started as a line crew member in 1934 with  
the company, then known as Hudson Underground Telephone Co. He 
worked his way up to general manager and to president of the 
company known as Western Reserve Telephone Co. 
</P>
<P>
	After making several acquisitions, Case founded Mid-Continent  
Telephone Co., which merged in 1983 with Allied Telephone Co. to 
form Alltel Corp. He was chairman and chief executive until he 
retired in 1991. 

</P>
<P>
                           *John J. Conley    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dr. John J. Conley, a surgeon who developed  
operations for improving the speech of patients who lost their 
voice boxes to cancer, died Sept. 21. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Conley, an otolaryngologist, also developed operations for  
rehabilitating the larynx, grafting facial nerves and 
reconstruction after the loss of the jaw to cancer. He developed 
the idea of single-stage rehabilitation after extensive head and 
neck surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	He pioneered reconstruction methods for the cheek and face as an  
Army surgeon in World War II, and developed further innovations in 
the 1960s and early 1970s. In the early 1990s, he founded the John 
Conley Foundation for Ethics and Philosophy in Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Conley retired at age 80, ending his professional ties to  
Columbia University's College of Physicians and Surgeons, 
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center, and St. Vincent's Hospital 
and Medical Center. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Pat Davis    	
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Pat Davis, a popular radio journalist  
who covered California politics and national news for three 
decades, died Friday of a heart attack during a bicycle ride. He 
was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	His news reports were heard regularly on KFBK in Sacramento, his  
home station, as well as KNX in Los Angeles, KGO in San Francisco 
and on CBS and Associated Press Radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis also appeared in a weekly political broadcast for public  
television on station KVIE in Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 1970s, he has covered virtually every major national  
news story in northern and central California, as well as 
presidential, gubernatorial and U.S. Senate campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife and two children.  

</P>
<P>
                       *Charles A. Federer Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	MYSTIC, Conn. (AP) -- Charles A. Federer Jr., the editor in chief  
of Sky and Telescope magazine, died Tuesday. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Federer started the magazine for amateur astronomers in 1941 and  
retired in 1974. The magazine now has a circulation of about 
125,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Federer taught himself astronomy as a child growing up in  
Redding. He earned a physics degree from the City College of New 
York in the 1930s and founded his own magazine by combining two 
money-losing journals, The Sky and The Telescope. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Norbert Gaughan    	
</P>
<P>
	CROWN POINT, Ind. (AP) -- Former Bishop Norbert Gaughan, who  
fought the Vatican's move to scale back his duties as bishop of the 
Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary after suffering a series of strokes, 
died Friday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaughan was installed as the second bishop of the Gary Diocese  
in July 1984. He moved the center of diocesan operations from the 
main cathedral in beleaguered Gary to a new $1.3 million ``pastoral 
center'' in nearby suburban Merrillville. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaughan suffered a stroke in April 1989, followed by a severe  
second stroke in February 1992 that kept him from his duties for 
three months. Pope John Paul II appointed Bishop Dale Melczek, then 
auxiliary bishop for the Archdiocese of Detroit, to handle the 
diocese's administrative duties. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1993, Gaughan traveled to Rome to appeal to the pope  
for the ``complete reinstatement'' of his job, but to no avail. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaughan retired from the active ministry in June 1996.  

</P>
<P>
                       *Alastair Hetherington    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Alastair Hetherington, editor of The Guardian for  
nearly 20 years and later head of the British Broadcasting Corp. in 
Scotland, died Sunday. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	As editor of The Guardian from 1956 to 1975, Hetherington  
oversaw the move of the venerable Manchester Guardian to the 
renamed newspaper's present base in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Hetherington joined the Manchester Guardian in 1950 after four  
years at The Glasgow Herald, and served as assistant editor and 
foreign editor. In 1971, he was named Journalist of the Year in the 
National Press awards. 
</P>
<P>
	He became head of BBC Scotland in 1975 and held the post three  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Hetherington wrote a half dozen books including, ``A Walker's  
Guide to Arran,'' the Scottish island where he had a home. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, four children and three  
stepchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Akio Morita    	
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Akio Morita, the entrepreneur, engineer and savvy  
salesman who helped establish Sony Corp, died Sunday of pneumonia. 
He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Morita co-founded Sony in a bombed-out department store after  
World War II. He was the last of a generation of Japanese 
industrialists that included carmaker Soichiro Honda and 
electronics rival Konosuke Matsushita. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Morita's guidance, Sony was instrumental in changing  
Japan's image from a maker of slipshod products to a world leader 
in high-quality automobiles and electronics. In the process, his 
company became a multibillion dollar conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Morita retired as Sony's chairman in 1994. A year earlier he had  
suffered a stroke that left him weakened and in a wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
	He caused a stir in 1989 by co-authoring ``The Japan That Can  
Say 'No''' with current Tokyo Gov. Shintaro Ishihara. In it, Morita 
criticized U.S. corporate culture as overindulgent. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Morris Pashman    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Former New Jersey Supreme Court Justice Morris  
Pashman died of leukemia Sunday. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Pashman was a member of the court for 10 years. He was forced  
into mandatory retirement in September 1982. He served as 
assignment judge in Bergen and Passaic counties before being named 
to the high court by Gov. William Cahill. 
</P>
<P>
	He quickly established a reputation as a dissenter on the court,  
often making up the lone voice in 6-1 opinions. Another former 
justice, Richard Hughes, once referred to Pashman as ``the father 
of the dissent opinion.'' 

</P>
<P>
                           *Sal Salvador    	
</P>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Sal Salvador, a guitarist who performed  
with some of jazz's top musicians, died of cancer Sept. 22. He was 
73. 
</P>
<P>
	Born as Silvio Smiraglia, Salvador taught himself how to play  
guitar and became known as a be-bop improviser. He performed with 
Stan Kenton, Bill Evans, Phil Woods and other jazz greats. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1970 until recently, Salvador taught jazz at the University  
of Bridgeport and Western Connecticut State University. He also 
gave private lessons in New York City. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Wayne Sevier    	
</P>
