<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mattel Shares Plunge 28 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- A profit warning by Mattel Inc. is  
raising speculation about whether Jill E. Barad will remain at the 
helm of the company that's home to the Barbie and Hot Wheels toys. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel stock plummeted nearly 30 percent Monday after Barad  
announced that the company's children's software subsidiary, The 
Learning Company, will lose $50 million to $100 million in the 
third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	That could put pressure on Mattel's board to replace the  
embattled Barad with new management. Some institutional investors 
already were pressing quietly for a change, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I personally like Jill Barad, but I suspect there is some  
pressure from institutional shareholders for change,'' said Erik 
Gustafson, a portfolio manager at Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham Inc., which 
holds nearly 5 million Mattel shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been continual suggestion by outside commentators,  
including institutional investors, that the board consider a new 
management team,'' he said. ``I suspect this exacerbates that and 
makes the call for change even louder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barad, who is forsaking a seat on Microsoft's board to focus on  
Mattel, has the ``full support'' of the company's board of 
directors, spokesman Glenn Bozarth said. She was not available for 
interviews, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel was expected to provide more detail on the loss when  
third quarter results are released Oct. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's drop in the share price was the most dramatic in a long  
slide for Mattel stock. Shares have lost 74 percent of their value 
since hitting a 10-year peak of $46 3/4 in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Barad, 48, was named chairwoman and chief executive officer in  
1997 after building the Barbie brand from a $200 million-per-year 
line into an industry giant with annual sales of $1.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's slide has raised questions of whether Barad could  
handle the top job, said Jim Silver, editor of The Toy Book, an 
industry publication. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anybody knows for sure, but obviously you would  
have to guess the board is watching things closely,'' Silver said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Learning Company isn't the only problem that Barad faces.  
Hasbro, the No. 2 U.S. toymaker, has gained on Mattel ground with 
mega-hits like Furby, Pokemon dolls and ``Star Wars'' action 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel's president and chief operating officer left earlier this  
year. And it was announced Monday that Mattel Media President David 
Haddad was quitting to head eParties, an online party supply 
company launched by Internet incubator eCompanies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mattel has lacked hit product power, and has been facing  
internal management turmoil for quite some time,'' Jill Krutick, an 
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, wrote in a message to clients. 
</P>
<P>
	Krutick cut her earnings estimate for all of 1999 by nearly  
half, from $1.35 per share to 76 cents a share. Estimates for 2000 
earnings from $1.75 per share to $1. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel blamed the disappointing profits on a range of problems,  
including higher-than-expected returns of The Learning Company 
merchandise, a lost licensing deal, bad debts and termination of 
agreements with some distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel's core businesses remain sound, Barad said in a brief  
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, The Learning Company performance masks the  
underlying vitality of our core U.S. business,'' Barad said. ``This 
strength was most evident in over-the-counter sales improvements 
for Barbie, Fisher-Price and our Wheels brands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Orders for those brands exceeded Mattel's capacity to ship by  
more than $100 million, she said. Excess orders will be filled 
early in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-quarter results will be released Oct. 21, the company  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel acquired The Learning Company earlier this year for $3.8  
billion in stock as part of an effort to tap the growing market for 
sophisticated, interactive toys. The Learning Company's software 
titles include Carmen Sandiego, American Greetings, The Print Shop, 
Riven and Myst. 
</P>
<P>
	A third-quarter loss is especially disturbing because investors  
were expecting positive results that would show Mattel was managing 
the acquisition and resolving its other problems, said Gustafson. 
</P>
<P>
	``A major miss,'' he said. ``We thought the company was healing  
and in better shape, and that business was good. In some of their 
core product lines, it was good. But this complete, devastating 
miss at The Learning Company has just caught all of us by 
surprise.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
