<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> JFK Administration Reunites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The last time so many former members of John F.  
Kennedy's administration were under one roof was the 35th 
president's funeral. 
</P>
<P>
	In a class reunion of sorts, dozens gathered Sunday to celebrate  
the 20th anniversary of the library and museum built in his honor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very moving experience,'' said Theodore Sorensen, 71,  
former special counsel to Kennedy. ``This was a very special 
group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A panel discussion featuring Sorensen, former assistant attorney  
general Burke Marshall and historian Arthur Schlesinger Jr. focused 
on their former boss' achievements, from avoiding nuclear disaster 
to fostering loyalty and honesty in his administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Decrying ``the new cynicism about American politics,''  
Schlesinger recalled Kennedy's ability to inspire both a nation and 
a young group of staffers he called on for help in running the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a youthful time, a youthful administration, a young  
president,'' said Stewart Udall, 79, former Secretary of the 
Interior. ``At a time when there's so much gridlock and stupidity 
in Washington, it might be productive for the younger generation to 
recreate and understand what happened (during Kennedy's tenure).'' 
</P>
<P>
	The forum, part of a monthlong series of events to commemorate  
the 20th anniversary of the John F. Kennedy Library and Museum, was 
attended by more than 40 members of the administration and hundreds 
of members of the public. 
</P>
<P>
	The celebration was to resume today, with Kennedy's daughter,  
Caroline Kennedy, co-sponsoring a forum on citizenship and 
community service. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Daly, executive director of the library and former staff  
assistant to Kennedy, said the reunion was meant to be a festive 
occasion to celebrate the president's legacy and give the public 
``a sense of what it was like then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the faces have changed a bit,'' he said. ``But it was  
very gratifying.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
