<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM, AT&AMP;T Offer Cos. Web Packages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM and AT&AMP;T are pooling their huge marketing  
resources to try to attract small- and mid-sized companies seeking 
to exploit the promise of the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest computer company and the No. 1 U.S.  
telecommunications provider plan to sell a combined package of 
package of products and services to help businesses set up Web 
sites for handling transactions, sales and communications. 
</P>
<P>
	The unusual alliance underscores the huge potential market in  
business customers trying to cut costs and boost sales by using the 
Internet. While large corporations are far along in developing 
Internet presences, many smaller companies are just getting 
started. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM plans to sell computers and software for running the Web  
sites while AT&AMP;T will provide Internet connections to customers. 
The price for the package starts at $35,000, said a source familiar 
with the alliance, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies would not comment ahead of an announcement  
Wednesday on the arrangement. 
</P>
<P>
	The offering will be jointly sold by IBM's and AT&AMP;T. While IBM  
has a huge sales force, targeting many thousands of small- and 
mid-sized businesses requires the far-flung resources of 
third-party distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies will pool their immense marketing resources to  
promote the products. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance comes as the battle rages to attract business  
customers drawn to the Web's potential. A recent study by Giga 
Information Group estimates that corporations around the world will 
save up to $1.25 trillion -- close to France's entire gross domestic 
product -- by doing business over the Internet by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Those savings range from reducing the amount of people it takes  
to process a sales request to making it easier and less expensive 
to order office supplies online. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
