<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reports: Bidding War for Sprint Corp. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A bidding war has erupted for the Sprint Corp.,  
with two companies reportedly offering as much as $100 billion for 
the nation's third-largest long-distance telephone company. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint's board members met Sunday to compare a $93 billion offer  
from MCI Worldcom Inc. with a $100 billion offer from BellSouth 
Corp., sources familiar with the issue told The New York Times, USA 
Today and The Wall Street Journal. MCI's offer is a stock swap and 
BellSouth's a combination of cash and stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks were said to be continuing.  
</P>
<P>
	Such a deal would be the largest takeover ever, eclipsing last  
year's $82.5 billion merger agreement between the Exxon Corp. and 
the Mobil Corp. The effect might not be immediately apparent to 
consumer because telephone rates are already competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	Acquiring Sprint could yield billions in cost savings for MCI  
Worldcom or BellSouth by eliminating overlapping operations and 
expanding product lines. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI Worldcom is the No. 2 long-distance carrier. BellSouth is  
the dominant provider of local phone service in the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications companies have scrambled to consolidate for  
greater reach, increased financial clout and the ability to offer 
local, long-distance, wireless and Internet access services. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint has an extensive long-distance network and a collection  
of local telephone operations around the nation. It also has a 
national wireless network and one of the major networks through 
which other companies provide Internet access to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint-MCI Worldcom would be a competitor with the AT&AMP;T Corp.,  
which would remain the nation's largest long-distance company. 
</P>
<P>
	Any deal is subject to approval by antitrust regulators. No Bell  
company has yet received approval to offer long-distance service in 
its local-service region. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 12:00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ginsburg Back on Supreme Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seventeen days after undergoing surgery for  
colon cancer, Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg was on the 
bench today as the nation's highest court opened its 1999-2000 
term. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg, looking slightly thinner and paler than usual, smiled  
broadly as she took her place at the end of the bench. Before 
taking her seat, she smiled at her husband, Martin, and two grown 
children, James and Jane, who were in the courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	She asked 12 questions of lawyers arguing the first of two cases  
heard by the court today. 
</P>
<P>
	Issuing a flurry of orders on opening day, the court:  
</P>
<P>
	--Turned away arguments that Mumia Abu-Jamal, a former radio  
reporter sentenced to death for the 1981 killing of a Philadelphia 
policeman, was denied a fair trial. However, there is little 
likelihood he will be executed soon. 
</P>
<P>
	--Let Knox County, Tenn., school officials require drug testing  
of everyone offered a teaching job. Without comment the court 
rejected a teachers group's argument that such tests are 
unconstitutional if officials do not suspect the tested individual 
of using drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Turned away challenges to Arizona's program allowing up to $500  
in tax credits for contributions for scholarships at religious and 
other private schools. Justices refused to review a state court 
decision that the credits do not violate the Constitution's 
requirement for separation of church and state. 
</P>
<P>
	--Left standing a ruling that participation by Michael Montalvo,  
a Colonial Heights, Va., 12-year-old with AIDS, in a 
rough-and-tumble karate school would pose too much of a threat to 
the health and safety of other students. 
</P>
<P>
	As is court custom, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist made no  
mention of Ginsburg's recent illness as he declared the new term 
open. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of Ginsburg's colon was removed during her surgery on Sept.  
17, but last week court spokeswoman Kathy Arberg said doctors found 
that the cancer had not spread to any lymph nodes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg, 66, fell ill this summer while teaching in Crete, and  
initially was treated for acute diverticulitis, a gastric disorder. 
Arberg said last week that the severe abdominal inflammation for 
which Ginsburg was first treated was unrelated to the colon cancer, 
but it led doctors to discover the tumor. 
</P>
<P>
	The justice went home from Washington Hospital Center last  
Tuesday. While she was in the hospital, she participated in the 
court's consideration of a number of cases granted review in 
advance of today's term opening. 
</P>
<P>
	Also sitting in the courtroom's guest section today was retired  
Justice Byron R. White, the only living retired justice. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 17:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley: Clinton Health Plan Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seizing upon the day's headlines, Democratic  
presidential candidate Bill Bradley scored the Clinton-Gore 
administration a failure in helping Americans secure health 
insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore's proposal to expand the Children's  
Health Insurance Program to extend coverage to nearly every child 
``simply modifies the programs whose success rates are clearly in 
question,'' Bradley said Monday in a statement from his New Jersey 
campaign headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The former senator from New Jersey was reacting to a Census  
Bureau report finding that the number of Americans without health 
insurance increased by nearly 1 million -- to 44.3 million -- last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	With an eye on Gore's child-focused health plan that builds on  
the Clinton administration's agenda, Bradley said: ``It's clear 
that the current federal programs for children, Medicaid and the 
Children's Health Insurance, are not achieving their goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to stop nibbling around the edges and live up to the  
challenge of providing affordable health care to everyone in 
America,'' Bradley continued. 
</P>
<P>
	His statement reflected a new dynamic in the tightened  
Bradley-Gore race for the Democratic nomination: the eagerness of 
each side to draw direct and sharp contrasts with the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley has proposed $65 billion in government subsidies and tax  
breaks to help individuals pay for health insurance. He estimates 
his plan would extend insurance coverage to at least 95 percent of 
the population. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Chris Lehane countered that Bradley's proposal --  
projected over 10 years -- would blow almost as much of the federal 
budget surplus as ``the Republicans' risky tax scheme'' and would 
also ``imperil Medicare and Social Security.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
