<DOCNO> APW19991004.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 23:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese, Gold Funds Gain in 3rd Q / Mutual Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Third-quarter mutual fund performance was down  
virtually across the board. 
</P>
<P>
	Surprisingly, the only two fund sectors to see the kind of  
double-digit growth investors have come to expect in the 1990s were 
categories that have been pummeled through much of the decade -- 
funds related to Japan and gold, according to Lipper Inc., a New 
York firm that tracks mutual fund performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The entire mutual fund industry got caught in the overall market  
downdraft that saw the Dow Jones industrial average shed 1,000 
points, or 9 percent, during the final weeks of the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a typical September, which has historically been a  
difficult time for stocks, and that took a lot of spark out of the 
mutual fund market,'' said Robert Walsh, a portfolio manager with 
King Investment Advisors in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh said three factors contributed to the third quarter  
downturn: fears that the Federal Reserve Board would raise interest 
rates for a third time this year to keep inflation at bay; concerns 
that Y2K computer bugs could hurt companies' ability to do 
business; and the dollar's recent slide against foreign currencies, 
especially the Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider some of the dismal performance figures: Diversified  
United States stock funds, whose portfolios include stocks from 
similar-sized companies but from a number of different industries, 
were down on average 5.37 percent; and sector funds, whose 
portfolios include stocks from the same industries, fell an average 
of 3.51 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Within those categories, certain popular niches stood out for  
their dismal performances. For example, diversified funds that 
track the performance of the S&AMP;P 500 index fell an average of 6.35 
percent. And funds that focus on financial services stocks fell 
12.68 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The science and technology fund group, which rose an average of  
7.02 percent, was the only sector to record the kind of 
performances mutual fund investors have grown accustomed to in the 
1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Japanese and gold oriented funds rose 22.78 percent  
and 19.21 percent, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese funds clearly benefited from the dollar's decline  
against the yen. As the dollar plunged to 3 1/2-year lows against the 
yen and Japan's economy recovered from recession, many foreign 
investors pulled their money out of U.S. funds and put it into 
Japanese funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Pacific region funds rode the Japanese wave to an average 8.35  
percent third quarter gain. 
</P>
<P>
	Latin American funds stumbled, however, losing an average of  
10.25 percent on fears that economies in that region aren't 
developing the types of cutting edge technologies, such as the 
Internet, analysts said. Other emerging markets funds fell 6.73 
percent on average on similar concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	International gold stocks got an unexpected boost late last  
month when a group of European central banks decided to put a cap 
on their sales of gold bullion. The announcement triggered the 
biggest one day price increase for gold in 13 years, and pushed the 
price of South African gold stocks up an average of 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	World prices for the metal have been falling for two decades  
since peaking at $875 an ounce in January 1980 -- a time when the 
U.S. inflation rate was in double figures, oil prices were rising 
rapidly and Soviet troops were entering Afghanistan. Gold has 
historically been a haven for investors in times of turmoil, but 
less so in recent years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
