<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 15:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Athletics Encouraged by Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- It lasted for just one day in August. Yet  
it provided what the Oakland Athletics hope was a glimpse into 
their future. 
</P>
<P>
	The A's, picked by many observers to finish last in the AL West,  
flirted with the playoffs and put together their first winning 
season since 1992 while improving by 13 games over last season -- 
the biggest increase in victories in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	It all came together on Aug. 22, when the A's defeated Toronto  
4-3 and took advantage of a loss by the Boston Red Sox to move into 
sole possession of the top spot in the chase for the AL wild card. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they fell into a tie with Boston the next day, and within  
a week were trailing the Red Sox for good, the A's showed that a 
young, low-budget team can compete for a postseason spot. 
</P>
<P>
	With a $22.8 million opening-day payroll that ranked among the  
five lowest in the majors, and with a team sprinkled with rookies 
and second-year players, Oakland had the best home record in the AL 
(52-29) and posted the league's third-best ERA (4.69). 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a successful season, a big step in the right  
direction,'' manager Art Howe said. ``I think these guys have had 
about as much enjoyment in this season as they've had in any 
season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of those enjoying it the most was Randy Velarde, traded from  
the Anaheim Angels to the A's along with pitcher Omar Olivares on 
July 29. Instead of selling off players before the trade deadline, 
as they had in recent seasons, the A's obtained several players as 
part of their playoff push. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Velarde and Olivares, the A's got Kevin Appier  
from Kansas City and -- as part of the trade that sent Kenny Rogers 
and Billy Taylor to the New York Mets -- got Jason Isringhausen, who 
converted all eight of his save chances for Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coming over here rekindled my spirit and made me excited to  
play every day,'' Velarde said. ``To come over to a team that was 
in contention and be a part of that was inspiring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Velarde was one of several A's to put together a stellar season.  
He hit .317 and became the sixth major league player with 200 hits 
in a season in which he played for two clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Giambi hit .315, had 33 homers and drove in 123 runs, one  
short of the Oakland record set by Jose Canseco in 1988. John Jaha, 
signed as a free agent last winter when other teams rejected him 
because of foot problems, made the All-Star team while hitting 35 
homers and driving in 111 runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Stairs led the team with 38 homers and had 102 RBIs. Ben  
Grieve overcame a deep slump in the first half of the season to hit 
28 homers and drive in 86 runs. 
</P>
<P>
	On the mound, Gil Heredia went 13-8 and was the only pitcher to  
throw 200 innings for the A's. Tim Hudson, who started the season 
in the Double-A minors, went 11-2 with a 3.23 ERA while outdueling 
Randy Johnson and Pedro Martinez. 
</P>
<P>
	Isringhausen had a 2.13 ERA in 20 appearances and made himself a  
top candidate to become the closer the A's have been searching for 
since the departure of Dennis Eckersley. 
</P>
<P>
	While the A's improved significantly on the field, the situation  
deteriorated off the field. A deal was finally worked out to sell 
the team to local buyers who promised to keep the club in Oakland, 
but major league owners tabled that deal and left the franchise's 
future in limbo. 
</P>
<P>
	And while attendance improved to 1.4 million fans from 1.2  
million the previous season, the A's still had one of the worst 
home attendance marks in the majors. Even when the team was in the 
playoff race, a three-game series against Minnesota drew fewer than 
23,000 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	The A's hope the growth of players such as Grieve, Hudson and  
shortstop Miguel Tejada will continue the turnaround next year, but 
Howe knows a few offseason moves could be the key to success. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to need some veterans to come in next season to  
keep this going,'' he said. ``And we're going to need the right 
guys.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
