<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Japan Sees Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In a mixed signal about Japan's prospects for  
economic recovery, the central bank reported today a steep rise in 
business confidence but a drop in business investment plans. 
</P>
<P>
	In its closely-watched quarterly ``tankan'' survey, the Bank of  
Japan said sentiment among large manufacturers had brightened over 
the last survey to a figure of minus 22 from minus 37, it's biggest 
improvement since November 1987. The result exceeded analysts' 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The tankan measures the percentage of firms seeing business  
conditions improve minus the percentage seeing conditions worsen. 
The bank surveyed 9,275 companies in September for the latest 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	Large manufacturers are also optimistic that conditions will  
improve by the next survey. They see sentiment advancing to a 
figure of minus 16 by December. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentiment also improved in all categories of company surveyed,  
from big nonmanufacturers to small manufacturers. And all see 
further improvement by December. 
</P>
<P>
	But the tankan also showed that business investment continues to  
taper off in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The worse-than-expected capital spending figures for this fiscal  
year could yet spoil Japan's nascent economic recovery, traders in 
financial markets said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the central bank survey, large corporation capital  
spending index for this fiscal year is seen falling to minus 9.4 
from minus 5.8 in the last quarter. It's the lowest figure since 
September 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey was released on the heels of two straight quarters of  
growth in Japan's economy and a drop in the jobless rate from a 
record high. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's gross domestic product -- the measure of all goods and  
services produced within its borders -- expanded 2 percent for the 
first quarter of the year after more than a year of recession. It 
followed that up with a gain of 0.2 percent in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the government announced that the unemployment rate  
fell to 4.7 percent in August from a record high of 4.9 percent the 
previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's economy has been struggling to emerge from its deepest  
downturn in a half century. Some analysts still urged caution. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tankan numbers show an improvement that exceeds  
expectations, but I'm skeptical that this can continue,'' said 
Yoshio Shukuwa, a market economist at Sanwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are still worries about this economic recovery --  
specifically, the rising yen,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks got a small lift from the report. The benchmark 225-issue  
Nikkei Stock Average closed up 51.15 points, or 0.29 percent, to 
17,763.71. On Friday, the index climbed 107.10 points, or 0.61 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Japanese yen gave up early gains against the dollar on  
news of the drop in business investment. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. dollar wound up at 106.11 yen on the Tokyo foreign  
exchange market today, up 0.17 yen from late Friday and also above 
its late Friday level of 104.96 yen in New York. The greenback 
traded from 104.42 yen to 106.22 yen during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	While down for the day, the yen still is near the 3 1/2-year high  
reached last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities fear that if the yen becomes too strong, the  
country's budding economic recovery could be endangered as profits 
at big exporters suffer. A stronger yen makes Japanese products 
more expensive in overseas markets. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
