<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers' Offense Hits Bad Patch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jerome Bettis isn't campaigning to get the  
ball more, even though the Pittsburgh Steelers' offense keeps 
getting less and less yardage when Kordell Stewart has it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what it is,'' Bettis said Monday, a day after a  
second straight touchdown-less Sunday afternoon. ``All I know is, 
we're not playing Steelers football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The question is what kind of football that would be. Four games  
into the season, Bettis doesn't have a 100-yard game -- and the 
Steelers' starting offense doesn't have a touchdown in two home 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Much like the NFL revived instant replay this season, the  
Steelers' slow-go offense is a replay of December. Throw out the 
opening night 43-0 rout of expansion Cleveland, and Stewart has led 
two touchdown drives in seven games, six of them losses. 
</P>
<P>
	It gets worse.  
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers had never lost more than three consecutive home  
games since moving into Three Rivers Stadium 1970, but now have 
lost four in a row -- their longest streak since they played in Pitt 
Stadium in the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers' offense hasn't been so bad since the Nixon  
administration -- not Richard Nixon, but Mike Nixon, who was 2-12 in 
his only season as coach in 1965. The Steelers didn't score more 
than 22 points in a game that season. 
</P>
<P>
	They've changed offensive coordinators, systems and their  
philosophy this season. But what the Steelers haven't changed are 
the results. 
</P>
<P>
	They have lost seven of nine dating to last season, a span in  
which their offense -- throwing out the Cleveland game -- has scored 
74 points. That's barely a touchdown a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the blame is falling upon Stewart, but he's not getting  
much help from receivers who can't get open and an offensive line 
that can't protect him. Even All-Pro center Dermontti Dawson had a 
rare bad game in last week's 29-10 loss to Seattle, and that was 
before Stewart was sacked four times against Jacksonville, twice 
for safeties. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second week in a row the Steelers' offensive starters  
have been outscored by the opposing defense. Seattle did it last 
week as Merton Hanks returned an interception for a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	And while he's not getting much help, these numbers don't lie:  
in his last eight games, Stewart has two touchdown passes and 12 
interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't have time to throw the ball, and when he does,  
we're not getting open,'' receiver Hines Ward said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers' defense has yielded one touchdown in two games,  
yet wound up a loser both times. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're playing a good team like Jacksonville, you've got  
to make plays, and we're not making them,'' said Bettis, who has 
232 rushing yards in four games -- or 126 fewer than last season. 
``When we need a big play, we can't make it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart hasn't been the same quarterback since the Steelers let  
Yancey Thigpen leave after the 1997 season, when Stewart threw for 
21 touchdowns and ran for 11. But don't look for any quarterback 
change, now or any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a lack of production that would get quarterbacks around  
the NFL benched, Stewart is in the first season of a $27 million 
contract extension that paid him an $8.1 million signing bonus. The 
Steelers don't often throw that kind of money around, certainly not 
for a player who winds up sitting the bench behind 37-year-old Mike 
Tomczak. 
</P>
<P>
	One problem that needs fixing: Stewart and his receivers aren't  
reading defenses the same way. Offensive coordinator Kevin 
Gilbride's system calls for receivers to adjust their routes to the 
defense, and for the quarterback to make the same adjustments. 
That's why several passes have landed incomplete without a receiver 
in the vicinity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Defenses are going to continue to try to do everything they  
can to confuse him until he figures out this game.'' said Jaguars 
safety Carnell Lake, Stewart's teammate a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Or, at least until Stewart and the rest of the Steelers figure  
out Gilbride's offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a matter of everybody having confidence in what  
we're doing, starting with myself,'' said Stewart, who is 
next-to-last in the AFC passer ratings, trailing only the 
now-benched Scott Mitchell of Baltimore. ``We're just trying to get 
something going, because nothing's happening right now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
