<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Oct. 4, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Higher; Dow Up 128.23  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply today, led by  
telecommunications and transportation issues, as news of big 
corporate mergers gave interest-rate weary investors something to 
be excited about. The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 128.23 
at 10,401.23. Broader stock measures also moved higher. The Nasdaq 
composite index was up 59.14 at 2,795.99. Telecommunications issues 
helped carry the market higher after BellSouth joined a bidding war 
with MCI WorldCom for Sprint, the No. 3 U.S. long-distance carrier. 
Sprint and MCI gained while BellSouth slid. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10401.23 + 128.23
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,761  Declines 1,249  Unchgd  520
NYSE Volume:         776,301,680
Most Active NYSE issue:         Mattel Inc11 3/4   - 5 1/8
S&AMP;P 500:         1302.80 + 19.99
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          789.83  +  3.30
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,795.99  + 59.14
Gold(final) -    $316.40    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
Silver(final) -   $5.560  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Fed Expected To Stand Pat on Rates  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the economy still racing along, the  
Federal Reserve might be expected to be preparing to raise interest 
rates for a third time this year to cool things off. But most 
economists are betting that the central bank will leave rates 
unchanged when policy-makers meet tomorrow. They base that view on 
what Fed officials have had to say in recent weeks and also on 
economic indicators showing that while economic growth has been 
strong, keeping unemployment at a 29-year low, inflation has 
remained benign as well. Lawrence Chimerine, economist at the 
Economic Strategy Institute, a Washington think tank, says: ``They 
have moved pre-emptively twice this year. They can't keep 
pre-empting when the traditional indicators of an increase in 
inflation are not there.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Bidding War Erupts for Sprint Corp.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A bidding war has erupted for the Sprint Corp.,  
with two companies reportedly offering as much as $100 billion for 
the nation's third-largest long-distance telephone company. 
Sprint's board members met yesterday to compare offers from MCI 
WorldCom Inc., the No. 2 long-distance company, and a higher, 
last-minute bid from BellSouth Corp., the Atlanta-based Baby Bell, 
according to two people familiar with the negotiations. Sprint's 
board was scheduled to meet today to vote on MCI WorldCom's offer 
of about $63 a share. BellSouth is trying to trump that deal with a 
$72-a-share bid, according to the sources, who spoke on condition 
of anonymity. 

</P>
<P>
	Overall Auto Sales Up, Ford Slides  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- In the midst of one of the strongest years ever  
for U.S. auto sales, Ford Motor Co. took a breather last month as 
its sales declined 2 percent. Automakers sold about 1.4 million 
cars and light trucks in the United States last month, an increase 
of about 9.5 percent over last year. Analysts expect 1999 to break 
the record sales for the year. Ford said that sales of its Ford, 
Lincoln and Mercury cars were down 5 percent last month, mostly 
because of fewer sales to rental and business fleets. For the 
month, Ford, GM and DaimlerChrysler saw sales increase 4 percent. 
GM said its sales were up 8.5 percent, and DaimlerChrysler AG said 
sales at its Chrysler division were up 7 percent. Ford shares were 
at 51 5/16, up 11/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Mattel Stocks Plunge 29 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Mattel Inc. warned investors today  
that third-quarter profits will drop sharply due to a big loss at 
The Learning Company, the software maker acquired earlier this year 
to take Mattel beyond Barbie dolls and Hot Wheels cars into the 
world of high-tech interactive toys. The news pushed Mattel shares 
down more than 28 percent and prompted some speculation that the 
company's chairwoman and chief executive officer, Jill E. Barad, 
could soon be out of a job. Mattel, already struggling with a soft 
international toy market and an inability to produce a blockbuster 
hit in recent years, said it expected The Learning Company to lose 
$50 million to $100 million, pushing earnings for the world's 
largest toymaker into the range of 30 cents to 40 cents per share. 
Mattel stock fell 5 points, or more than 29 percent, to 11 7/8 today. 

</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T Said Studying Separate Stocks  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp., irked by a slumping stock price,  
reportedly may create separate ``tracking'' stocks to reflect the 
value of different businesses such as the company's cable and 
wireless operations. Any such plan would likely have to wait until 
after AT&AMP;T completes its acquisition of the cable TV company 
MediaOne Group, expected sometime next year, The Wall Street 
Journal said today. The debate over tracking stocks follows a 
recent 25 percent slide in AT&AMP;T's share price that some executives 
blame on confusion over how to value such a wide array of 
businesses, especially after the company's sudden foray into cable 
television. AT&AMP;T shares were at 43 3/4, up 2. 

</P>
<P>
	Walgreen Co. Earnings Jump  
</P>
<P>
	DEERFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Walgreen Co. reported a 5.2 percent rise  
in fourth quarter earnings today, thanks in part to strong pharmacy 
sales. The largest U.S. drugstore chain said said earnings reached 
$161 million, or 16 cents a share, compared to $152 million in the 
same quarter a year ago. Sales rose 18.7 percent for the quarter to 
$4.6 billion, with prescriptions accounting for 20 percent of the 
increase. Sales for the fiscal year were up 16.5 percent from last 
year, while annual net income rose to $624.1 million from $510.8 
million. 

</P>
<P>
	UPS Offers Customers Web Link  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service plans to provide free  
access to its World Wide Web site for customers who aren't already 
online. The service is called ``fenced'' Internet access because it 
allows users to link only to the UPS Web site. The service, which 
uses the Microsoft Internet Explorer browser and connection 
software from AT&AMP;T, will be unveiled Wednesday at the Fall Internet 
World show in New York and will be distributed to interested 
companies early next year. 

</P>
<P>
	Clear Channel To Buy AMFM for $17B  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Clear Channel Communications Inc. is buying AMFM  
Inc. for $16.8 billion in stock, creating a company that will 
dominate the airwaves with 830 radio stations across the nation. 
The combined company, which will keep the Clear Channel name, will 
operate radio stations in the 20 largest U.S. markets except 
Seattle, feeding every taste from country rock to 24-hour sports 
talk. To head off antitrust cries from regulators and consumer 
groups, executives plan to sell 125 radio stations worth about $4.2 
billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Hachette May Buy George Shares  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hachette Filipacchi Magazines hopes to buy the  
Kennedy family's stake in George magazine, the political and 
lifestyle publication founded by John F. Kennedy Jr., who died in a 
July plane crash. ``No final agreement has been reached as yet but 
hopefully an agreement will be completed relatively soon,'' HFM 
spokesman Keith Estabrook said today. He declined to provide 
details about the discussions. Hachette Filipacchi Magazines and 
the Kennedy family each own half of the magazine. 

</P>
<P>
	French Bosses Oppose 35-Hour Week  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Thousands of bosses gathered today in Paris to  
protest the French government's proposals for a shortened 35-hour 
workweek. They held their rally a day before lawmakers open debate 
on how to implement the controversial measure. About 25,000 
employers crowded into a noisy exposition hall, waving signs saying 
``For The Freedom Of Business.'' Across town, the Communist-backed 
union, the General Workers Confederation, drew some 25,000 people 
to its rally to press lawmakers not to leave companies too much 
leeway in interpreting the plan. 

</P>
