<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Ginsburg Back to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg,  
recovering from surgery for colon cancer, took the bench with her 
colleagues Monday as the nation's highest court opened its 
1999-2000 term. 
</P>
<P>
	The justice looked slightly thinner and paler than usual, but  
she smiled broadly as she took her place on the end of the bench. 
Her husband, Martin, and two grown children, James and Jane, were 
in the courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	As is court custom, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist made no  
mention of Ginsburg's recent illness as he declared the new term 
open. She asked 12 questions of lawyers arguing the first of two 
cases heard by the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Monday, Ginsburg spoke during an award ceremony in the  
court building. 
</P>
<P>
	``No words can convey how pleased I am to be here with you  
today,'' she told the audience. 
</P>
<P>
	The 66-year-old justice had part of her colon removed 17 days  
ago. Court spokeswoman Kathy Arberg last week said doctors found 
that the cancer had not spread to any lymph nodes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
