<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Denies Olympic Shortfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Sydney Olympic officials said Monday  
that reports the 2000 Games were facing a $140 million sponsorship 
shortfall were incorrect. 
</P>
<P>
	The report of the sponsorship shortfall came after International  
Olympic Committee vice-president Dick Pound, who negotiates key 
television and sponsorship deals, addressed the IOC executive board 
in Athens over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound, who was arguing for the scaling back of the  
commercialization of the Games, criticized the Sydney Organizing 
Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG) for setting its sponsorship 
revenue targets too high. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you push the envelope too far, you end up denigrating  
Olympic marketing,'' Pound said. 
</P>
<P>
	A SOCOG spokesman, who asked not to be identified, said reports  
of a shortfall were ``absolute nonsense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no secret that we still have to raise $140 million in  
sponsorship revenue, but it's also no secret that there's still a 
year to go before the Olympics,'' he said. ``So any suggestion that 
there is a $140 million shortfall for the Games or a black hole is 
just rubbish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Olympics minister Michael Knight said the  
shortfall was now down to about $78 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the meeting Dick Pound said SOCOG sponsorship and revenue  
raising efforts were a great success and should be hailed as 
such,'' the spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound also said the IOC executive board would consider imposing  
a cap on marketing revenues and reducing the share of funds going 
to organizing committees and national Olympic committees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
