<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 00:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets, Reds To Battle for Wild Card </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The New York Mets arrived first, the  
adrenaline of their ninth-inning win left up in the sky while they 
circled the airport for 35 minutes because of a storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly before sunrise, the Cincinnati Reds would show up,  
fresh-scrubbed from a numbing game played in standing water after a 
rain delay that took up most of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Long days, but not lost days. They still had one more to play.  
</P>
<P>
	The Mets and Reds came through when they had to Sunday, setting  
up the sixth one-game playoff in major league history today to 
decide the NL wild card. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel like there's any home-field advantage in a  
situation like that,'' said Pete Harnisch, who pitched the Reds to 
a bone-chilling 7-1 victory in Milwaukee. ``Both teams are playing 
on emotion and intensity. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot of season that just comes down to one game. That's  
exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not entirely surprising. Both teams wasted chances to wrap  
up a playoff spot in the last two weeks, setting themselves up for 
a long day Sunday followed by a one-game showdown tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can't wait to go,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said as he  
grabbed his hotel key then headed for the elevator shortly before 1 
a.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	There were times in the last two weeks that neither team thought  
it would get this far. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets opened a four-game lead on the Reds with only a dozen  
left, leaving Cincinnati just one misstep away from elimination. 
What followed was a horrendous slide -- seven consecutive losses -- 
that let the Reds pull ahead by 2 1/2 games last Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Things seemed so rosy for the Reds that they brought champagne  
to Milwaukee for a three-game series over the weekend. The corks 
never left the bottles -- the Reds lost the first two while the Mets 
beat Pittsburgh twice, leaving them tied heading into Sunday's 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston Astros clinched the NL Central with a win, leaving  
it to New York and Cincinnati to decide the wild card. The Mets had 
the first starting time and waited until the last minute before 
beating the Pirates 2-1 on Brad Clontz's run-scoring wild pitch in 
the bottom of the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets swarmed their home field when Clontz's pitch to Mike  
Piazza skipped to the backstop with the bases loaded. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess it's kind of indicative of the season we've had,''  
Piazza said. ``Everyone had us buried six feet under.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Up in Milwaukee, the Reds and Brewers felt like they were under  
six feet of water. A steady, heavy rain pushed back the starting 
time by five hours and 47 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of us watched the football game, some of us watched the  
Mets,'' manager Jack McKeon said. ``Some guys took batting 
practice. Nobody was nervous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Reds waited, the Mets got on a plane and headed for  
Cincinnati, hoping to clinch en route with a Brewers' victory. They 
got score updates as they circled the airport waiting out a storm, 
and knew by the time they landed that there would have to be one 
more game. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati's game had just ended when the Mets reached their  
hotel. Downtown streets were wet and deserted, and the players 
quickly filed off the bus and headed for their rooms. A few stopped 
to order pizzas. 
</P>
<P>
	The scene was surreal given what had happened in the last 12  
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of weird because everybody counted us dead a couple  
of days ago and nobody gave us a chance,'' closer John Franco said. 
``We did what we needed to do and we got some help. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's good for baseball. It's a compliment to the Reds  
and to us. People counted us out and they counted Cincinnati out 
all year, waiting for them to die. There's no quit in them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds had a surreal night of their own, playing in front of a  
few hundred fans on a soaked field in temperatures that turned 
their breaths to mist. 
</P>
<P>
	When it was over, there was no celebrating in the clubhouse,  
just a sense of relief that there was one more regular-season game 
to be played. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to take the momentum out of this clubhouse and  
put it in the plane with us and take it back to Cincinnati,'' first 
baseman Sean Casey said. ``We've got guys who are hurting and we've 
got guys who aren't playing their best ball. It was pure guts 
tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The playoff originally was scheduled for 2:05 p.m., but was  
pushed back to 7:05 p.m. because the Reds would be returning at 
such an early hour. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's Al Leiter (12-12) will start against Cincinnati's  
Steve Parris (11-3). If the Reds win, they'll start the first round 
in Atlanta against a team that won eight of nine from them this 
season. If the Mets win, they'll fly to Arizona for the first 
round. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds won five of their nine games against the Mets this  
season, but New York went 4-2 in Cincinnati. The main difference 
between them at this point is that the Reds managed to stay more 
consistent down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he felt that the Mets had gotten a reprieve, reliever  
Chuck McElroy said, ``In a way, but the Reds are still hot right 
now. They may have lost two of three in Milwaukee, but they're 
still a hot team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And a wet team. And a tired team.  
</P>
<P>
	The Mets could certainly identify.  
</P>
</TEXT>
