<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against most other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro slipped to $1.0698 at the end of the European trading  
day from $1.0705 Friday and the British pound fell to $1.6538 from 
$1.6558. The dollar also rose to 106.41 Japanese yen from 105.02. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in afternoon trading in New York, the dollar gave up some  
of its gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro regained its lost ground and was quoted at $1.0708 in  
New York this afternoon, where the pound was at $1.6557 and the 
dollar bought 106.10 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Against other currencies in European trading, the dollar bought  
1.4880 Swiss francs, down from 1.4898 Friday, and 1.4714 Canadian 
dollars, up from 1.4690. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8280 German marks, up from 1.8270; 
6.1327 French francs, up from 6.1293; 2.0595 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0593; and 1,809.94 Italian lire, up from 1,805.92. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $314.00 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$303.00 on Friday. In Zurich the bid price was $313.50, up from 
$305.00. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $9.50 earlier in Hong Kong to close at $313.00.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.57 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.60. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
