<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newpapers Seek More Minorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The American Society of Newspaper Editors set  
guidelines to bring the number of minority newspaper employees in 
line with the general minority population figures by 2025. 
</P>
<P>
	At the group's recent fall board meeting, ASNE approved  
benchmarks at three-year intervals designed to monitor the number 
of minorities working in newsrooms and increase the number of 
minority supervisors. 
</P>
<P>
	``These benchmarks are designed to show us where we are and how  
much further we have to go by 2025,'' said N. Christian Anderson 
III, publisher of The Orange County Register and ASNE president. 
</P>
<P>
	Minorities constitute about 28 percent of the population but  
only about 11 percent of reporters, copy editors, photographers, 
graphic artists and supervisors at daily U.S. newspapers, according 
to a 1999 ASNE survey. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1978, the society approved an intention of making newspaper  
staffs match the nation's racial composition by 2000. ASNE adopted 
the new 2025 target date after deciding the original date was 
unattainable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
