<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Rises; Soybeans Also Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures prices pushed higher Monday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade amid speculation that a government 
report due Friday will show lower-than-expected crop levels. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, gold futures rose $12.70 to $318 per ounce on  
the New York Mercantile Exchange, though still below last week's 
price rally that produced prices as high as $329 Tuesday. Platinum 
and palladium also rallied on gold's increase. 
</P>
<P>
	March world sugar fell 7 points to 6.84 cents a pound on the  
Board of Trade of the City of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices rallied to end higher, despite reports  
that rain throughout the Midwest did little to slow the harvest. 
Some buyers are positioning themselves for Friday's U.S. 
Agriculture Department report. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures prices also rose on ideas that the market had been  
technically oversold. Corn futures prices fell to 11-week lows amid 
continued harvesting and speculation that the U.S. Agriculture 
Department will report increased production Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.68 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 3/4 cents to $2.04 1/4 a bushel; December oats fell 
1 1/4 cents to $1.12 a bushel; and November soybeans rose 2 1/4 cents to 
$4.83 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, live cattle and feeder cattle rose, and lean hogs and  
frozen pork bellies fell in trading Monday on the Chicago 
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose 0.40 cent to $69.17 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose 0.15 cent to 82 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs fell 0.17 cent to 50.20 cents a pound; and February 
frozen pork bellies fell 1.83 cents to 63.77 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	The gold gains are a continuation of an up-move in the market,  
analyst Fred Bogart of Republic Gold said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gold is in a bullish phase,'' he said. ``It was in a bull  
market last week, even though it went down. The market is much more 
volatile these days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some said gold prices are by last week's announcement that  
several key European banks will limit gold sales and lending. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar buying is being affected by questions about how much the  
Russian government will buy once the autumn beet harvest ends. That 
country's beet harvest appears to be better than first predicted 
and weather has turned more favorable after a June drought. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
