<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Retirement Fund May Be Lost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Banking officials said Monday they have been  
unable to find evidence of a retirement account that Mexicans who 
worked in the United States say could hold as much as $150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The failure adds another roadblock in the path of the former  
workers, who claim they have been cheated of money they paid weekly 
into the retirement fund during the bracero program, which ran from 
1942 to 1964. 
</P>
<P>
	``The documentation has been searched for exhaustively, but we  
don't have a way of confirming the existence of the fund in this 
bank,'' said Alejandro Romero, an attorney for the National Rural 
Credit Bank, known as Banrural. 
</P>
<P>
	During World War II, the governments of Mexico and the United  
States created the bracero program which granted Mexicans temporary 
U.S. visas to work the land and man the railroads. About 2.6 
million Mexicans participated from 1942 until 1964. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement by the US and Mexico, each worker had 10  
percent deducted from his paycheck by the Farm Security 
Administration. It was sent to Banco Nacional de Credito Agricola, 
a predecessor of Banrural, or another bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Bracero advocates say that with interest, the fund could hold up  
to $150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	A dozen former braceros had gathered at the bank Monday to hear  
the promised report. 
</P>
<P>
	Romero said those with claims can come forward individually and  
provide with documents that prove they are entitled to money. 
</P>
<P>
	Bracero representatives said that unfairly places the burden of  
proof on people who have waited generations to receive the money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here in Mexico things seem to get lost, especially when the  
heat is on,'' said Ventura Gutierrez, general coordinator of Union 
Without Borders, a U.S.-based group representing former braceros 
trying to claim the benefits. ``If we have to go to Washington 
we'll go to Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gutierrez said he plans to meet this week with congressmen in  
Mexico to press for a remedy. 
</P>
<P>
	If that does not work, he said he will investigate the National  
Archives for documents proving the existence of the fund and the 
amount of money paid into it. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they want to do use the old divide and conquer tactic by  
placing the burden on affected individuals to prove they have right 
to the money,'' Gutierrez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutierrez earlier said he estimated that only about 2 percent of  
braceros were able to collect the money owed them from the fund. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1 million braceros have died, while approximately 20,000  
ex-braceros or their survivors have been located. 
</P>
<P>
	Miguel Angel Gonzalez, an attorney for the Foreign Relations  
Secretariat, said initial research there indicates that while the 
bracero program lasted until 1964, the savings fund existed only 
until 1950. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
