<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Open With Lame-Duck Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Larry Bird left for Florida as the lame-duck  
coach of the Indiana Pacers, promising to push his players toward 
the championship that eluded them in the lockout-shortened 1999 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter what I'm going to do,'' said Bird, who has  
announced he has no plans to coach after his current contract 
expires at the end of the upcoming season. ``It just matters how my 
team plays this year, how we stay together, and how we compete 
every night. It has absolutely nothing to do with me. These guys 
will be playing whether I'm here or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing that does matter to Bird is that he'll have a full  
training camp and exhibition season -- along with time for practice 
-- during the upcoming season. That wasn't the situation last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird has the nucleus back from the team that won the Central  
Division and he's eager to have the additional time for preseason 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year I really didn't care that much. With all the young  
guys we have, we'll try to give them the opportunity to play in the 
games and see how they do,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana reached the Eastern Conference finals for the fourth  
time in six seasons. However, the dream of making its first trip to 
the NBA finals came up short when Indiana was upset by the New York 
Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope the players will be in the right frame of mind and  
go to work,'' said Bird, who plans to hold 11 practice sessions 
this week before the Pacers leave the Disney Institute in Orlando 
on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was a strange season. We really didn't have a great  
training camp. It didn't seem like we were playing well on a 
consistent basis. We really didn't have time to prepare in 
practice,'' he said. ``This year we have no excuses. We need to go 
into camp in the right frame of mind and come out of camp ready to 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Preseason forecasts last season tabbed Indiana as a championship  
favorite, a role Bird believed they had the talent to achieve. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt I wanted to put as much pressure on them as I could,  
work them hard, keep them focused. We played well the first two 
series and (against) New York we didn't play well at all. We just 
didn't have players step up and play to their capabilities,'' Bird 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't win the whole thing, it's very disappointing.  
Last year was a great opportunity for us to go out, make it to the 
finals, give ourselves an opportunity for a championship. We came 
up short.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bird has his starting lineup intact. All five members are over  
30 and have been in the league 11 or more seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a year older,'' Bird said. ``Whatever happened last year  
is gone and you've got to move forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The big change this season is the trade to Toronto of Antonio  
Davis, who provided crucial minutes at power forward and backup 
center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Losing Antonio Davis, a guy who played two positions, is going  
to hurt us,'' Bird said. ``I think we have enough to keep it 
going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers acquired Jonathan Bender, an 18-year-old high school  
star from Mississippi who was the fifth overall pick in the draft, 
from the Raptors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bender is probably not going to play much,'' Bird said of the  
6-foot-11 rookie. ``It's a learning experience for him. He has a 
lot of talent, he's young. For the future, I can see the move they 
made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest battle for a starting job is likely to be at small  
forward, where 36-year-old Chris Mullin will be challenged by a 
group that includes former first-round draft picks Al Harrington 
and Austin Croshere, and this year's 21st overall, Jeff Foster, 
acquired from Golden State in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pretty loaded at the small forward position. The last  
two years we've been with Chris the whole time. You can't count him 
out,'' Bird said. ``If he comes out of camp the best small forward, 
he'll start. If not, someone else will.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
