<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 18:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utah Wins 'Greatest' Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- In the early 1960s, Tom Korologos needed a  
headline in a hurry for an advertising tabloid on skiing. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I put down, `The greatest snow on earth,''' said Korologos,  
then an editor for the Salt Lake Tribune and now a Washington 
lobbyist. ``The next thing I knew, the state tourist council 
grabbed it and ran with it. The phrase stuck, and then it appeared 
on license plates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus had copyrighted  
the phrase ``the greatest show on earth'' in 1872 and objected to 
Utah's similar-sounding claim. 
</P>
<P>
	The world-famous circus unsuccessfully tried to block Utah from  
obtaining its own trademark in 1988, then took its case to the 
federal courts in 1996 after Congress enacted the Federal Trademark 
Dilution Act. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to take up Ringling  
Bros.' appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's finally over,'' said Spencer Kinard, assistant director  
for the Utah Travel Council, who argues ``the greatest snow on 
earth'' is a fact, not a ripoff. ``We never stopped using it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ringling Bros. was disappointed. Julie Strauss, vice president  
and corporate counsel for Ringling Bros.' modern owner, Feld 
Entertainment, said, ```The greatest show on earth' is one of our 
most important corporate assets. We vigorously protect this 
trademark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Had Ringling Bros. prevailed, Utah would have had to drop  
bragging rights from advertising copy, travel guides and maps and 
possibly even recall license plates. 
</P>
<P>
	Kinard says Ringling Bros. was particularly concerned about a  
door being opened for such claims as the greatest bar on earth or 
greatest car on earth. 
</P>
<P>
	``At one time they said, `We will go to the ends of the earth to  
stop you from using this phrase,''' said Ralph Finlayson, assistant 
Utah attorney general who defended Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Ringling's case against Utah backfired when its own consumer  
survey failed to prove that consumers were confused by the similar 
slogans, a federal appeals court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah, moreover, had enlisted meteorologist Jerry Brown to lend a  
scientific basis to its claim. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 inches of snow blanket Utah's northern mountains  
annually. And thanks to the combined effects of the desert and the 
Great Salt Lake, winter storms dispersing dry, powdery snow often 
linger for days over Wasatch Mountain resorts. 
</P>
<P>
	Korologus, 66, says there is no question Utah has the world's  
finest powder snow. He was surprised to hear Ringling Bros. took 
its case to the nation's highest court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never won a case at the Supreme Court before,'' he quipped.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
