<DOCNO> APW19991004.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 07:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Won't Halt ``Greatest Snow'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to stop Utah  
from bragging about ``the greatest snow on earth,'' a phrase the 
Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus says illegally dilutes 
its ``Greatest Show on Earth'' trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's highest court, without comment, rejected an appeal  
filed by lawyers for the world-famous circus. The justices let 
stand rulings that threw out a 1996 lawsuit aimed at getting Utah 
to stop using the trademarked phrase to promote its winter sports 
attractions. 
</P>
<P>
	P.T. Barnum's circus held the ``Greatest Show'' trademark since  
1872, long before it merged with the Ringling Circus in 1919. Utah 
has used the ``greatest snow'' trademark since the 1960s, but that 
practice was challenged by the circus after Congress enacted the 
Federal Trademark Dilution Act of 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Until that law was passed, federal trademark law protected only  
against trademark infringements. The 1995 law protects owners of 
``famous'' trademarks ``against another person's commercial use ... 
of a mark or trade name if such use ... causes dilution of the 
distinctive quality of the mark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The act defines dilution as the lessening of the capacity of a  
famous mark to identify and distinguish goods or services, 
regardless of any competition between the two trademark owners or 
the likelihood of public confusion. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge in Alexandria, Va., and the 4th U.S. Circuit  
Court of Appeals threw out the circus' lawsuit before it reached a 
jury, ruling that no trademark dilution had occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Proof of dilution requires a showing of ``actual economic harm  
to the famous mark's economic value by lessening its former selling 
power,'' the appeals court ruled last March, adding that the circus 
had not offered such proof. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the circus said the  
4th Circuit court's ruling conflicts with other federal appeals 
courts' interpretation of the 1995 federal law. But Utah's lawyers 
said no such conflict exists. 
</P>
<P>
	The circus' appeal was supported in a friend-of-the-court brief  
submitted by companies holding famous trademarks, including Revlon, 
John Deere, Listerine, Harley-Davidson, Newsweek, Tide, Disney and 
Bank of America. 
</P>
<P>
	The brief said the 4th Circuit court's ruling wrongly makes it  
harder to stop dilution than it is to stop infringement of a 
trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Combined Shows  
vs. Utah Division of Travel Development, 98-2004. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 00:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Can Anything Save Broncos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	After the New York Jets got their first win at the expense of  
Mike Shanahan's winless Denver Broncos, Bill Parcells ran around 
the field at Mile High Stadium looking for Shanahan. When he 
finally found him, Parcells pulled the Denver coach aside and 
whispered in his ear. 
</P>
<P>
	Ah yes, advice from the coach who's 1-3 to the one who's 0-4.  
</P>
<P>
	It was long overdue.  
</P>
<P>
	In March 1988 at the NFL meetings in Phoenix, Al Davis, who had  
just hired Shanahan to coach his Raiders, introduced his then 
35-year-old coach to his good friend Parcells, who graciously 
welcomed the new member of the NFL's coaching fraternity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you need help,'' Parcells said as they shook hands,  
``just call me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Who knows if Shanahan ever called? His tenure with the Raiders  
lasted just 16 games because he didn't follow Davis' coaching 
instructions, and when he went to Denver, he managed two Super Bowl 
victories without Parcells' help, beating the Jets in the AFC title 
game last season. 
</P>
<P>
	But he won't win a third Super Bowl this season -- only the 1995  
Chargers have ever started 0-4 and made it to the playoffs. That's 
not something the Broncos are likely to repeat, particularly if 
Terrell Davis' knee injury as is serious as first believed. 
</P>
<P>
	None of this was expected two months ago, when the Broncos  
opened camp confident they could become the first team ever to win 
three straight Super Bowls. Rod Smith even wore `3' instead of `80' 
in training camp, and the party line was that Bubby Brister, 4-0 in 
place of John Elway last season, could replace Elway without a 
problem, particularly with the NFL as watered-down as it proved to 
be. 
</P>
<P>
	How wrong everyone was.  
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, people forgot how good Elway was, even with his  
numbers declining as Davis took over the offensive load. They also 
forgot his leadership skills. 
</P>
<P>
	For another, they forgot how important Steve Atwater's  
leadership was to the defense, even as his speed and ability to 
covers receivers declined. Atwater returned to Mile High Stadium 
with the Jets Sunday and made the tackle that stopped Denver's last 
serious drive in New York's 21-13 win. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, everything that was supposed to be positive for Denver  
has turned negative. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale Carter, for example, was signed during the offseason to  
solidify the secondary. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter, as he was in Kansas City, has been spotty, great on one  
play, awful on the next. His pass interference penalty set up the 
go-ahead touchdown in Sunday's game, and his influence on his 
teammates can be as negative as Atwater's was positive. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, after Brister was spotty in exhibition games, Shanahan  
decided to go to Griese, the second-year man who threw just three 
passes as a rookie. Griese doesn't have the arm of either Elway or 
Brister, allowing teams to stack defenses to stop Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Griese was finally lifted for Brister after throwing  
three interceptions, including one on which Davis was injured 
making the tackle. Brister threw two more interceptions in 
desperation time, but at least he looked like he had been there 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan's postgame comments were the usual coachspeak -- the  
stuff about being unable to convert in the red zone and having too 
many turnovers. Parcells' were just as predictable -- about winning 
ugly and not committing the dumb penalties that have hurt the team 
since Vinny Testaverde was injured in the opening half of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's probably too bad that Parcells whispered to Shanahan  
without anyone listening in. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe he was giving him some important advice he promised 11  
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Shanahan probably wasn't listening.  
</P>
<P>
	He's got problems even Parcells can't solve.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
