<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lou Dobbs To Work With NBC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lou Dobbs, who gained a following as CNN's  
financial news anchor, then quit amid reports of a dispute with 
management, has joined NBC but will largely stay on the radio for 
now. 
</P>
<P>
	Dobbs appeared on NBC's ``Today'' show today, saying he would  
put out a financial newsletter with NBC and be host of a radio 
program for the network. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're together going to create a newsletter on markets,  
finance, and the political economy, if you will, (and) provide some 
monthly insight for folks who are watching these somewhat turbulent 
markets,'' Dobbs said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's for investors who are looking for a little more insight  
or perspective than they might get day to day. We're looking 
forward to it,'' Dobbs said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal also sets up a potential future television relationship  
between Dobbs and NBC once his three-year no-compete clause with 
CNN expires, The New York Times reported today. The clause prevents 
him from taking a job with any other television entity. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Times said he is able to sidestep the clause for now by  
appearing on NBC and its cable financial news outlet, CNBC, as a 
guest to promote his newsletter and radio program. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by host Matt Lauer ``are we OK here,'' because of the  
no-compete clause, Dobbs replied, ``Of course we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dobbs left CNN in June, saying he planned to launch Space.com, a  
Web site devoted to informing users about outer space. He said last 
week that the Web site was still a priority but he also was 
pursuing offers for other ventures, the Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly before his departure from CNN, Dobbs was involved in an  
unusually public spat with CNN president Rick Kaplan. A visibly 
unhappy Dobbs interrupted ``Moneyline'' so CNN could show a 
presidential news conference and told viewers it was under Kaplan's 
orders. 
</P>
<P>
	It prompted a Kaplan deputy to issue memos stating that CNN's  
executive producers have the authority to break into ``Moneyline'' 
to cover news when warranted. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his CNN duties, Dobbs was president of CNN's  
financial network, CNNfn. It has run a distant second in influence 
to NBC's CNBC, the cable leader in business news. But Dobbs' early 
evening ``Moneyline'' on CNN drew more than twice as many viewers 
as CNBC's competing ``Business Center.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
