<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Far-Right Party Makes Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- A party whose leader once praised the  
Hitler era appears to have captured second place in Austrian 
national elections -- the best-ever showing for any far right party 
in Europe since the end of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The Freedom Party's second-place showing -- which could change  
with 200,000 absentee ballots still to be counted -- leaves no party 
with an absolute majority, putting Joerg Haider's Freedom Party in 
a powerful position in the formulation of a government coalition. 
The election's final results will be announced next week. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Sunday's provisional results, Haider's party won 27  
percent, 5 percent more than in the last election and the party's 
best showing since its founding in 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is terrible, it is frightening ... the world has not  
learned from its history,'' said Israeli Justice Minister Yossi 
Beilin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian newspaper Corriere della Sera's front page carried  
an editorial cartoon with a figure of Hitler raising his right hand 
and yelling ``Sieg Haider.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the French Catholic daily La Croix, which described Haider  
as ``chancellor apprentice'' and a ``macho,'' explained Haider's 
success as an ``authoritarian populism `made in Austria.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor Viktor Klima's Social Democratic Party remained in  
first place, with 34 percent of the vote. The conservative Austrian 
People's Party of Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel dropped to 
third place with 27 percent, only 14,000 votes behind the Freedom 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	The Social Democrats, the senior government coalition party for  
the past 13 years, have ruled out working with Haider's party 
because of its rightist policies. The Peoples' Party, the 
Socialists' coalition partner, have announced they would go into 
the opposition if they came in third. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless these positions change, Austria faces weeks of political  
uncertainty and the possibility of new elections if a viable 
government cannot be formed. 
</P>
<P>
	Haider, 51, said his party had ``risen with a sensational  
election result.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer by training, the telegenic Haider has gained ground by  
addressing people's grievances in powerful and often strident 
speeches. He also appealed to fears among small business people and 
workers that European Union expansion into the former Soviet bloc 
could put jobs at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Austria is Europe's third most prosperous nation. The crime rate  
is low, and there has been no social or ethnic strife since the end 
of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Austrians feel a need for change. Much of Haider's  
popularity is based on the alienation many wage earners feel under 
the two ruling parties' high taxes and other policies. He has 
lambasted the stifling bureaucracy and ``fat paychecks'' of 
government officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Haider's success likely will be frowned upon abroad. He is best  
known for having praised Adolf Hitler's employment policies and for 
having called veterans of the Nazi Waffen SS ``men of character.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Freedom Party's campaign was dominated by calls to stop  
immigration -- posters in Vienna, the capital, warn against 
``over-foreignization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haider has also promised generous child care checks and other  
benefits that other parties say cannot be financed. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring a major change in the results from the absentee ballots,  
the Social Democrats will hold 65 seats in parliament, the Freedom 
Party 53 seats and the People's Party 52. The Greens, who won 7 
percent, will have 13 seats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
