<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Leader Will Testify on His Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch is  
ready to appear before Congress -- on his terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch says he's not available to testify at a congressional  
hearing this month because he's busy overseeing the reforms of the 
scandal-tainted Olympic movement. But he said he's prepared to go 
to Capitol Hill as soon as the reforms are adopted by the 
International Olympic Committee in December. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ready to go, but only in the right moment,'' Samaranch  
said. ``I have to walk into the House with the changes in my 
pocket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision, announced Sunday at the close of a three-day IOC  
executive board meeting in Athens, allowed Samaranch to seize the 
political initiative and defuse the hostilities with his Washington 
critics. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said the IOC will ``fully cooperate'' with Rep. Fred  
Upton, who requested that he appear at an Oct. 14 hearing into 
excesses related to Atlanta's winning bid for the 1996 Summer 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I welcome, indeed seek, the opportunity to inform you and your  
colleagues,'' Samaranch said in a letter to Upton. 
</P>
<P>
	Upton had threatened to subpoena Samaranch if he refused to  
testify voluntarily before the House commerce subcommittee on 
oversight and investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch declined to appear last April when the Senate held  
hearings prompted by the Salt Lake City vote-buying scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch told Upton that his immediate priority is pushing  
through reforms aimed at restoring the image and credibility of the 
IOC after its worst crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Describing the reform process as ``extremely important and  
time-consuming,'' Samaranch said: ``It is essential that I work 
full time to generate the required consensus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am sure you will understand that my primary responsibility  
in these circumstances must rest with the need to ensure that our 
reforms proceed as planned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Samaranch said he would appear before Upton's committee  
any time after the Dec. 11-12 session at which the IOC will vote on 
sweeping reforms of its structure, rules and procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Apart from my inability to come to the United States earlier,  
this would also provide the most suitable opportunity to give you 
the best and most complete information, not only on what went 
wrong, but also and above all, on what remedies are being put into 
place,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, a Spaniard, said he will need a Spanish interpreter  
at the hearing ``to avoid any misunderstanding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he would welcome a visit by Upton to IOC  
headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said he would ask the two IOC members in the United  
States, Anita DeFrantz and Jim Easton, and IOC director general 
Francois Carrard to be available to testify at the Oct. 14 hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	In its latest move toward reform, the IOC announced in Athens  
that it has asked to be governed by an international anti-bribery 
convention. Reforms in the works also include new rules on age 
limits, terms of office and the bidding and site selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	``In every crisis, you find a positive side, sometimes very  
small,'' Samaranch said at a news conference. ``This crisis gave us 
the possibility to change many things in our organization. It will 
allow us to present a new, younger and renovated IOC to the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Upton has called the hearing to investigate what he described as  
a ``culture of corruption'' surrounding Atlanta's bid. 
</P>
<P>
	A report submitted to his panel last month detailed gifts,  
travel, favors and offers of college scholarships and job 
assistance to IOC members and their families from the Atlanta bid 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Upton said the report, prepared by former Attorney General  
Griffin Bell, proved ``votes were for sale'' and accused the IOC of 
fostering a corrupt bid culture. 
</P>
<P>
	But Samaranch said Sunday: ``I think the Bell report is very  
clear. It says there was no corruption. There are things that you 
can find in the report that are not as important as what happened 
in Salt Lake City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has forwarded the Atlanta report to the IOC's new  
ethics commission, which will determine whether any IOC members 
committed wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Samaranch said the IOC will decide in December whether to go  
ahead with a scheduled executive board meeting in Colorado Springs 
and Salt Lake City in February. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC has cited a possible ``scheduling conflict'' that could  
force the U.S. meetings to be postponed. Some IOC members are 
reluctant to travel to the United States because they could face 
questioning by FBI agents investigating the Salt Lake scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The executive board said it was pressing ahead with its plans  
for a world anti-doping agency. The agency will be set up by the 
end of October and be operational by Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said the agency will be based in Lausanne, defying the  
critics who say it should be totally independent of the IOC. While 
the head of the agency hasn't been appointed yet, Samaranch said it 
definitely won't be the IOC president. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch took a conciliatory line toward White House drug  
policy adviser Barry McCaffrey, who has been harshly critical of 
the IOC and its anti-doping project. 
</P>
<P>
	``I respect (McCaffrey) very much,'' he said. ``If he wants one  
day to cooperate with us, (the door) will be open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Salt Lake City organizers received IOC approval for their  
proposal to set aside for Utah residents 20 percent of the 887,000 
tickets for the 2002 Winter Games. The IOC said Salt Lake City's 
proposal to auction some tickets over the Internet needed more 
study. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
