<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Eyes 'Tracking' Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp., irked by a slumping stock price,  
reportedly may create separate ``tracking'' stocks to reflect the 
value of different businesses such as the company's cable and 
wireless operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Any such plan would likely have to wait until after AT&AMP;T  
completes its acquisition of the cable TV company MediaOne Group, 
expected sometime next year, The Wall Street Journal said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate over tracking stocks follows a recent 25 percent  
slide in AT&AMP;T's share price that some executives blame on confusion 
over how to value such a wide array of businesses, especially after 
the company's sudden foray into cable television. 
</P>
<P>
	One plan being discussed calls for three new stocks representing  
AT&AMP;T's wireless unit, its cable and Internet ventures, and its 
outsourcing unit for businesses, the Journal said, citing people 
familiar with the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's board was scheduled to hold its annual strategy session  
in September, when the tracking-stock possibility was expected to 
be discussed, but that meeting was delayed until later this month 
because of Hurricane Floyd, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the nation's largest long-distance company declined  
to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	A new tracking stock wouldn't represent an ownership interest in  
any of the AT&AMP;T units, which would still be reflected by AT&AMP;T's 
common stock. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, a tracking stock represents a stake in a specific  
division's financial performance. That way, an investor can choose 
whether to focus on an established, lower-risk business such as 
AT&AMP;T long-distance calling, or the company's high-priced gamble on 
using cable TV systems to deliver telephone and Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, a fast-growing business, even if it generates  
little or no profits, can generally command a higher premium on 
Wall Street if it is not masked within a larger corporation. One 
recent success story that may inspire AT&AMP;T is Sprint PCS, the 
wireless company that has far outperformed corporate parent Sprint 
since the tracking stock was launched last year. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's reported discussions come less than a year after the  
company scuttled plans to create separate stocks for its wireless 
business and recently acquired cable operations. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, and for months to come, AT&AMP;T's shares were soaring  
amid enthusiasm over a $140 billion spending spree highlighted by 
the takeover of cable giant Tele-Communications Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, however, investors have grown wary of the  
billions of dollars more that will need to be spent on upgrading 
and expanding the company's cable and wireless infrastructure. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of AT&AMP;T closed up $2, or 4.8 percent, at $43.75 on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
