<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted Reporter Loses Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former radio reporter convicted and  
sentenced to death for the 1981 killing of a Philadelphia policeman 
lost a Supreme Court appeal today. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away arguments that Mumia  
Abu-Jamal was denied a fair trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal's jailhouse writings about the justice system  
attracted worldwide attention. Thousands of supporters have staged 
demonstrations in Philadelphia to demand a new trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pennsylvania Supreme Court twice upheld Abu-Jamal's  
conviction and death sentence, most recently last year. The state 
court found no merit in the various arguments his lawyers raised. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal, a onetime Black Panther and radio journalist, was  
convicted of fatally shooting Philadelphia police officer Daniel 
Falkner, who was shot after stopping Abu-Jamal's brother for 
driving the wrong way down a city street. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal was found wounded at the murder scene. He has denied  
shooting Falkner, contending he was framed. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeal acted on today raised three legal arguments, none of  
which focused on Abu-Jamal's claim of innocence. But his lawyers 
did tell the justices about ``an array of evidence powerfully 
supporting his longstanding insistence that he is victim of a 
monumental injustice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The appeal centered on these claims:  
</P>
<P>
	--Abu-Jamal wrongly was stripped of his right to represent  
himself during his trial's jury-selection phase. 
</P>
<P>
	--He wrongly was removed from the courtroom after disrupting the  
trial proceedings, a violation of his right to confront the 
witnesses against him. 
</P>
<P>
	--He wrongly was excluded from a meeting in which the trial judge  
disqualified a sequestered juror who secretly had gone home to tend 
a sick cat. 
</P>
<P>
	``The prosecution's theory of the case was never placed within  
the crucible of meaningful adversarial testing such that the 
resulting verdict engenders confidence that justice was done,'' the 
appeal said. 
</P>
<P>
	State prosecutors urged the justices to reject Abu-Jamal's  
appeal. They said he killed Faulkner ``by cold-bloodedly shooting 
him in the face as the officer lay helpless on the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While today's action frees state prosecutors to seek an  
execution date, Abu-Jamal is not likely to be executed any time 
soon. He still can challenge his state court conviction in federal 
courts, a process that someday could lead back to the Supreme 
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Abu-Jamal vs. Pennsylvania, 98-1702.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 02:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Radio City Restoration Complete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- All that glitters is gold again at Radio City  
Music Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	From its 3,000-pound gold silk curtain and scalloped sunburst  
ceiling to Depression-era artwork that has been hidden for decades 
under layers of grit and grime, the New York landmark visited by 
millions each year has been restored to its former Art Deco 
grandeur. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sparkling jewel once again,'' said Bob Russo, chairman  
of the restoration committee and general manager of Madison Square 
Garden, whose parent company Cablevision has a 25-year lease on the 
building and owns Radio City Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	The $70 million, seven-month restoration project was to be  
unveiled tonight at a benefit for the Lustgarten Foundation for 
Pancreatic Cancer. The event, which was to feature Billy Crystal, 
Ann-Margret, Sting, Tony Bennett, Ann Miller and Raquel Welch, will 
be aired on NBC on Dec. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first major renovation of the building since it opened  
Dec. 27, 1932. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers replaced all six miles of the faded neon lights on the  
hall's famous marquee, rewired 1,500 chandeliers and re-insulated 
walls to improve the acoustics. All 5,901 seats were reupholstered. 
</P>
<P>
	Once considered the largest indoor theater and most modern  
structure of its time, the hall aged badly. Burnt out ceiling 
lights went unchanged, antiques were placed in storage rather than 
repaired, carpets and seats became shabby. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1970s, the once grand lady of performance halls -- in debt  
and losing audiences with its tired formula of family movies and a 
stage show -- was nearly demolished. Saved by the wrecking ball 
after the city declared it an architectural landmark in 1979, a new 
management team was brought in and the hall slowly rebounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, nearly 2 million people visited Radio City.  
</P>
<P>
	The most Herculean effort in the restoration came in restoring  
the hall's artwork, which includes the 60-by-40 foot ``Fountain of 
Youth'' mural painted by Ezra Winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, Russo said, the work got darker as layers of  
smoke and grime built up. It was made worse when someone decided to 
coat the artwork with polyurethane, sealing in the dirt and turning 
the painting yellow. 
</P>
<P>
	Art experts, using Q-tips, tiny scalpels and cotton squares  
restored the mural that graces the staircase leading to the 
mezzanine. 
</P>
<P>
	Eileen Collins, dance captain of the hall's signature Rockettes,  
said the sight of the restored theater moved her to tears. ``When I 
saw the theater, I felt like crying; especially when I thought of 
what almost was.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 14:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Davis Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Terrell Davis, the NFL's MVP last year, will miss  
the rest of the season because of a knee injury, a devastating blow 
to a championship team already reeling from four straight losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Denver Broncos' running back tore ligaments and cartilage in  
his right knee while making a tackle Sunday during the first 
quarter of a 21-13 loss to the New York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to him and he's in as good as spirits as he could  
possibly be in,'' coach Mike Shanahan said today. ``He's working 
through it right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis is expected to be out four to six months and make a full  
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, with the ACL and the advancements they've made in  
technology, you never know for sure,'' Shanahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach said Derek Loville will start in place of Davis. This  
is the third season he has backed up Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan, whose winless team is clearly diminished by the  
retirement of John Elway, will also review his quarterbacks. Brian 
Griese, who replaced Bubby Brister during preseason, threw three 
interceptions Sunday. Brister entered late in the fourth quarter 
and threw two interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, who led the NFL in rushing last season with 2,008 yards,  
has been off to a slow start. He was hurt during an interception 
return by Jets safety Victor Green. 
</P>
<P>
	Broncos offensive tackle Matt Lepsis made a diving tackle to cut  
down Green at the sideline, but Lepsis also caught Davis, trailing 
the play slightly, on his right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis was assisted by trainers on the sideline, then limped to  
the locker room. He did not return. 
</P>
<P>
	After Davis' departure, the Broncos scored only a field goal.  
Davis rushed for 18 yards on eight carries. For the season, he has 
211 yards. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 22:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Kids May Smoke To Lose Weight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Children who want to lose weight are more likely  
to experiment with cigarettes, researchers reported in this month's 
issue of the journal Pediatrics. 
</P>
<P>
	``In both boys and girls we found children who thought about  
(smoking) were more likely to be concerned about their weight,'' 
said one of the study's authors, Dr. Alison Field of Harvard 
Medical School and Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston. ``And 
those who were doing something to lose weight were more likely to 
smoke than those who were not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study looked at more than 16,000 children, ages 9 to 14.  
</P>
<P>
	They were asked questions about their weight, including what, if  
anything, they were doing to lose weight. They were also asked if 
they smoked or considered smoking. About 6 percent of the 
youngsters were contemplating smoking cigarettes and 9 percent had 
smoked. 
</P>
<P>
	``Girls who were unhappy with their appearance were twice as  
likely to think about using tobacco,'' Field said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The study did not directly ask the children if any actually  
smoked to lose weight, because ``we didn't want them to think we 
were suggesting this is a way to lose weight,'' Field said. 
Instead, the youngsters were asked separate questions regarding 
weight loss and smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	Boys who exercised daily to lose weight were 90 percent more  
likely to have experimented with cigarettes than those who did not, 
Field said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the Journal of Clinical Investigation published a study  
that found moderate smoking helps the body burn fat. But the 
researchers also warned that smoking shouldn't be considered a 
substitute for dieting because it was a greater health risk than 
the added weight. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Michael Jellinek, the chief of child psychiatry at  
Massachusetts General Hospital, said that although he doesn't 
believe the main reason children smoke is to lose weight, it is a 
factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there is a tremendous amount of pressure to fit the  
societal stereotype of being very thin, and smoking fits into 
that,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 20:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bucks' Camp Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. FRANCIS, Wis. (AP) -- George Karl thinks the Milwaukee Bucks  
can turn their honeymoon season into a long and successful 
relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bucks, fresh off their first playoff berth since 1991, were  
all smiles in the first get-together at their suburban training 
center on Monday. They had good reason to be: for the first time 
this decade, Milwaukee has a legitimate chance to advance beyond 
the first round of the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like the mix of elements we've got here,'' said Karl, whose  
rookie season in Milwaukee was the best by any coach in franchise 
history. ``We're a little old, a little new, a little borrowed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And not the least bit blue.  
</P>
<P>
	Milwaukee's surge to a 28-22 record last season was a sign the  
perennially moribund franchise was on the way up for the first time 
since the Don Nelson era. 
</P>
<P>
	Karl said his task for the coming season is to merge Milwaukee's  
new arrivals with its talented, youthful returning core of 
starters. The Bucks have a week of camp in St. Francis before their 
exhibition schedule starts in Toronto on Oct. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each year it gets better and better for us,'' said Glenn  
Robinson, who's entering his sixth season in Milwaukee. ``We have 
more depth than we did last year, and the players we've got want to 
win more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offseason didn't start well, with Michael Curry and Dell  
Curry leaving the team via free agency. Those departures were among 
the factors that got general manager Bob Weinhauer fired and former 
Knicks GM and Bucks player Ernie Grunfeld hired as his replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld, who built the New York team that made the NBA Finals  
last June, did a startlingly efficient job of filling Milwaukee's 
holes while not tearing apart the team's youthful starting lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	He replaced 3-point specialist Dell Curry with veteran Dale  
Ellis, a more consistent shooter. He resisted the urge to trade 
Robinson, whom Karl expects to have a breakout year. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld couldn't address the Bucks' need for a big-time center,  
but he did the next-best thing, acquiring several players whose 
combined efforts could help. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we obviously needed to get bigger and tougher, and I  
think we did that,'' Grunfeld said. ``It won't be center by 
committee, but we'll have a solid front line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bucks left last year's first-round playoff sweep by the  
Indiana Pacers convinced they needed a more physical inside 
presence that could play defense and improve the numbers of the 
second worst rebounding team in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Enter Danny Manning, J.R. Reid and a healthy Scott Williams, all  
of whom should help Tim Thomas and Ervin Johnson to match up with 
bigger teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got pushed around a few times last year,'' Karl said.  
``That won't happen as much this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karl lobbied hard for the acquisition of Reid, particularly  
after attempts to pry young center Kelvin Cato from the Portland 
Trail Blazers failed. Karl called Reid several times during the 
offseason and sold the unrestricted free agent on the Bucks' 
potential. 
</P>
<P>
	``You look around this room, and we've got most of the tools we  
need to succeed, if not all the tools,'' shooting guard Ray Allen 
said. ``Now it's a matter of us playing together and getting to 
know each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the best addition to the opening-day lineup will be Sam  
Cassell, who was acquired from New Jersey in March but played just 
four regular season games with Milwaukee because of an ankle 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	During the offseason, Cassell lost 15 pounds and worked to  
regain the quick step that made him one of the league's top point 
guards with Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	While Karl said a forecast of a 50-win season was ``a little bit  
on the optimistic side,'' at least one new Buck isn't so sure. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a nice mix of players,'' Reid said. ``The way the  
league is so equal right now, who knows what we can do?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 20:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
