<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Idaho Farmers Seek Water District / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IDAHO FALLS, Idaho (AP) -- Upping the ante in a fight over one of  
the West's most valuable commodities, Idaho farmers in Bonneville 
and Jefferson counties who irrigate by pumping from an aquifer are 
organizing to protect their water rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioners last week approved an ordinance allowing farmers  
in Bonneville and Jefferson counties in central Idaho to vote on 
whether they want to create a groundwater district. Some farmers 
think the district will help protect their water rights in the face 
of increasing challenges, primarily from farmers in the Magic 
Valley area who irrigate from the river. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Taylor of Osgood hopes to get the issue on the November  
ballot but the farmers may have to wait until next February to vote 
to create the district and staff its three-member board. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers in the Twin Falls Canal Co. and the Northside Canal Co.  
have filed a complaint in the Snake River Basin Adjudication Court 
alleging farmers from American Falls north to Madison County are 
pumping too much water from the aquifer. They say groundwater 
pumping depletes spring flows into the Snake River near American 
Falls, which means less water for them. That case is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Idaho's Snake River Basin Adjudication is the largest in the  
history of the West. It started in the mid-1980s and affects about 
180,000 water rights throughout southern and central Idaho. It 
already has cost over $30 million and is expected to cost an 
additional $20 million or more. 
</P>
<P>
	Creation of a groundwater district will allow farmers to  
organize and assess a levy to pay for attorneys and hydrologists to 
respond to the Magic Valley farmers' claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will allow the groundwater users to act in a united  
fashion to solve problems and to respond to threats to their water 
rights,'' Taylor said. 
</P>
<P>
	It will also allow farmers to measure how much water is being  
taken from the aquifer. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to a complaint, the Legislature passed a law for the  
formation of Groundwater Measurement Districts. Four districts were 
created covering the eastern Idaho Snake River plain. 
</P>
<P>
	But if they create a groundwater district, farmers within the  
proposed boundaries of the Bonneville-Jefferson Water District 
could hire their own hydrologist to conduct their own measurements. 
</P>
<P>
	Norm Semanko, a Twin Falls attorney representing Magic Valley  
surface water irrigators, is not troubled by the creation of 
groundwater districts. In fact, he encourages it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we've got someone we can sit and talk to,'' Semanko said.  
``Up until just two or three years ago, all we had was a disparate 
pack of thousands of water users.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texans will receive nearly 10 percent of the  
more than $1.3 billion being doled out by the Agriculture 
Department under a federal conservation program that pays producers 
not to plant crops on their environmentally sensitive land. 
</P>
<P>
	The Agriculture Department on Monday announced the payment  
schedule, which averages $5,000 per farm or $45.15 per acre. 
</P>
<P>
	``The CRP is ... has reduced soil erosion and expanded wildlife  
habitat while improving air and water quality, restoring wetlands 
and encouraging tree planting,'' Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman 
said. ``And at the same time, it has strengthened farm income.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas has more acres enrolled in the CRP, 3.6 million, than any  
other state. Texas producers will receive $130 million in rental 
payments for September and October, USDA said, second only to 
Iowa's $137 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the program, producers voluntarily retire environmentally  
sensitive land for 10 to 15 years. In return, they receive annual 
rental payments. Enrolled land must be highly erodible, contribute 
to a serious water quality problem or provide substantial 
environmental benefits if devoted to certain specific conservation 
uses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
