<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Travel Firms To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Travelocity.com, a Texas online airline  
reservation service, and America Online's primary travel partner 
have agreed to form a new company in a multimillion-dollar merger, 
officials of both companies say today. 
</P>
<P>
	Fort Worth, Texas-based Travelocity, a 3-year-old online airline  
reservation service, takes in $9 million a week in revenue and has 
provided hundreds of jobs in the San Antonio area and Dallas-Fort 
Worth. It will combine with Preview Travel Inc., to form a new 
company headquartered in Fort Worth. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said the merger would create a new powerhouse  
in the online travel market, which is the largest retail e-commerce 
category. It is projected to grow from $7.8 billion in 1999 to 
$32.1 billion by 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Travelocity's owner, Sabre Inc., will contribute the assets of  
its online reservations division plus $50 million in cash in 
exchange for 70 percent ownership in the new company, formed as a 
Delaware limited partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	Current Preview Travel stockholders will hold 30 percent of the  
combined entity through a new corporate entity, Travelocity.com 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the new company will benefit from a new,  
five-year contract with America Online Inc. It will make 
Travelocity.com exclusive reservations engine for all 
travel-related services within the AOL service, AOL.COM, 
CompuServe, Digital City and Netscape. 
</P>
<P>
	Terrell B. Jones, the president of Travelocity.com, will be  
president and chief executive officer of the new company. Donald J. 
Carty, chairman of Sabre Inc., will serve as chairman of the board 
until a new Sabre chief executive officer is named. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new Travelocity.com will bring together the very best of  
Travelocity and Preview Travel -- two successful and talented 
organizations -- to create an unparalleled combination of content 
and innovative services to online consumers,'' Jones said in a 
prepared statement. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, Sabre Inc. has said it too is considering an initial  
public offering for Travelocity.com, where customers can buy plane 
tickets and other travel services over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Boards of directors at both Sabre and Preview Travel have  
approved the merger, which is expected to close in first quarter 
2000. But the deal is subject to regulatory approval, customary 
closing conditions and requires approval by Preview Travel's 
stockholders. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the largest online travel sites, Travelocity.com had $301  
million in gross travel sales for the first half of 1999, exceeding 
the total $285 million it recorded for all of 1998. Travelocity.com 
has more than eight million registered members. 
</P>
<P>
	Preview Travel is a leading online travel site with nine million  
registered members and reported gross bookings of $200.1 million in 
1998 and $166.7 million in the first half of 1999. Preview Travel 
offers integrated travel content and services to AOL's 18 million 
subscribers. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
