<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Oct. 4, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg Back on Supreme Court  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As the Supreme Court opened its 1999-2000 term  
today, Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg was on the bench. 
Ginsburg had surgery for colon cancer just 17 days ago. The court 
issued a flurry of orders, including allowing Knox County, Tenn., 
school officials require drug testing of everyone offered a 
teaching job. Justices turned away an argument that former radio 
reporter Mumia Abu-Jamal was denied a fair trial, and rejected a 
challenge to Arizona's program allowing up to $500 in tax credits 
for contributions for scholarships at religious and other private 
schools as a violation of the separation of church and state. 

</P>
<P>
	Groups Seek More Diversity on Court  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A coalition representing minorities and  
women's groups called for greater ethnic and gender diversity among 
Supreme Court law clerks as the court opened a new term today. 
Among the new class of 35 law clerks at work for the highest 
court's nine justices are five minority clerks -- two blacks and 
three Asian-Americans. Last year's class included one, a Hispanic. 
NAACP President Kweisi Mfume said the court still sends out the 
message that ``people of color need not apply'' for the influential 
clerkships. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Facing Test-Ban Fight  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Facing almost insurmountable odds, the Clinton  
administration is trying to round up Senate votes to ratify the 
global treaty signed three years ago to ban nuclear tests. 
President Clinton was beginning with a strategy session today with 
members of his national security team, and he will lobby senators 
in person and on the telephone this week. Even if all 45 Democratic 
senators approve the treaty, 22 Republicans would have to join them 
to provide the needed margin. The vote is set for Oct. 12. 

</P>
<P>
	Convicted Killer Captured in Mo.  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, Mo. (AP) -- A convicted killer who broke out of an  
Arkansas prison and may have killed a man for his truck was 
arrested today in Missouri, police said. Kenneth D. Williams was 
captured in southern Missouri after a high-speed chase in which a 
motorist was killed, said an Arkansas state police spokesman. 
Williams escaped from the Cummins Unit maximum-security prison in 
southeastern Arkansas yesterday, and investigators said he was 
considered a suspect in the killing of a man who was found dead 
near the prison. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Allowed To Export More Oil  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- While still deadlocked on an overall new  
policy for Iraq, the Security Council today authorized Baghdad to 
temporarily export more oil. The council unanimously adopted a 
draft resolution that slightly adjusts the U.N. oil-for-food 
program, which lets Iraq export $5.26 billion in oil over six 
months to buy food and medicine for its people suffering under 
sanctions. Iraq is expected to reach the $5.26 billion ceiling 
between Oct. 8 and 12 -- more than a month before the six-month 
period expires. Because of low oil prices and production limits, 
Iraq fell more than $3 billion short of the ceiling last year. 

</P>
<P>
	State Farm Policy Holders Get $456M  
</P>
<P>
	MARION, Ill. (AP) -- A jury today ordered the nation's largest  
auto insurer to pay $456 million for allegedly cheating customers 
by ordering body shops to use substandard repair parts. Lawyers for 
State Farm policyholders complaining about ``aftermarket parts'' 
had asked for more than $5.4 billion in damages in the class-action 
lawsuit. Critics claim such parts fail to provide the same fit, 
finish, corrosion protection and, in some cases, safety as the more 
expensive parts made for automakers. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Push Upward; Dow Up 125  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks shot higher today, with  
telecommunications issues leading the way on word that BellSouth 
joined a bidding war with MCI WorldCom for Sprint. Market watchers 
were also guessing whether the Fed will raise interest rates when 
it meets tomorrow. Only a handful of economists now figure the 
central bank will see a need to cool off the economy. Just before 
the hour, the Dow industrials were up 125.38 at 10,398.38. On the 
NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,720-1,186. The Nasdaq was up 38.64 
at 2,775.49. 

</P>
<P>
	Cubs Fire Manager Jim Riggleman  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Cubs manager Jim Riggleman was fired  
today after a season in which his team went from 90-game winners to 
last in their division despite 63 homers from Sammy Sosa. The 
dismissal came one day after the Cubs finished their season with a 
67-95 record, the second worst in the National League and the 
team's worst since 1980, not counting the strike years of 1994 and 
1981. Cubs general manager Ed Lynch said he decided to fire 
Riggleman more than a week ago. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  



  	   	
</P>
