<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 07:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Won't Revive Band's Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today sidestepped a dispute  
between a Virginia high school band director and the sheriff who 
arrested him during a parade for failing to speed up his marching 
band. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, refused to revive band director  
Robert F. Spiers' lawsuit against the sheriff who arrested him. 
</P>
<P>
	The unusual legal case began during the annual Warsaw Harvest  
Parade in Warsaw, Va., in October 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Spiers was leading the Lancaster High School Red Devils marching  
band along the parade route when band members started lagging 
behind participants in front of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Richmond County Sheriff Gene Sydnor, who was directing traffic,  
twice asked Spiers to speed up his band, saying the second time, 
``Pick up the pace or you're out of the parade.'' Spiers said he 
told the sheriff his students were going as fast as they could. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydnor grabbed a banner held by two band members and began  
turning them off the parade route. When Spiers told the band to 
keep moving toward its buses, Sydnor arrested him, handcuffed him 
and sat him on a curb. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now sit here and let everyone look at you,'' Spiers said the  
sheriff told him. Spiers was taken to police headquarters and 
released, and no charges were filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Spiers sued the sheriff, accusing him of unlawful arrest, false  
imprisonment, using excessive force and causing him emotional 
distress. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydnor sought dismissal of the lawsuit under qualified immunity,  
which protects government officials from being sued unless their 
actions violated a clearly established right. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge let Spiers' lawsuit go forward, but the 4th U.S.  
Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the case after ruling that the 
sheriff was entitled to immunity. Sydnor overreacted, but he 
reasonably could have concluded the band director was obstructing 
the sheriff's performance of his duties, the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Spiers' lawyers said Sydnor should  
have realized the arrest was unlawful. ``Failure to force a high 
school band to march faster than humanly possible is not an 
actionable offense in Virginia,'' the lawyers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Spiers vs. Sydnor, 98-1984.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 02:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chow Takes Chance With Coed Boxing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	People find out what Loi Chow will risk to make $1,500 and  
think: If he's that desperate, why not just sell a kidney? 
</P>
<P>
	But maybe he's not desperate at all.  
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe,'' said boxing trainer Vern Miller, ``he's writing a  
book or something. Who knows? I'm pretty sure he's planning to use 
this publicity for something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chow won't be the first person to gain notoriety from women's  
boxing, only the first man. Come next Saturday, the part-time 
jockey and weightlifter, who stands just a shade over 5 feet and 
weighs 125 pounds, will give new meaning to the term ``Battle of 
the Sexes.'' He will be the male half of what is believed to be the 
first professional man-woman boxing match ever in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	This is not farce, a husband-vs.-wife or  
boyfriend-vs.-girlfriend game-show stunt with ludicrously large, 
padded gloves. This is the real deal, on the undercard in Seattle's 
Mercer arena, sanctioned by the state of Washington. This will 
cross some very clear boundaries. More than pride could get hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	What Chow, 34, expects to get, he won't say. If he does win, he  
was supposed to; and if he loses, well, he apparently hasn't 
thought that far ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``This fight will be over within a minute,'' Chow boasted during  
one of his few interviews. ``The first combination I land, the 
fight will be over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, who trains the female half of the bout, isn't so sure.  
He's known 36-year-old Margaret McGregor for a while now and 
wouldn't step into the ring with the 5-5, 130-pound pro kick boxer 
himself. She turned pro last April and won all three of her bouts 
against women. The reason McGregor decided to fight a man was 
because the other women she was scheduled to fight kept ducking 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	``We went through a couple months where a couple of fights fell  
through,'' Miller recalled. ``Margaret would train to be sharp, 
then have a hard time shutting down all that excitement and 
emotion, so sometimes she'd wind up fighting exhibitions against 
guys. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then one time someone told a local promoter about a guy, a  
lightweight, who was about to turn pro. And she kept asking to 
fight this guy. So I looked at the rulebook and saw nothing against 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That ``guy'' was Hector Morales, who claims to have had 10  
fights as an amateur in Mexico. He originally took the bout, then 
dropped it. At first, Morales said he was backing out because he 
was ashamed to tell his mother he was fighting a woman. Now he says 
problems with his visa made it impossible to guarantee he could 
take the fight when it was scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	In stepped Chow, who sparred with Morales, but hasn't had a pro  
fight in three years. The good news is the layoff can't hurt him -- 
much. Chow was already a very undistinguished 0-2 during his brief 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``But Loi Chow is a better boxer even than me,'' Morales said.  
``I guarantee he will win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if he loses?  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I got to admit, I was thinking about this when I was  
going to fight,'' Morales said. ``My friends, you know, were 
kidding me about being a `woman beater.' 
</P>
<P>
	``But then I started thinking, `If I lose, I jeopardize my whole  
career. If I lose to a woman, what man is ever going to fight me 
again? But for her, it's a different story, a big, big story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's part of the problem, too. Women's boxing is already a  
big, big story, equal parts sugar and spice. 
</P>
<P>
	Mia St. John, who insiders will tell you can't break an egg, is  
12-0 against hand-picked opponents and splashed across the cover of 
Playboy magazine. Muhammad Ali's 21-year-old daughter, Laila Ali, 
makes her pro debut Friday night in Verona, New York, already 
promising knockouts in rhyme. Just this past Saturday in Las Vegas, 
on the undercard of the Julio Cesar Chavez-Willy Wise fight, 
Christy Martin, one of the racket's proven superstars, collected 
$100,000 by starching Daniella Somers in the fifth round of a 
scheduled 10-round fight. 
</P>
<P>
	For those reasons, it's no longer just the prudent or the boxing  
purists who will be covering their eyes if McGregor vs. Chow 
actually goes off as scheduled. It's people like promoter Rick 
Kulis, who runs the International Female Boxers Association and 
knows just how far spilling real blood could set his sport back. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tell him not to worry,'' Miller said.  
</P>
<P>
	He's trained a few fighters and says few of them took to it  
better than McGregor. Miller is convinced it was because she knew 
what she wanted out of it. When McGregor was little, she bit off 
the feet on her sister's Barbie dolls. As a grownup, a man she 
loved hit her. Fighting back came easy. It felt good. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all grow up with ideas and fairy tales and set roles,''  
Miller said. ``But let me tell you, Margaret is no Red Riding Hood. 
If anything, she's the big, bad wolf.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated  
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
