<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firefighters Battle Calif. Blazes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMPO, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters worked today to block two  
southern California fires burning through brush and grass, while 
lower temperatures and calmer wind elsewhere in California kept 
huge blazes for spreading. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller fires lingered in the forests of Oregon.  
</P>
<P>
	Six firefighters were injured fighting a 4-day-old fire that  
blackened 5,000 acres near the La Jolla Indian Reservation in 
northern San Diego County. One firefighter was struck by a boulder 
rolling down a slope and was hospitalized in critical condition, 
said Tony Pereira, spokesman for the California Department of 
Forestry. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind drove the fire into part of the Cleveland National Forest  
by Sunday and charred a section of Palomar Mountain. The blaze, 
which was started Thursday by a trash fire, was 40 percent 
contained Sunday night, Pereira said. 
</P>
<P>
	In southern San Diego County, a blaze near Campo, a few miles  
north of the U.S.-Mexico border, destroyed a storage building and 
charred 2,000 acres of brush. It started Sunday afternoon but the 
cause was not known, said spokeswoman Betty Hawkes. 
</P>
<P>
	Near the central California coast in the scenic Big Sur country,  
the cooler, calmer weather eased the pressure on firefighters. Both 
of those fires in the Los Padres National Forest -- the 33,000-acre 
Tassajara fire and the 40,000-acre Hare fire -- were 50 percent 
contained Sunday, U.S. Forest Service spokesman Robert Brady said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two fires started weeks ago by lightning in far northern  
California continued burning in the Trinity Alps Wilderness. They 
had spread across 93,397 acres, but one was 95 percent contained 
and the other was 30 percent contained, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in northern California, a 48,000-acre fire in the Sierra  
Nevada foothills of Tehama County, near Red Bluff, was 60 percent 
contained Sunday and fire crews allowed residents of remote Panther 
Springs and Boon Docks to return home, state forestry spokesman Tom 
Hostetter said. Full containment was expected by Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A blaze on steep terrain in the Siskiyou National Forest near  
Brookings, Ore., grew to 1,760 acres Sunday but firefighters got 
help from fog and high humidity. The fire, which began Tuesday, was 
25 percent contained, said spokesman Frank Carson. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in Oregon, crews had contained a fire that burned  
1,057 acres west of Eugene. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
