<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hokies As Championship Contenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- While the mere mention of Virginia  
Tech and the national championship seemed laughable just a few 
weeks ago, the team notorious for playing weak teams early in the 
season might be changing the notion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hokies have stepped up their competition considerably in the  
last 10 days, and given Clemson and Virginia the same harsh 
treatment as James Madison and UAB. 
</P>
<P>
	What's more, the last two victories against teams from the ACC  
have come with millions watching, and the dominance is getting 
noticed. In The Associated Press top 25 released Sunday, the Hokies 
climbed three spots to No. 5, their highest ranking ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's big time,'' defensive end Corey Moore said Saturday  
night, after the Hokies knocked Virginia from the rankings with a 
31-7 victory on ESPN2. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not trying to make a statement to anybody, but to the  
guys that are watching, I think we made a big statement,'' he said, 
speaking also about a 31-11 triumph against the Tigers on a 
Thursday night game shown nationally on ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	Both games demonstrated not only that Virginia Tech's No.  
1-ranked defense is as good as advertised, but also that the young 
offense is capable of dominance, too. 
</P>
<P>
	In Scott Stadium, redshirt freshman Michael Vick showed none of  
the impatience that led to three interceptions against the Tigers. 
By allowing plays to develop, he threw for 203 yards by halftime. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is our first big game when we really stepped up as an  
offense and proved ourselves,'' said wide receiver Andre Davis, who 
burned Virginia's Tim Spruill deep both times he tried. ``People 
have got to recognize our offense now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis had two catches for 110 yards, including a 60-yard  
touchdown, and seemingly could have run free all night had the 
Hokies chosen to run up the score. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the Hokies opted just to run, with tailback Shyrone  
Stith carrying 11 times for 85 yards in the second half, when the 
Hokies added only 3 points to a 28-7 halftime edge but trimmed 
large chunks off the clock in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be surprised if anybody played well on defense,''  
Virginia coach George Welsh snapped after his team gave up 424 
yards. ``We let them do anything they wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia Tech, meanwhile, let Virginia do nothing it wanted,  
holding Thomas Jones to 83 yards rushing, his lowest total since a 
55-yard effort against the Hokies last season. The Cavaliers were 
held to less than 10 points for the first time since a 26-9 loss at 
Blacksburg three seasons ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who averaged 155 yards in the Cavaliers' first four  
games, said the defense was the best he's faced, comparable to 
top-ranked Florida State's. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter who it is,'' he said. ``If they're good,  
they're good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Ellis was sacked six times, including twice each by John  
Engleberger and Michael Hawkes, and Virginia's Donnie Scott punted 
nine times. 
</P>
<P>
	On a day when No. 3 Florida and No. 5 Texas A&AMP;M both fell from  
the unbeaten ranks with close losses, the Hokies forged ahead in 
impressive fashion. 
</P>
<P>
	The toughest games remaining -- No. 18 Syracuse on Oct. 16 and  
No. 19 Miami on Nov. 13 -- both will be played before sellout crowds 
in Blacksburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Welsh seems to think Virginia Tech can be a major factor come  
championship time. 
</P>
<P>
	``That kind of defense can take you all the way just about,''  
the Virginia coach said, ``just as long as your offense doesn't 
hurt you.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
