<DOCNO> APW19991004.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 08:08:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NL Playoffs a Jumbled Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Playoff baseball is coming a day early, again.  
</P>
<P>
	While Pedro Martinez and Orlando Hernandez are all prepared for  
the AL postseason, Greg Maddux and Randy Johnson will have to wait. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because nothing is set in the NL, and it won't be until  
tonight's one-game playoff for the wild-card spot between the New 
York Mets and Cincinnati Reds at Cinergy Field. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know a lot about the National League clubs,'' Arizona  
manager Buck Showalter said. ``You don't hear the players saying, 
`If this happens or that happens.' We know we will be playing a 
quality opponent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This will be the second straight year a one-game playoff has  
decided the final NL spot. Last season, Chicago beat San Francisco 
5-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Tonight's game starts at 7:05 p.m. EDT, with Al Leiter likely to  
start for the Mets against Steve Parris. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Mets win, they will take off for Arizona and face Johnson  
and the Diamondbacks. That also would send Houston to Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Reds win, they'll go to Atlanta and see Maddux and the  
Braves. In that case, Houston would play at Arizona in the 
best-of-5 first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoever wins, I don't think anybody will have anything to be  
ashamed of,'' New York reliever John Franco said after the Mets 
arrived at their Cincinnati hotel around 12:40 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets beat Pittsburgh 2-1 and the Reds weathered a rain delay  
of five hours, 47 minutes before winning at Milwaukee 7-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to go 163 games now, but it was worth the wait,''  
Cincinnati manager Jack McKeon said. 
</P>
<P>
	The AL matchups, meanwhile, look extremely familiar.  
</P>
<P>
	New York vs. Texas, Boston vs. Cleveland. For the second  
straight year, and third time overall. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes for an interesting playoff,'' said David Cone, who  
helped pitch the Yankees to the World Series championship last 
year. ``All four teams legitimately think they have a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Yankee Stadium, Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez will pitch the  
opener on Tuesday night against Texas' Aaron Sele. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas will be trying to avenge last year's three-game sweep --  
and a four-game playoff loss in the opening round in 1996 -- to the 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Last postseason, the hard-hitting Rangers scored only one run in  
the entire series against New York and batted just .141. They have 
since added Rafael Palmeiro to a lineup that includes Juan Gonzalez 
and Ivan Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a great deal of respect for that organization, for the  
job Joe Torre has done,'' Texas manager Johnny Oates said. ``They 
are a professional team. But they had the season of the century 
last year. They're 15, 16 games less this season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Pettitte is scheduled to start Game 2 for the Yankees on  
Thursday, followed by Roger Clemens and, if necessary, Cone. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not an easy task. I know our record is good against  
them, but it doesn't mean that we expect anybody to roll over and 
play dead. That's not a part of what they do,'' said Torre, the 
Yankees manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``Again, I can't put enough emphasis on pitching,'' he said.  
``In a five-game series, you really can't afford to stumble. You 
get a little more air to breath in a seven-game series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians, who became the first team in the majors to score  
1,000 runs since 1950, will face Martinez in the opener. He led the 
majors in wins (23) and ERA (2.07) and topped the AL with 313 
strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez won Game 1 at Jacobs Field last year, but the Indians  
came back to win the next three and chase Boston. In 1995, 
Cleveland completed a three-game sweep of the Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hoping the third time is the charm against these guys,''  
Boston's Mike Stanley said. ``It's frustrating to continue to play 
them and keep losing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Indians catcher Sandy Alomar Jr.: ``It seems like we have  
to play Boston every year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux will throw the first pitch of the postseason on Tuesday  
afternoon at Turner Field. Kevin Millwood, Tom Glavine and, if 
necessary, John Smoltz will follow in the Atlanta rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our pitching staff is in great shape,'' Braves manager Bobby  
Cox said. ``It's as healthy as it's been all year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Bank One Ballpark, Johnson was to start for the second-year  
Diamondbacks in Game 1 Tuesday at 11:09 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	The late start time at Arizona was partly to make sure all games  
in the first round are televised -- ESPN, Fox and NBC will take 
turns showing them. Tonight's game in Cincinnati was to be shown on 
ESPN. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
