<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harbaugh Stays Chargers Starting QB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- There is no quarterback controversy with the  
San Diego Chargers. Yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with a bruised elbow and two slightly cracked ribs, Jim  
Harbaugh remains in charge of the Chargers' feeble offense, coach 
Mike Riley said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Riley left himself some wriggle room.  
</P>
<P>
	``I need to consider all things, but right now that's where I'm  
at,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbaugh was forced out in the first quarter of Sunday's 21-14  
victory over the Kansas City Chiefs. Backup Erik Kramer threw two 
touchdown passes, but it was the Chargers' defense that won the 
game, intercepting Elvis Grbac four times, two of which set up 
scores. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers don't return to practice until Wednesday, and  
Harbaugh doesn't expect to do much work this week. ``But I expect 
to be able to play on Sunday,'' Harbaugh said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers (2-1) visit Detroit on Sunday, their first game  
against Bobby Ross since he was forced out as San Diego's coach 
following the 1996 season. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old Harbaugh said this elbow injury isn't nearly as  
serious as the one that bothered him last year. As far as the ribs, 
``If they're sore or broken, it's the same thing,'' he said. In 
other words, it's nothing a flak jacket can't solve. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel surprisingly well, I guess,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Harbaugh could have gone back in had anything happened to  
Kramer. He kept throwing on the sideline so his elbow wouldn't 
tighten up. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Erik would have gotten hurt, there's really not much of a  
contingency plan there. I just wanted to be able to go back in if 
that happened,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of injury to both Harbaugh and Kramer, the Chargers  
really would have been hurting. With Ryan Leaf still rehabbing from 
shoulder surgery, wide receiver Mikhael Ricks is the emergency 
quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mikhael Ricks would have to go in and hand the ball off to  
somebody,'' Riley said. ``We weren't having very good success 
moving the ball with the regular quarterbacks, let alone having to 
go to our emergency guy. We haven't done enough work with that, 
either. We'll do a little more of that this week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ricks hurt his neck on a reverse that set up San Diego's third  
touchdown. He later returned to the game. 
</P>
<P>
	That third TD, an 11-yard pass from Kramer to Chris Penn, was  
the only completion to a Chargers wide receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need some bigger plays,'' Riley said.  
</P>
<P>
	San Diego's offense gained only 132 yards and is averaging 224  
yards per game. The only teams more pathetic on offense are 
Philadelphia and Cleveland, both 0-4. 
</P>
<P>
	With the way the offense has sputtered, the Chargers may  
actually welcome the return of Leaf, who had a troubled rookie 
season, on and off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaf hopes to be ready to play by the Oct. 24 home game against  
Green Bay. One week later, the Chargers visit Kansas City, where 
Leaf had a disastrous game in 1998 that he'd like to atone for. 
</P>
<P>
	``You saw what happened on Sunday,'' Leaf said, referring to  
Harbaugh's injury. ``They're both older guys, so it could come at 
any moment. Even if I am third string, I have to be prepared and 
ready to go in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaf began throwing last week, and said he made about 30 throws  
of 20-25 yards on Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
