<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CBS Plans Majority Web Co. Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS Corp. is buying its first majority stake in  
a Web destination as the company steps up an aggressive expansion 
of its presence on the Internet, a source familiar with the deal 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS has agreed to pay an undisclosed amount of cash for CTC  
Bulldog Inc., an Irvington, N.Y. venture formed earlier this year, 
said the source, speaking on condition of anonymity. The agreement 
also calls for CBS to carry ads promoting the site. 
</P>
<P>
	An announcement was planned in New York on Tuesday. Spokespeople  
from CBS and CTC Bulldog declined to comment on the deal, which was 
first reported Monday by The Wall Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	CTC Bulldog's Web site hasn't yet been unveiled but is ready to  
launch. It plans to use promotions such as prizes to try to draw 
Internet viewers, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS has been greatly expanding its Web strategy and currently  
holds minority stakes in 11 Web sites, including SportsLine USA and 
financial news provider MarketWatch.com, which sold stock to the 
public this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS generally has exchanged air time to promote the sites in  
exchange for its stakes. While some of the investments have paid 
off handsomely, CBS currently has no single Web destination to help 
guide Internet surfers to other holdings. In contrast, NBC has Web 
portal Snap.com and ABC created Go.com to organize links to its Web 
properties. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether CBS would use its latest Web holding to unify its  
disparate properties, the source would only say: ``This is the 
beginning of what they're doing. It's their entrance.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
