<HEADLINE> Bush Backs Giuliani on Museum Flap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush on Monday backed  
New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's attempts to cut off city 
funds for the Brooklyn Museum of Art for going ahead with a 
controversial art exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	The show, which opened Saturday, features, among other items, a  
black Virgin Mary adorned with body parts and elephant dung. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what I've read, the exhibit besmirches religion,'' Bush,  
the GOP presidential front-runner, said during a campaign stop with 
Gov. George Pataki. ``It denigrates someone's religion. I don't 
think we ought to be using public monies to denigrate religion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's right,'' Pataki added. ``When you use public money to  
denigrate someone's religion, I think it's wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, President Clinton disagrees with Giuliani, his  
spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Monday that  
Clinton agrees with his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who opposes 
Giuliani's position. Mrs. Clinton is considering mounting a bid for 
the U.S. Senate from New York, and Giuliani is her likely opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president has indicated that he supports the first lady's  
position, and my understanding of the first lady's position is 
while she would find this objectionable -- wouldn't see it -- she 
doesn't ... agree with the action that the mayor's taken,'' 
Lockhart. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do have a grand tradition of freedom of expression in this  
country and a rich cultural art and humanities history that I think 
should not become part of or be attacked in the political 
context,'' Lockhart added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
