<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UPS Offers Customers Web Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service plans to provide free  
access to its World Wide Web site for customers who aren't already 
online. 
</P>
<P>
	The service is called ``fenced'' Internet access because it  
allows users to link only to the UPS Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	The service, which uses the Microsoft Internet Explorer browser  
and connection software from AT&AMP;T, will be unveiled Wednesday at 
the Fall Internet World show in New York and will be distributed to 
interested companies early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	It enables companies that aren't already online to use the UPS  
Web site to track packages, estimate shipping times, calculate 
shipping costs and request pickup without having to go through UPS 
customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta-based shipping giant already provides those services  
online for customers with Internet access. UPS said it receives 
about 1 million tracking requests daily on its Web site. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
