<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lou Holtz' Wife Gets Good Prognosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Beth Holtz, with her husband nearby,  
underwent successful surgery Monday at the Mayo Clinic to remove 
her adrenal gland and a cyst on her ovary. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina coach Lou Holtz said in a statement that the  
operation went extremely well and his wife's prognosis is 
excellent. 
</P>
<P>
	Beth Holtz, who had a throat cancer operation two years ago, is  
expected to stay in the Rochester, Minn., hospital for five days, 
then recover at the family's home in Orlando, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz had left the team Sunday and met his wife at their  
daughter's home in Indianapolis before the couple traveled to 
Minnesota. He is expected back at his office Tuesday and will be 
running the afternoon practice. 
</P>
<P>
	This surgery should end a frightening time for the Holtz family.  
</P>
<P>
	In September, Beth Holtz felt numbness and a lack of circulation  
in her leg. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors discovered tumors in her adrenal gland, lung, kidney and  
ovary. The only one found to be malignant was the adrenal gland, 
her son, Skip, an assistant to his father, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her latest troubles have nothing to do with the throat cancer,  
which radiation treatments have kept in remission, Skip Holtz said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past two weeks, Lou Holtz has been upbeat and confident  
about his wife's recovery. ``She's stronger than I am,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Their son says that strength comes from the couple's faith and  
solid family ties. ``It has always been that way,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the concerns about his mother's recovery was her frailty  
after her throat cancer. She dropped to 85 pounds and needed nearly 
a year to feel like herself again, Skip Holtz said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was hard to gain the weight back since treatments created  
much scar tissue in her throat and damaged her taste buds, Skip 
Holtz said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took her so long in the past,'' he said. ``It's one of the  
worries about this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other family members are expected to remain with Beth Holtz once  
Lou Holtz comes back to South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Skip, who is trying to spark the least productive Division I-A  
offense in the country, likely will not be among them. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been one of the most difficult years of my life,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Beth Holtz's medical problems also have kept Lou Holtz spinning  
in different directions. The 62-year-old keeps a hectic schedule 
normally, but he made two round trips between the Mayo Clinic and 
Williams-Brice Stadium last week, visiting his wife and preparing 
the Gamecocks for their 36-10 loss to Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Beth Holtz was key in convincing her husband to end his TV  
studio retirement and take control of the Gamecocks. Her presence 
her helped persuade Skip to leave as Connecticut's head coach so 
his three children could be near their grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	The Holtzes have been married for 38 years and have four  
children, Luanne Altenbaumer, Skip, Kevin and Elizabeth Messaglia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gamecocks (0-5), who are home this week against Kentucky,  
have the country's longest Division I losing streak at 15 games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
