<HEADLINE> Another Step in Expos' Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- The proposed sale of the Montreal Expos to a  
group headed by New York art dealer Jeffrey Loria took a step 
forward Monday when the team's current owners gave their unanimous 
consent in principle. 
</P>
<P>
	Expos chairman Jacques Menard, who has helped Loria put together  
the investors who hope to buy the time from Claude Brochu's group, 
said the plan will be forwarded to the commissioner's office. While 
Menard hopes the sale could be put to a vote within a month or so, 
but the approval process for baseball sales usually takes much 
longer than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have confidence in our ability to convince major league  
baseball that we have here a business plan which will make Montreal 
a winning baseball city,'' Menard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Loria and the new investors would buy 35 percent of the team and  
hold the controlling interest. The current group, which might bring 
in some new partners, would own the remaining 65 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan is tied to the team obtaining funding for a new  
ballpark. 
  	   	
