<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Close Up / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A central bank survey showing further optimism  
about Japan's economy helped pushed up Tokyo share prices slightly 
today. The dollar also gained against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 51.15  
points, or 0.29 percent, to 17,763.71. On Friday, the index climbed 
107.10 points, or 0.61 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. dollar was trading at 106.11 yen on the Tokyo foreign  
exchange market today, up 0.17 yen from late Friday and also above 
its late Friday level of 104.96 yen in New York. The greenback 
traded from 104.42 yen to 106.22 yen during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	In the stock market, Tokyo share prices moved higher following  
the release of the quarterly ``tankan'' survey by the Bank of Japan 
earlier today. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey stated that sentiment among large manufacturers had  
brightened over the last survey to a figure of minus 22 from minus 
37, its biggest improvement since November 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	The tankan measures the percentage of firms seeing business  
conditions improve minus the percentage seeing conditions worsen. 
The bank surveyed 9,275 companies for the latest report. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the tankan also showed that business investment  
continues to taper off in Japan. Investment plans for large 
companies showed they expect spending on plant and equipment to 
shrink by 9.4 percent this year. In June, the same companies had 
forecast only a 7.9 percent drop. 
</P>
<P>
	As the implications of the capital spending plans became clear  
to traders, buying dried up. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market rose a bit on the tankan results at first, but  
rather than rally, share prices then stumbled to trade within a 
narrow range,'' said Kazunori Shimono, manager of the equity 
trading section at Tokyo-Mitsubishi Personal Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Though market conditions aren't bad, the tankan results were  
not positive enough for players to buy higher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed up 0.90 points, or 0.06 percent, to 1,515.98. 
The TOPIX closed up 8.25 points, or 0.55 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 434.23 million shares, down from 543.54 million shares 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Decliners outnumbered advancers 657 to 568 on the first section  
of the Tokyo stock exchange, while 113 remained unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average closed  
at 10,273.00 points, down 63.95. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar gained against the yen as the  
tankan survey showed weaker-than-expected corporate capital 
spending plans for fiscal 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The worse-than-expected capital spending figures for this fiscal  
year could yet spoil Japan's nascent economic recovery, which 
triggered investors to buy dollars, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the central bank survey, large corporation capital  
spending index for this fiscal year is seen falling to minus 9.4, 
from minus 5.8 in the last quarter. It's the lowest figure since 
September 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 113.82 yen today, up 0.46  
yen from its level late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.6000 percent from Friday's finish of 1.6750 percent. Its price 
rose 0.66 points to 100.87. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
