<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tanker Makes Emergency Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRNS, Australia (AP) -- A United States Air Force tanker plane  
loaded with aviation fuel made a successful emergency landing at 
Cairns airport today after a faulty sensor incorrectly indicated 
one of its engines was on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The K-135 midair refueller, a converted Boeing 707, with nine  
crew aboard, took off early this morning from the airport at this 
city 1,050 miles north of Sydney, AirServices Australia spokesman 
Richard Green said. 
</P>
<P>
	Four minutes later, the pilot requested emergency services be  
placed on standby after noticing a warning light indicating an 
engine was on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot shut down the plane's number three engine and landed  
safely at the civilian airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers who inspected the engine determined there had been no  
fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was caused by a loose hose clip, which allowed very hot  
heated air into the engine cell and activated the fire alarm 
sensor,'' Green said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tanker had been returning to Hickam Air Force Base in  
Honolulu, said Merv Fowler, air traffic control manager at Cairns 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Further details on the flight and its crew were not immediately  
available. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 18:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Owners Renew Expansion Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The NFL's expansion team mystery tour continues  
in Atlanta, with owners still trying to decide whether to give 
Houston or Los Angeles the league's 32nd franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion committee is scheduled to meet Tuesday evening,  
with the full ownership convening the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	The league is weighing whether to award its 32nd franchise to  
Robert McNair and Houston, which has a stadium and financing plan 
ready to go, or to Michael Ovitz, the Hollywood super-agent who 
proposes to build a stadium at Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion committee may or may not make a firm  
recommendation to the league ownership, which may or may not make a 
final decision. And there are signs that the selection process, 
which has been dragging on all year, could be further delayed by 
putting off any decision until the owners meet again next month -- 
and maybe beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	There also is sentiment among at least some of the owners to try  
to assure having teams in both cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones suggested that the league give  
Houston the expansion team, then find an existing team to move to 
Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston has the more complete package, including $195 million in  
public funds for a stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Ovitz, whose group of backers include grocery  
billionaire Ron Burkle and actor Tom Cruise, seems to have 
captivated some NFL owners as a potential franchise owner because 
of his background in the entertainment industry. NFL commissioner 
Paul Tagliabue has called Ovitz a ``visionary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The league also is very aware that it doesn't have a presence in  
what is the nation's second-largest TV market. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz, who initially proposed building a stadium on a former  
landfill in suburban Carson, moved back in the forefront of the Los 
Angeles picture last week after oil billionaire Marvin Davis 
dropped his bid to bring a team to Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Coliseum, the league's top choice for a team  
several months ago, seems to be on the back burner. The NFL had 
asked for public funding for the Coliseum remodel and parking 
improvements, then opened the bidding up to other groups in the 
area after there was no promise of public money. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz has agreed to pay the league a reported $25 million in  
earnest money if he and his group are awarded a franchise. Such a 
deposit would guarantee the league that Ovitz and his backers meet 
the terms of their agreement, or forfeit the money. 
</P>
<P>
	If Ovitz and his group get the team, he may have some  
flexibility on where to put it. Although Hollywood Park was 
approved by the owners as a possible site for a team several years 
ago, there may be some stumbling blocks to building a stadium 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	Parking, one of the league's complaints about the Coliseum, also  
could be a problem at Hollywood Park. There are plenty of 
additional spaces across the street at the Forum, but that arena is 
now owned by Ed Roski and his partner. Roski has been snubbed by 
the NFL in his attempt to bring a team to the Coliseum.. 
</P>
<P>
	There also is a question of whether some of the team owners now  
would approve a stadium on the same property with a horse racing 
track and a casino. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz said recently that he was optimistic about getting the  
expansion franchise, but cautioned that any such move would have to 
be approved by 24 of the league's 31 team owners. 
</P>
<P>
	They did reach a consensus last March, voting 29-2 to  
conditionally award the team to Los Angeles. The condition was that 
a stadium and financing plan agreeable to the NFL was presented by 
Sept. 15. That deadline passed quietly, however, and the league 
began talking again with Houston as well as continuing discussions 
with interested Los Angeles groups. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
