<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Profits Rise for Manchester United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, England (AP) -- Manchester United, considered the  
world's richest soccer club, has seen its operating profits 
increase by 20 percent to $53.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the club reported Monday a 22 percent decrease in  
full-year net income after spending on high-salaried players was 
taken into account. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the year ended July dropped to $27.8 million from  
$32.5 million. The club reported sales were up 26 percent to $183.8 
million from increased gate receipts and sponsorship revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Manchester United, the first English club to win Europe's triple  
crown -- European Champions Cup, league title and domestic F.A. Cup 
-- has spent heavily on player salaries in recent years to remain 
competitive in the 20-team English Premier League. 
</P>
<P>
	United said player salary costs increased by $12.8 million  
during the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial report came a day after the club sustained a  
humiliating 5-0 loss at league-rival Chelsea, Manchester United's 
first league defeat in 30 matches. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
