<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Criticizes Clinton Nuke Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful  
Elizabeth Dole had harsh words Monday for President Clinton's push 
for a nuclear test ban treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to the New Hampshire Federation of Republican Women,  
Dole called Clinton's take on foreign policy and the Comprehensive 
Test Ban Treaty ``wishful thinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Clinton-Gore foreign policy is no guarantor of our  
nation's security,'' she said. ``The Clinton-Gore rose-colored 
glasses have not adapted to the harsh realities of the world 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the fall of the Soviet Union, then-President Bush signed a  
limited testing moratorium to take effect Oct. 1, 1992, for nine 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton continued the moratorium -- the country's last test was  
in September 1992 -- then signed the comprehensive global treaty in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty went to the Senate for ratification in 1997 but  
languished there until last week when Majority Leader Trent Lott, 
R-Miss., unexpectedly scheduled a full Senate vote for next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole said the treaty is ``ineffective and unverifiable.''  
</P>
<P>
	``In a time when America is naked to ballistic missile attack,  
there is no evidence that the (ban) would reduce proliferation,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among her concerns, Dole said barely half of nuclear-capable  
countries have signed the agreement and that the Central 
Intelligence Agency has difficulty monitoring low-level tests. She 
also said computer model testing, an alternative to actual nuclear 
tests, is inadequate to maintain the safety and security of the 
nation's aging nuclear stockpiles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Common sense says the (treaty) must be rejected and I say we  
must scrap this ill-conceived plan,'' Dole said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
