<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roof Leak Affects Cleveland Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A leaky roof on a control tower led to flight  
delays and cancellations Monday at Cleveland Hopkins International 
Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Water from overnight rain dripped on the computer displays that  
air traffic controllers use to guide planes when they are between 
five and 40 miles from Hopkins, said Federal Aviation 
Administration spokeswoman Elizabeth Isham Cory. 
</P>
<P>
	FAA officials shut down the operation because of the possibility  
of electrical shock. 
</P>
<P>
	A regional air traffic control center in Oberlin took over the  
work of guiding planes to within five miles of the airport. As 
usual, another control tower at Hopkins guided planes the rest of 
the way. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the FAA nor airport officials could say when the  
Terminal Radar Approach Control would be functioning again. 
</P>
<P>
	The airport had 308,550 arrivals and departures last year and is  
a hub for Continental Airlines. Continental spokeswoman Catherine 
Stengel said the airline has 279 daily departures from Hopkins. 
Flights were delayed an average of 2 1/2 hours Monday, and about 10 
round trips were canceled, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Small leaks at the tower had been reported since the FAA  
replaced rooftop air conditioning units in August. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
