<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Vagina Monologues' Funny, Candid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Say a word three times and it's yours. If that's  
the case, playwright and performer Eve Ensler probably has a patent 
on ``vagina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The v-word happens to be the subject of her astonishing theater  
piece, ``The Vagina Monologues,'' which opened Sunday at 
off-Broadway's Westside Theater. Over the years, it's not exactly 
been a topic of conversation for what used to be called polite 
society. Yet this linguistic pioneer, who looks like a cross 
between Louise Brooks and Anna Wintour, has set out to change all 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	Ensler breaks taboos by talking, talking and talking some more --  
stripping fear and shame from what she celebrates here. It makes 
for quite a party. Funny, outrageous, emotionally affecting and 
occasionally angry. 
</P>
<P>
	The actress sits primly on a high red chair, her only prop a  
swing microphone. 
</P>
<P>
	The evening consists of monologues Ensler constructed from  
interviews with women about ``down there,'' two words the 
playwright herself would never use today, although more than a few 
of the women she interviewed would. 
</P>
<P>
	Ensler begins by saying she is worried, worried about what  
people think of vaginas -- and worried even more about what they 
don't think about them. ``There's so much darkness and secrecy 
surrounding them -- like the Bermuda Triangle,'' she confides to the 
audience. ``Nobody ever reports back from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ensler does -- and she doesn't shrink from the serious, either. A  
bittersweet quality permeates a set of interviews she did with a 
group of women between the ages of 65 and 75, who arrived too early 
for the sexual revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	She also deals with mass rape in Bosnia, a tragedy of such  
immense proportions that it overwhelms its victims and the society 
in which they live. She then recounts the horrors of genital 
mutilation, which has affected, according to Ensler, upwards of 100 
million women. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet there also is a celebration of birth, in which Ensler  
witnesses the arrival of her granddaughter, a joyous affirmation of 
life that she describes in jubilant detail. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the evening's most provocative and hilarious sections,  
Ensler uses a four-letter synonym for vagina, one of those words 
that would be used but never heard on the new television show 
``Action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the Fox sitcom about the machinations of a young Hollywood  
producer, four-letter words are bleeped for comic effect. The 
repetition quickly becomes gimmicky -- and unfunny. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Vagina Monologues'' confront words to demystify and disarm  
them. In doing so, Ensler disarms the audience, too. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991004.0178 </DOCNO>
