<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Wants Cheaper Prescriptions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Steve  
Forbes on Monday said Americans shouldn't have to cross the border 
to buy prescription drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes also promised to modernize the military and said there  
needed to be fewer restrictions on spending by political campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said such change won't come if another Washington insider  
is elected. 
</P>
<P>
	``To move forward, it is going to take an independent outsider  
and individual not beholden to the establishment, special 
interests, lobbyists,'' Forbes said during a campaign appearance. 
``They have no hooks in me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes said he was discouraged to hear that some New Hampshire  
residents go to Canada to buy prescription drugs at cheaper prices. 
If elected, he promised a drug support system that would eliminate 
them to travel to Quebec for medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he would work to modernize the military, adding  
that people in the service must be paid adequately to support 
themselves, their families and their country. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the military, as it now is funded, is not ready to  
handle conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, a millionaire publisher who is financing his campaign,  
addressed the issue of campaign finance reform, saying fewer 
restrictions were needed on spending and that candidates ought to 
be able to do more with the money they have. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, speaking at the Mount Washington Hotel in Bretton Woods,  
Forbes said the International Monetary Fund was obsolete and called 
for its abolishment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
