<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators Look at Lowe's Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, N.C. (AP) -- A small fire damaged a Lowe's home  
improvement store and state and federal investigators are trying to 
determine if it is related to recent bombings at three other Lowe's 
stores in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire Sunday evening at the Lexington Lowe's Home Improvement  
Warehouse damaged a door and was quickly extinguished, authorities 
said. No one was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Two bombs exploded Sept. 22 at Lowe's stores in Asheboro and  
Salisbury, injuring three people. A third bomb was found last week 
at a Lowe's store in Concord and investigators believe the same 
person or group is responsible for all three bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said today they had not yet determined if the fire was  
connected to the bombs, but they had contacted the State Bureau of 
Investigation and the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators have confirmed they are looking for links between  
the Asheboro blast and an accident at Lowe's Motor Speedway in 
Concord on May 1 that killed three spectators and injured eight. 
</P>
<P>
	The News &AMP; Record of Greensboro reported last week that someone  
had called North Wilkesboro-based Lowe's to complain not enough was 
done for victims of the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe's is the corporate sponsor of the track, which is owned by  
Concord-based Speedway Motorsports Inc. The speedway reported a 
bomb threat last week on the same day of the discovery of the store 
bomb. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
