<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magistrate Convicted of Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERKELEY SPRINGS, W.Va. (AP) -- A magistrate has been convicted  
of fraud for fabricating a story that she was attacked in her 
northeastern West Virginia office. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonnie Riffle was found guilty Friday in Morgan County Circuit  
Court on two felony counts of Workers' Compensation fraud and five 
misdemeanor counts of filing false reports. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just utterly shocked,'' said her lawyer, Paul Lane, adding  
that Riffle will appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The convictions could lead to four years in prison and fines of  
up to $10,000, Lane said today. The judge asked that a sentencing 
investigation be completed by Oct. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Riffle, 43, testified Friday that a man wrapped a belt or rope  
around her neck while she worked late in her office on Feb. 16. She 
said she was cut on her face after she told the assailant she did 
not have money. 
</P>
<P>
	But state Medical Examiner James Kaplan testified that Riffle's  
facial wound was self-inflicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Riffle was suspended without pay by the state Supreme Court when  
she was indicted in April. 
</P>
<P>
	She remains free on bond pending sentencing.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
