<DOCNO> APW19991004.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 23:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Finds Test Ban a Hard Sell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Four decades after President Dwight Eisenhower  
proposed a global prohibition on nuclear testing, U.S. 
policy-makers still are debating whether Americans would be safer 
with or without such a ban. 
</P>
<P>
	A week from today, the Senate votes on the Comprehensive Test  
Ban Treaty, a troubled Clinton administration initiative signed by 
154 nations -- but ratified by only two of the seven acknowledged 
nuclear powers, Britain and France. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Armed Services Committee opens three days of hearings  
today on the treaty. The first session, a closed one, will explore 
a central question: Can the United States maintain the integrity of 
its nuclear arsenal without occasional testing? 
</P>
<P>
	``If there were some feeling of weakness about that stockpile,  
it could induce a leader of another nation or some rogue element or 
some terrorist to challenge the United States,'' said Armed 
Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va. ``There can be no 
doubt about the credibility of that stockpile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even Clinton acknowledges he doesn't have the votes right now to  
win ratification, but told reporters on Monday, ``I hope we can get 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By most counts, the administration is 15 votes or more short of  
the 67 needed to ratify a treaty. Democrats blame Senate Republican 
leaders for rushing to a vote after sitting on the treaty for two 
years, not giving them enough time to marshal public support. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you ask people what's the most important thing they worry  
about, the test ban treaty is not on the top of the list,'' said 
Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster. However, a July poll he 
conducted for the Coalition to Reduce Nuclear Dangers, a pro-test 
ban advocacy group, suggested 82 percent of the American public 
supported such a treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate critics say the treaty, which would ban all nuclear  
testing and set up a seismic monitoring network to gauge 
compliance, is seriously flawed -- and unverifiable because there 
are ways to muffle atomic blasts. They contend it would not prevent 
U.S. enemies or terrorist elements from developing nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Foreign governments will decide whether to develop nuclear  
weapons based on a calculus of national interests, not on whether 
the CTBT has been ratified by the U.S. Senate,'' said Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	To date, only the United States has used nuclear weapons -- the  
two atomic bombs against Japan that ended World War II in August 
1945. But putting the nuclear genie back into the bottle has proven 
virtually impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Treaty supporters say it is crucial to keep nuclear weapons from  
proliferating further. They say it would keep large countries with 
advanced nuclear weapons already in their arsenals, including 
Russia and China, from manufacturing even more threatening weapons, 
and make it easier to rein in smaller nuclear powers, like India 
and Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	It would also lock in U.S. superiority achieved through more  
than 1,000 nuclear tests. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since we don't need nuclear tests, it is strongly in our  
interest to achieve agreement that can help prevent other countries 
like India, Pakistan, Russia, China, Iran and others from testing 
and deploying nuclear weapons,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	As to whether U.S. stockpiles could be kept current, Clinton  
said, ``We are spending $4.5 billion a year to make sure ... we can 
maintain the integrity of our stockpile.'' The United States has 
not conducted a nuclear test since 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., a staunch test-ban foe who refused to  
hold hearings on the treaty for two years, announced he would hold 
one Thursday -- with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright as the 
leadoff witness to ``make her case for the treaty.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
