<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Case Against Sportswriter Dropped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Washington State University campus police,  
who arrested a Seattle Post-Intelligencer sportswriter in a dispute 
that followed last weekend's Cougars football game, have dropped 
their accusations, a school athletics spokesman said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelo Bruscas was arrested for investigation of fourth-degree  
assault and obstruction of an officer after Washington State's 
victory over California on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also will not pursue a case against Jeff Evans, a WSU  
sports information student employee who was cited for fourth-degree 
assault in the same dispute, athletics spokesman Rod Commons said. 
</P>
<P>
	Commons on Monday issued a letter of apology to Pacific  
Northwest sports journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will do everything in our power to make sure the mistake is  
not repeated,'' Commons wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Bunting, the P-I's managing editor, said in a statement the  
newspaper was ``gratified'' that Bruscas was exonerated. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have accepted the university's apologies for this  
unfortunate incident, and we intend to move on,'' Bunting said. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident occurred as reporters were trying to make their way  
to an interview room in WSU's Bohler Addition to speak with Cougars 
players. A WSU event security guard barred the media from entering 
the building. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans, who had a key, unlocked the door the security officer was  
guarding so he could enter. 
</P>
<P>
	As the door cracked open, reporters also went through past the  
guard, who reported he was pushed by Evans. Police also alleged 
Bruscas pushed the guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Once inside, a campus police officer confronted the reporters,  
asking them to stop. Bruscas didn't stop right away, deciding to 
use a restroom first. 
</P>
<P>
	The female officer handcuffed Bruscas as he came out of the  
restroom and then took him to the campus police station, where he 
was cited and released. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans was notified that he had been cited in a telephone call to  
his home that night. 
</P>
<P>
	``After looking into what happened, it is clear to us that  
Angelo did not strike, push or shove anyone,'' Bunting said. 
</P>
<P>
	``While it is true that Angelo initially disobeyed (the  
officer's) order to `halt' because he urgently needed to use the 
restroom, she was not wearing a recognizable uniform and he did not 
know she was a police officer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters have had immediate post game access to the interview  
room in the past. Commons has said the security guard had been told 
to hold back the media for 10 minutes on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	From now on, a sports information staff member will be assigned  
to monitor the entrance to the interview area after games, Commons 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
