<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Payroll Jumping $8M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Pirates' payroll will increase  
from $24 million to $32 million next season, yet will again be 
among the lowest in the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	The payroll is expected to jump to $40 million in 2001, the  
Pirates' first season in their new ballpark, but will be less than 
half that of the Yankees and Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	``For us, it's going up,'' managing general partner Kevin  
McClatchy said. ``For others, that's a pretty small payroll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati general manager Jim Bowden said last weekend the Reds  
would have to increase their payroll $20 million in 2000 to retain 
their current club. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite not having a single $3 million player this season, the  
Pirates finished third in the NL Central, ahead of the Cardinals 
and Cubs, teams which much bigger payrolls. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the third season of a five-year plan designed to field  
a contending team once the Pirates open PNC Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you can judge a five-year plan in its third  
year,'' McClatchy said. ``But, from my standpoint, it's on track.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
