<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Grains Move Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices fell in early  
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, after a busy harvest 
weekend in some areas and continued reports of large supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans futures prices were lower as harvesting continued over  
the weekend in some soybean growing areas. Corn futures fell to an 
11-week low, amid reports of a big crop and declining feed use. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures prices tumbled Friday after an independent analyst  
reported the U.S. corn crop was higher than government estimates. 
The U.S. Agriculture Department will release a new production 
forecast this Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures prices also declined early today on reports of  
large supplies and lack of export demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Some farmers and analysts are expecting a delay in harvests in  
parts of the Midwest that saw heavy weekend rains, including parts 
of southern Michigan and northern Ohio, Indiana and Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading today, wheat for December delivery fell 3 3/4  
cents to $2.63 1/2 a bushel; December corn fell 1 cent to $2.04 cents 
a bushel; December oats fell 1 1/4 cent to $1.11 a bushel; and 
November soybeans fell 1 1/4 cent to $4.79 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, meat and livestock futures prices were mixed in early  
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose 0.20 cent to 68.97 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle was unchanged at 81.85 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs fell 0.37 cent to 50 cents a pound; and February frozen 
pork bellies fell 1.05 cents to 64.55 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
