<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Yen; Down Vs. Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the Japanese yen on  
Monday after a new survey raised concerns over whether Japan will 
be able to sustain its current economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 106.23  
Japanese yen, up from 104.96 late Friday. The euro was quoted at 
$1.0735, up from $1.0728. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's economy has been struggling to emerge from its deepest  
downturn in a half century. But there have been signs of recovery: 
There has been two straight quarters of growth in Japan's economy 
and a drop in the jobless rate from a record high. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan, in its closely watched quarterly ``tankan''  
survey, said sentiment among large manufacturers had brightened 
over the last survey to a figure of minus 22 from minus 37, its 
biggest improvement since November 1987. The result exceeded 
analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The tankan measures the percentage of firms seeing business  
conditions improve minus the percentage seeing conditions worsen. 
The bank surveyed 9,275 companies in September for the latest 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	But the tankan also showed that business investment -- what  
companies spend on equipment and plants -- continued to taper off. 
The large corporation capital spending index for this fiscal year 
is seen falling to minus 9.4 from minus 5.8 in the last quarter. 
It's the lowest figure since September 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	That spooked investors, who saw the decline in capital spending  
as a sign that Japan's economic growth may be slowing. 
</P>
<P>
	While the dollar rose today, investors watched their moves ahead  
of meetings this week by the U.S. Federal Reserve and the European 
Central Bank, where they will both decide whether to raise interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher U.S. rates could benefit the dollar by making  
dollar-backed assets more attractive to investors. The same would 
be true in Europe if the ECB boosted rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4829 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4820, and 1.4697 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4769. The British 
pound rose to $1.6559 from $1.6548. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8219 German 
marks, down from 1.8229; 6.1105 French francs, down from 6.1139; 
and 1,803.70 Italian lire, down from 1,804.71. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
