<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Says Book Won't Hurt Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite harsh criticism of his new book's  
conclusions about World War II, Republican presidentical candidate 
Pat Buchanan said Monday he did not think the controversy would 
hurt him politically. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've gotten more press attention than I've gotten since (1996)  
when I won (the) New Hampshire'' primary, Buchanan said on CNN's 
``Larry King Live.'' ``The book's headed for the best-seller list, 
and I'm leading the polls for the Reform Party nomination even 
though I haven't joined it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan said he would probably make a final decision by the end  
of the month on whether to leave the GOP and join the Reform Party. 
</P>
<P>
	His book, ``A Republic, Not an Empire,'' has drawn criticism for  
his argument that Germany was not a threat to the United States 
after 1940. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he thought the book would hurt him politically,  
Buchanan said, ``I do not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The book is its best defense. When it hits the best-seller  
list, people are going to read it. They're going to realize all 
this talk that it's some kind of sequel to (Adolf Hitler's) 'Mein 
Kampf' is a lot of nonsense from hysteriacs,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
