<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Casey Ready for First Nets' Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) -- Even with Jayson Williams sidelined  
until at least January and Kerry Kittles coming off knee surgery, 
coach Don Casey thinks the New Jersey Nets have the pieces to make 
the playoffs this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jim McIlvaine put it best the other day,'' Casey said Monday  
during the Nets media day. ``Everything looks good on paper. I 
praise the Knicks and (Jeff) Van Gundy. They really got it done on 
the court with their backs against the wall without a couple of 
their main guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Knicks went to the NBA Finals in June in the  
lockout-marred season, the Nets had everything go wrong. After 
opening the season with a 3-17 record, John Calipari was fired. 
Casey took over on an interim basis and finished 13-17, a 
performance that earned him the full-time job despite missing the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets still face problems heading into this season.  
</P>
<P>
	Williams, an All-Star center two years ago, is still battling to  
get back into shape after breaking his leg in April and undergoing 
recent knee surgery. January is the earliest anyone hopes to see 
him on the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Kittles, their talented shooting guard who averaged almost 13  
points, also had offseason surgery and is not 100 percent with the 
Nets ready to open training camp on Tuesday at the Atlantic City 
Convention Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to dig in, the coaches and players as well,'' Casey  
said. ``It looks good. We finished OK, but it's a longer season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The good news for the Nets is that they have two of the most  
talented young players in the game in point guard Stephon Marbury 
and forward Keith Van Horn. 
</P>
<P>
	Marbury, acquired in March just before Calipari was fired,  
averaged 21.3 points and 8.9 assists last season. Van Horn averaged 
21.8 points and 8.5 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to win. That's it,'' Marbury said after taking his  
physical at Hackensack Medical Center. ``We're going to win. We're 
young, dynamic, and determined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The words are part of a Nets' advertisement, so many laughed  
when Marbury said them. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can go out and play like them words, I think we can  
definitely do something this year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The big question is in the middle, where Jamie Feick, McIlvaine  
and Gheorghe Muresan will try to combine to give the team minutes 
at center. 
</P>
<P>
	With Marbury and Kendall Gill at the guards, Scott Burrell and  
Johnny Newman at the small forward and Van Horn playing the No. 4 
spot, the Nets should be OK. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we are definitely one of the top five teams in the  
East,'' Burrell said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's on paper though.  
</P>
<P>
	``This team has no identity,'' Casey said. ``It's not  
established yet. When I went to Boston, they always felt they were 
going to win 50-plus games a year because they have been doing it 
for 10 years. This team has not done that. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to keep everyone happy and try to establish the  
type of play, a style strong and resolute,'' he added. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
