<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Samaranch Asks Greeks To Be United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- International Olympic Committee president  
Juan Antonio Samaranch on Monday called on Greeks to unite in their 
support for the 2004 Olympics and dispelled rumors of delays by 
Athens organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I am asking something, it is unity,'' Samaranch said after  
three days of IOC meetings in Athens. 
</P>
<P>
	During the meetings, Athens organizers presented an update of  
their progress since being awarded the games two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Athens organizers told the IOC they decided to make image  
building a top priority following media reports of disorganization, 
delays and problems with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	``Following the official report presented by the organizing  
committee, there are no delays,'' Samaranch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said that although problems were normal until the end  
of the games, he trusted Athens organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to assure you things are going quite well,''  
Samaranch said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that he was impressed by the new Athens 2004 logo, a  
white wreath-shaped olive branch floating in a sky and sea blue 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	``The games are very important, not only for us ... It is a  
golden opportunity for Greece,'' Samaranch said. ``The games in 
Athens, they have three dimensions... sport and culture, but you 
have something that belongs only to your country, that that is a 
history, the Olympic history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While in Athens, Samaranch met with Premier Costas Simitis,  
Culture Minister Elisavet Papazoi and signed a final agreement to 
establish an Olympic Truce Center with Foreign Minister George 
Papandreou. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic Truce is aimed at reviving a tradition whereby  
warring parties suspended their conflicts during the ancient 
Olympic Games in Greece. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
