<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tycoon Brothers Battling in Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- It is a tale of two brothers from a  
billionaire family fighting over wealth and power from the family's 
oil business. Entwined through the years have been enough takeover 
attempts, conspiracies and betrayals to fill a soap opera. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, brothers Bill and Charles Koch face each another in  
federal court once again. 
</P>
<P>
	On behalf of the United States, Bill Koch is suing Koch  
Industries -- built by his father into the country's leading crude 
oil purchaser and now run by his older brother Charles Koch -- over 
allegations that it stole millions of dollars in oil from Indian 
lands and federal leases. Jury selection began today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Osage Nation, from which Koch gets most of the oil it  
obtains from Indian lands, isn't joining the civil lawsuit. Chief 
Charles Tillman said the tribe couldn't prove any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We even permitted Bill Koch to access and review and  
investigate the records,'' he said. ``There is no proof.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side will say how much potential liability is involved  
for Koch Industries, the nation's second-largest privately held 
company with $30 billion in sales. But Bill Koch could receive up 
to one-third of the court award if he wins. 
</P>
<P>
	The staggering wealth involved has some Oklahoma producers  
questioning whether the Tulsa lawsuit has legitimate claims or if 
the courtroom is just a personal battleground for Bill Koch (age 
58, net worth $650 million) and Charles Koch (age 63, net worth 
$3.4 billion). 
</P>
<P>
	Last year in Topeka, Kan., Bill Koch fought his brother in  
federal court claiming he was cheated out of more than $1 billion 
when he sold his stake in Koch Industries back in 1983. He lost. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge who heard the case later said, if given a second  
chance, he would not have let the case go to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, the lawsuit alleges Koch Industries routinely  
instructed employees to underreport the amount of oil they collect 
from producers' tanks. It accuses Koch of collecting enough oil to 
fill 5.3 million barrels -- more than $133 million worth -- without 
paying for it from 1981-1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is expected to last months.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of history behind this case and the parties  
involved,'' said Koch Industries spokesman Jay Rosser. ``We're 
confident our integrity will be affirmed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The idea Oklahoma producers were not aware that they were being  
ripped off makes the merits of the case shaky, said Dewey Bartlett 
Jr., president of the Oklahoma Independent Petroleum Association. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the American Petroleum Institute's manual on  
standards for measuring crude oil, it is impossible to measure oil 
without error because of the variables involved. 
</P>
<P>
	The case against Koch Industries relies heavily on company  
records that show millions of dollars in ``overages,'' or the 
amount of oil the company took in above what it paid for. 
</P>
<P>
	Koch Industries officials concede the company made about $10  
million per year from overages, but they say that was a small 
amount for a company purchasing and transporting more than 20 
million gallons a day. 
</P>
<P>
	But the lawsuit maintains that Koch employees were trained to  
alter information on how much oil was collected, and some former 
employees, including former division manager Phillip Dubose, are 
expected to testify. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is how you got promoted with Koch,'' Dubose told The  
Associated Press. ``They wouldn't use the word steal, but they 
would insinuate to change the numbers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others involved in oil production say they have no evidence of  
wrongdoing on the part of Koch Industries. Many expect nothing more 
from the trial than another family fight. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is probably more interest by people in non-oil states  
than those in oil states who think something sinister is going 
on,'' said Bland Williamson, general counsel for the Oklahoma 
Independent Petroleum Association. ``Those in oil states understand 
the practice and the circumstances.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
