<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Oct. 4, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Bidding War Erupts for Sprint Corp.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A bidding war has erupted for the Sprint Corp.,  
with two companies reportedly offering as much as $100 billion for 
the nation's third-largest long-distance telephone company. 
Sprint's board members met yesterday to compare offers from MCI 
WorldCom Inc., the No. 2 long-distance company, and a higher, 
last-minute bid from BellSouth Corp., the Atlanta-based Baby Bell, 
according to two people familiar with the negotiations. Sprint's 
board was scheduled to meet today to vote on MCI WorldCom's offer 
of about $63 a share. BellSouth is trying to trump that deal with a 
$72-a-share bid, according to the sources, who spoke on condition 
of anonymity. 

</P>
<P>
	Online Travel Firms To Merge  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Travelocity.com, a Texas online airline  
reservation service, and America Online's primary travel partner 
have agreed to form a new company in a multimillion-dollar merger, 
officials of both companies say today. Fort Worth, Texas-based 
Travelocity, a 3-year-old online airline reservation service, takes 
in $9 million a week in revenue and has provided hundreds of jobs 
in the San Antonio area and Dallas-Fort Worth. It will combine with 
Preview Travel Inc., to form a new company headquartered in Fort 
Worth. Company officials said the merger would create a new 
powerhouse in the online travel market, which is the largest retail 
e-commerce category. It is projected to grow from $7.8 billion in 
1999 to $32.1 billion by 2004. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon To Sell Through Wireless Devices  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Amazon.com is making it easier for  
customers to shop anywhere and anytime the mood strikes them. A 
week after moving to offer online shoppers just about anything they 
could want to buy -- from yard sale trinkets to buffalo steaks -- 
Amazon planned to announce today it will become one of the first 
e-commerce companies to sell its products through new wireless 
devices. The move is timed to coincide with this week's nationwide 
release of 3Com Corp.'s new Palm VII, a hand-held computer that 
will provide wireless Internet access to allow users to read 
e-mail, shop and browse popular Web sites. 

</P>
<P>
	3Com Slashes Palm VII Price by $100  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Competition is driving down the price of  
electronic organizers. Pressured by rival sellers of less expensive 
hand-held computers, 3Com Corp., is slashing prices by as much as 
$100 on its Palm electronic organizers. Effective today, the Palm 
VII, a wireless organizer that lets users exchange messages and 
retrieve information off the Internet, costs $499, down from $599. 
3Com also reduced the monthly fees it charges users to hook into 
the wireless network serving the device being released nationwide 
this week. 

</P>
<P>
	Pac Bell Blamed for Crashes  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Pacific Bell is to blame for computer crashes  
that have hit state agencies since the company was hired by 
California for $1 billion to transport data across high-speed 
telephone lines, the Los Angeles Times reported today. The problem 
``has been a lot worse than anything we expect from Y2K,'' said 
Elias Cortez, the state's chief information officer. The 
malfunctions began shortly after Jan. 1, when the company began 
providing telecommunications for the state's data network, the 
report said. The company has a seven-year contract to do the job. 

</P>
<P>
	Clear Channel To Buy AMFM for $17B  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Clear Channel Communications Inc. is buying AMFM  
Inc. for $17.4 billion in stock, creating a company that will 
dominate the nation's airwaves with 830 radio stations. AMFM, 
formerly called Chancellor Media and the largest radio station 
group in the U.S., has been searching for a buyer since the 
beginning of the year. Clear Channel, the third-largest radio 
company in the country, has always been seen as the most likely 
bidder, but early negotiations faltered. The combined company, 
which will keep the Clear Channel name, will also own 425,000 
outdoor billboards and 19 television stations. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Sees Mixed Economic Signals  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In a mixed signal about Japan's prospects for  
economic recovery, the central bank reported today a steep rise in 
business confidence but a drop in business investment plans. In its 
closely-watched quarterly ``tankan'' survey, the Bank of Japan said 
sentiment among large manufacturers had brightened over the last 
survey to a figure of minus 22 from minus 37, it's biggest 
improvement since November 1987. The result exceeded analysts' 
expectations. But the tankan also showed that business investment 
continues to taper off in Japan. The worse-than-expected capital 
spending figures for this fiscal year could yet spoil Japan's 
nascent economic recovery, traders in financial markets said. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mixed today, with  
prices rising in Tokyo and Hong Kong but falling in Singapore and 
Seoul. The Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 51.15 
points, or 0.29 percent, to 17,763.71. In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng 
Index rose 142.62 points, or 1.1 percent, closing at 12,875.86. 
Share prices in Singapore closed lower. The benchmark Straits Times 
Index fell 13.39 points, or 0.7 percent, to 2,037.87. The Korea 
Composite Stock Price Index fell 20.98 points, or 2.5 percent, to 
818.37. 

</P>
<P>
	Stock Prices Keep Sliding  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks resumed their slide Friday after new  
reports showed that the economy's surging growth has not slowed in 
recent months. The data renewed concerns that the Federal Reserve 
will raise interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 
63.95 to close at 10,273.00, after falling nearly 153 points 
earlier in the session. The blue-chip index ended a fairly volatile 
week just 6.33 points below last Friday's close. Broader stock 
indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 edged up 
0.10 to 1,282.81, and the Nasdaq composite index fell 9.31 to 
2,736.85. 

</P>
