<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Timor Mission Appears on Fast Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Devastation and empty streets greeted  
international peacekeepers when they arrived in East Timor. Now, 
two weeks later, people are returning to their burned-out homes and 
aid is starting to reach the countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been a mission without bloodshed, a multinational  
deployment that has occurred at remarkable speed compared with 
similar operations elsewhere in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``This marriage of humanitarian and security forces moving  
hand-in-glove and reaching out to the people is quite 
exceptional,'' said Michel Barton, a spokesman for the U.N. 
humanitarian aid coordination office. 
</P>
<P>
	``This could be a significant turning point in terms of future  
operations of this type.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The peacekeepers have established their presence in about  
two-thirds of East Timor, and commanders say they will have the 
whole region covered in the ``very near future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, they are moving into the battered and depopulated  
area bordering Indonesian-controlled West Timor, where the 
rampaging militia gangs that laid waste to much of East Timor are 
still believed to be active. 
</P>
<P>
	The force -- which has not yet reached its mandated size of 7,500  
troops -- has accomplished all this despite being only a fraction of 
the 40,000-member NATO force that went into the much smaller area 
of Kosovo earlier this year. It is also far smaller than the 60,000 
peacekeepers deployed to Bosnia in 1995 or the 23,000 sent to 
Somalia in 1992-93. 
</P>
<P>
	Close to a half-million East Timorese remain dispersed in the  
hills of their half-island homeland. Some 250,000 fled to West 
Timor after militias and their Indonesian backers launched a 
rampage of violence in the aftermath of an Aug. 30 referendum that 
resulted in the overwhelming endorsement of independence from 
Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have liked sometimes to have been even better than we  
have been, but it's just hard sometimes when you're so thin on the 
ground,'' said Brig. Gen. Mark Evans, commander of the Australian 
troops in the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans credited the force's success to the extensive training of  
its Australian soldiers in conducting rapid operations over large 
stretches of northern Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Because Australia's peacetime army is so small, the emphasis is  
on versatility. Its 22,000 troops are trained to do multiple jobs 
that would be carried out by several soldiers in larger armies. 
</P>
<P>
	``In these 14 days, we've seen an immense turnaround in the  
situation in Dili, and now we're seeing it in the rest of East 
Timor as well,'' Evans said. ``You'll see much more of that in 
coming weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humanitarian groups have quickly followed the peacekeepers,  
distributing food, plastic sheeting and roofing timber to the tens 
of thousands of homeless. 
</P>
<P>
	The effort was initially focused on the capital Dili -- where the  
first mass food distribution is planned for Tuesday -- but has 
quickly spread to outlying areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as the eastern part of the island is concerned, there's  
every reason to be confident that the full humanitarian effort will 
cover the entire region within a few days,'' Barton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The main worry in East Timor is the fate of those still hiding  
in the central mountain range. U.N. and other aid officials fear 
food is running low there and the approaching rainy season will 
result in illness and malnutrition on a massive scale. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there are the recurrent threats from militia commanders to  
fight their way back into East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans predicted that the militiamen, who fled to West Timor  
ahead of sweeps by his men, probably will try to make a stand in 
coming days. 
</P>
<P>
	``The militias have never been up against a force like this, but  
I think that at some point they will try something against us,'' he 
said. ``We're well prepared for this, and whoever tries it will 
feel the consequences and they won't be very pleasant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We only shoot to kill; that's part of our doctrine.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
