<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Bosses Oppose 35-Hour Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Thousands of bosses gathered today in Paris to  
protest the French government's proposals for a shortened 35-hour 
workweek. They held their rally a day before lawmakers open debate 
on how to implement the controversial measure. 
</P>
<P>
	About 25,000 employers crowded into a noisy exposition hall,  
waving signs saying ``For The Freedom Of Business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Across town, the Communist-backed union, the General Workers  
Confederation, known as the CGT, also drew some 25,000 people to 
its rally to press lawmakers not to leave companies too much leeway 
in interpreting the plan. The union held rallies in other cities as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	The French Parliament adopted the Socialist-sponsored law  
shortening the workweek from 39 to 35 hours in June 1998, although 
lawmakers left out many details about how the plan would be 
implemented. Salaries would remain the same for the shorter week, 
but questions remained about whether pay cuts could be made 
elsewhere, like in bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Lionel Jospin's leftist government hopes that by  
cutting the workweek, companies will have to hire more employees to 
keep the same level of productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	Many business leaders say the law is unrealistic and undermines  
their authority, while workers' unions fear it may not go far 
enough to ease unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the National Assembly is to begin discussing details  
of the plan, including how it will be put into the work code and 
how it will affect managers and part-time help, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd of bosses at the Paris rally, sponsored by MEDEF,  
France's association of bosses, hooted and stomped their feet when 
speakers laid out their complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Ernest-Antoine Seilliere, who heads MEDEF, said the law to  
implement the plan, if passed, would be a ``historic error,'' 
harmful to dialogue between employees and employers, among other 
things. 
</P>
<P>
	Serge de Poix, of Laval in western France, came to the rally by  
bus with 30 others from his region. 
</P>
<P>
	``These laws are making me expand my factories in Asia, not in  
France,'' said de Poix, 42, who owns compact-disc factories in 
Europe, the United States and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies with more than 20 employees must implement the law  
before Jan. 1, though smaller companies have until Jan. 1, 2002. 
The government has offered tax breaks to encourage businesses to 
take up the plan ahead of schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, Labor Minister Martine Aubry, sponsor of the  
shortened workweek, said the initiative has already surpassed the 
government's projections by saving or creating a total of 105,000 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The law is one of the most dramatic labor changes in France  
since 1936, when the leftist Popular Front introduced paid 
vacations and a 40-hour workweek. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
