<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Jury Examines Sprewell Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) -- New York Knicks guard Latrell Sprewell  
has no remorse for injuring a man and a woman in a car crash last 
year, and should pay them $450,000 in actual damages plus two 
months of his salary in punitive damages, their lawyer said Monday 
in closing arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for Sprewell said the plaintiffs' attorneys were  
trying to make minor injuries seem major and were concealing the 
total amount they want: $3.5 million. The attorney advocated 
requiring Sprewell, who admitted responsibility for the crash, to 
give the victims $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	A Contra Costa County jury began deliberating Monday and was  
scheduled to continue Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell is being sued by Arnulfo Perlas, 55, and Irma  
Feliciano, 54, both of Antioch. They were treated for minor 
injuries but testified the accident caused nightmares, depression 
and problems with relationships. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell admitted in court that he caused the accident when he  
tried to drive his Mercedes-Benz back on the freeway from an 
exit-only lane near Walnut Creek. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell pleaded no contest to reckless driving and was  
sentenced to 90 days in jail, which he served under electronic 
detention at his Milwaukee home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
