<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 15:00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Travel Firms To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Two of the biggest names in the online  
travel-reservation industry are getting together in a deal that 
will create one of the nation's largest Internet commerce sites 
with nearly $1 billion in revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabre Holdings Corp. of Fort Worth, Texas, announced Monday that  
its Travelocity division is acquiring Preview Travel, an exclusive 
partner of America Online, and creating a new publicly traded 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The new venture, Travelocity.com, will give the company a step  
up against rival Expedia, Microsoft Corp.'s online-reservation 
company 
</P>
<P>
	``We're the clear leader here,'' boasted Terrell B. Jones,  
president of the new company. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabre chairman Donald J. Carty said the new company will be the  
third-biggest Internet commerce site and rank among the nation's 
top 10 travel agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabre Holdings will contribute the assets of its online  
reservations division plus $50 million up front, and possibly 
another $50 million later, for a 70 percent stake in the new 
company, which will be based in Fort Worth. Shareholders of San 
Francisco-based Preview Travel will own the remaining 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock of both companies soared after news of the deal.  
Preview Travel's 14 million shares rose 38 percent, or $6.68 3/4, to 
close at $24.31 1/4 on the Nasdaq market. Sabre's shares rose 14 
percent, or $6.12 1/2, to $49.50 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will have 17 million online members. In the  
first half of this year, Travelocity reported selling $301 million 
in travel bookings -- more than its total for all of 1998 -- and 
Preview recorded $167 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was a bit surprising to analysts who believed it more  
likely that Sabre would take its online division public. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, David Boczar, an analyst with Value Investing Partners of  
Westport, Conn., said the deal instantly helps Travelocity.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will allow them to grow their business and become even  
more dominant in the domestic market,'' he said. ``Clearly there's 
a lot of interest in e-commerce, especially in the travel 
industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials touted Monday's deal as a marriage between  
Preview Travel's marketing panache and Travelocity's technical 
expertise -- its parent, Sabre, is the world's leading 
airline-reservation systems company and is 82 percent-owned by AMR 
Corp., which also owns America Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	From its founding, an important part of Preview's business  
stemmed from its exclusive arrangement with AOL, making the 
reservation service available to AOL's 18 million subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrangement with AOL will be extended for five years, and  
the companies will share travel commissions and advertising 
revenue, said Jones, who moves from president of the old 
Travelocity to president and chief executive of the new venture. 
AOL said the agreement is worth $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the new company has also extended a partnership  
with Yahoo! Inc., but they declined to give the agreement's length 
or other details. Travelocity.com also has partnerships with other 
Internet portals, including Lycos, Go Network and ExciteAtHome. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel Weekly, a publication for travel agents, in June ranked  
Travelocity the 19th largest U.S. travel agency in gross receipts 
and ranked Preview Travel 31st. Microsoft's Expedia was ranked 
25th. 
</P>
<P>
	Directors of both Sabre and Preview Travel have approved the  
deal, which is subject to regulatory approval and ratification by 
Preview's stockholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said the acquisition will result in  
duplication but they said they expected to hire workers instead of 
going through layoffs. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
