<DOCNO> APW19991004.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-04 13:40:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monday's Supreme Court Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court took the following actions Monday:  
</P>
<P>
	--Let Arizona give tax breaks to people who donate money for  
scholarships at religious schools. Challengers called the program a 
violation of the constitutionally required separation of church and 
state. The court's denial of their appeal was saluted as a victory 
by backers of tuition vouchers and other aid for families whose 
children attend private schools. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allowed public schools in Knox County, Tenn., to require  
everyone offered a teaching job to take and pass a drug test. The 
school district said the tests were needed to ensure student 
safety. Teachers called the tests unreasonable searches under the 
Constitution's Fourth Amendment if officials do not suspect that 
the tested individual uses drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Turned down an appeal by a former radio reporter convicted and  
sentenced to death for the 1981 killing of a Philadelphia 
policeman. Mumia Abu-Jamal argued he was denied a fair trial. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to clarify when a product's design is distinctive enough  
to qualify for legal protection. The court said it will hear 
Wal-Mart Stores' appeal in a dispute with a manufacturer of 
children's clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	--Left standing a ruling that participation by Michael Montalvo,  
a Colonial Heights, Va., 12-year-old with AIDS, in a 
rough-and-tumble karate school would pose too much of a threat to 
the health and safety of other students. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
