<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heinz Consolidates Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Pittsburgh, meet Charlie the Tuna.  
</P>
<P>
	H.J. Heinz Co. said today it would combine all its U.S. food and  
food-service businesses under the same division, Heinz Sales Co., 
and base it in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The headquarters of the Star-Kist tuna and Heinz pet food brands  
will be moved to Pittsburgh from Newport, Ky. Heinz's pet foods 
include 9-Lives and Snausages. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Star-Kist's 425 salaried employees in Newport in  
northern Kentucky will be offered the chance to move to Pittsburgh, 
executives said. Heinz expects 200 people to make the move. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is combining operations in an effort to get foods to  
stores more quickly and boost sales. Heinz earlier moved its frozen 
foods and Weight Watchers divisions under the Pittsburgh management 
umbrella. 
</P>
<P>
	David Moran, previously vice president for Heinz U.S. retail  
sales, will be president of the new division. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of a fragmented collection of business fiefdoms, Heinz  
will become a unified, highly focused North American `megacompany' 
capable of fully leveraging the marketing, manufacturing and 
procurement power of its combined North American brands and 
businesses,'' said William Johnson, Heinz's chief executive 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The move ``will make us more nimble and entrepreneurial,''  
Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses will be organized by products -- such as condiments or  
frozen foods -- rather than brands, executives said. The businesses 
involved in the reorganization account for $5 billion of Heinz's $9 
billion in annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Heinz is renovating its Pittsburgh factory to make room for the  
new businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Heinz were up 12 1/2 cents to $43.75 in late morning  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
