<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opinion on Hispanic Challenge Asked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court said today it wants to know  
what the Clinton administration thinks about a pair of challenges 
by Hispanic voters in Texas to their school districts' at-large 
system of electing school board members. 
</P>
<P>
	The court asked Justice Department lawyers to file briefs  
commenting on the appeals by voters in San Antonio and suburban 
Houston. The voters contend they need only show that an election 
district could be drawn with more than 50 percent Hispanic 
voting-age residents, whether or not they are U.S. citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's response could take months, and the justices  
are not expected to say in the interim whether they will grant full 
review to the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Hispanic voters in the Pasadena Independent School District in  
suburban Houston sued in 1992, saying the district's at-large 
election system violates the federal Voting Rights Act by giving 
them an unequal chance to elect the candidates of their choice. 
</P>
<P>
	The school board has seven members, including one Hispanic.  
According to 1990 census figures, Hispanics make up about 30 
percent of the school district's population. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled against the voters in 1997, saying they  
did not show it was possible to draw a voting district with a 
majority population of Hispanics who were U.S. citizens. The court 
said about 60 percent of the Hispanic people living in the district 
were citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the judge's ruling  
in January, saying it courts must consider the citizen voting-age 
population of a group challenging a voting system. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, the Hispanic voters' lawyers said  
the 5th Circuit court's rule was too inflexible. Minority groups 
should be allowed to pursue voting rights cases if they can show 
they could elect their own representative under another plan, the 
appeal said. 
</P>
<P>
	The other challenge was filed by Hispanic residents of the Alamo  
Heights Independent School District in San Antonio. The voters said 
there has not been a Hispanic member of the school board in the 
past 70 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal trial judge ruled against the voters, saying they  
could not show that an election district could be drawn with more 
than 50 percent Hispanic voting-age residents who are U.S. 
citizens. The 5th Circuit court upheld that ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The school district's lawyers said people can bring  
voting-rights lawsuits only when they show they would make up the 
majority of an individual voting district. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases are Perez vs. Pasadena Independent School District,  
98-1747, and Valdespino vs. Alamo Heights Independent School 
District, 98-1987. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
