<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Gov. Kean Not Running for Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Former Gov. Thomas H. Kean said Monday he  
will not run for the U.S. Senate nomination that was being 
considered earlier this year by fellow Republican Gov. Christie 
Whitman. 
</P>
<P>
	The popular two-term governor mulled a possible Senate run for  
the seat in 2000, after Whitman decided to drop out of the race in 
early September. 
</P>
<P>
	The seat is being vacated by Democrat Frank Lautenberg.  
</P>
<P>
	Kean, who has twice turned back offers for him to run, said at  
the time he was ``giving it a thought. ... It's the third time it's 
come my way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He issued a two-paragraph statement announcing his decision,  
thanking those who offered support and adding, ``It would have been 
an honor to once again aspire to serve the people of New Jersey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kean served as governor from 1982 to 1990 and was barred by law  
from seeking a third consecutive term. His successor was Democrat 
Jim Florio, who was in turn knocked out of office by Whitman after 
one four-year term and might run for the Senate himself next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Kean, 64, has been president of Drew University in Madison since  
leaving office. He would have given his party a big-name candidate 
in their attempt to grab a long-held Democratic seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Party leaders thought they had that candidate in Whitman, but  
she eventually dropped out, saying she could not be a good governor 
and a good Senate candidate at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	Kean's departure will likely mean a tough primary on the  
Republican side. Rep. Robert Franks and Essex County James 
Treffinger have announced their intention to run, and former 
Libertarian gubernatorial candidate Murray Sabrin has also said 
he's in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Democratic side, Florio has an exploratory committee for  
the Senate race. Former Goldman Sachs chairman Jon Corzine has 
announced his candidacy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
