<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise; Dow Ends Up 128.23 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded sharply Monday, led by  
financial and telecommunications issues, as investors bet that the 
Federal Reserve will leave interest rates alone on Tuesday. Prices 
also got a boost from the latest corporate merger announcements. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 128.23 to 10,401.23 after  
posting losses in three of the past four sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader indicators also closed higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was up 21.79 at 1,304.60, and the Nasdaq composite index rose 
59.12 to 2,795.97. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the pounding that the market took in early and late  
September, it got pretty oversold, so it was set up for a reflex 
bounce or a short-term rally,'' said Richard McCabe, chief market 
analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Going into the week, the Dow had 
fallen more than 9 percent since August. 
</P>
<P>
	But McCabe predicted the rally would be short-lived. ``We  
haven't gotten to the bottom yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the market has come to believe that the Federal  
Reserve will leave interest rates unchanged when its policy-writing 
Open Market Committee meets Tuesday. While widespread worries about 
higher rates sent stock prices plunging in recent weeks, most 
economists say there actually are few signs that the economy is 
growing too fast. 
</P>
<P>
	A spate of merger announcements also helped lift investors'  
spirits. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications issues rose after BellSouth joined a bidding  
war with MCI WorldCom for Sprint, the No. 3 U.S. long-distance 
carrier. Sprint rose 3 9/32 to 60 9/32, and MCI added 1 1/8 to 71 5/8 
while BellSouth slid 2 11/16 to 42 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio stocks rose after Clear Channel Communications said it is  
buying AMFM Inc. for $16.7 billion in stock, creating a company 
that will dominate the airwaves with 830 radio stations across the 
nation. AMFM's stock rose 1 5/16 to 65 3/16 while Clear Channel 
fell 3 7/8 to 76 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Gemstar International Group Ltd. said it would buy TV Guide for  
about $9.2 billion in stock and debt to improve its electronic 
program guides. Gemstar fell 7 7/16 to 76 3/16, while TV Guide 
added 4 13/32 to 45 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Dow component AT&AMP;T, the No. 1 long-distance company,  
rose 2 to 43 3/4 as news spread that it may create separate 
``tracking'' stocks to reflect the value of different businesses 
such as the company's cable and wireless operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The takeovers always add some pizzazz,'' said Barry Hyman,  
market strategist for Ehrenhrantz King Nussbaum. ``It creates a new 
landscape and people think bigger is better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American Express led the Dow, rising 6 3/16 to 137 9/16 on  
optimism that interest rates will remain stable. Higher rates could 
hurt borrowing, which would hurt the giant credit card company's 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks of several major retailers, including Wal-Mart, up 2 to  
50 5/16, gained amid hopes for strong sales reports due out later 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	But some stocks were held back by warnings of disappointing  
third-quarter earnings. Mattel, the world's largest toymaker, said 
its profits will miss forecasts by as much as 55 percent because of 
lower-than-expected sales at its Learning Co. software division. 
Mattel dropped 5 to 11 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	HMO stocks dropped after a class-action lawsuit was filed  
against Humana, accusing the health plan of failing to tell 
customers that costs greatly influenced health coverage decisions. 
Humana fell 1/16 to 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-7 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,729 up, 1,263 down and 523 
unchanged on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume of all listed shares totaled 1.06 billion shares,  
compared with 1.01 billion in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 3.08 to 426.61.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.3 percent,  
Germany's DAX index was up 1.8 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 
1.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 1.2 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
