<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suns Promote GM to Team President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Phoenix Suns general manager Bryan Colangelo was  
promoted to team president Monday, succeeding his father in a 
position the senior Colangelo had held since since he bought the 
team 12 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old Colangelo retains his GM title for the fifth  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	He also will continue as president of Phoenix Arena Sports,  
which oversees operations of the WNBA's Phoenix Mercury and the 
Arizona Rattlers of the Arena Football League. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Colangelo, who hired Bryan in the scouting department a  
year after he took over on Oct. 14, 1987, is still the chairman, 
CEO and managing general partner. 
</P>
<P>
	He also holds those positions with baseball's Arizona  
Diamondbacks and serves on the NBA Board of Governors, but said he 
didn't make the move because he was swamped. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think he's entitled to the promotion,'' the senior  
Colangelo said. ``He deserves the title. He's done a terrific 
job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Colangelo, who played basketball at Cornell while studying  
for a degree in business management, received the credit for 
rebuilding the Suns after they traded Charles Barkley to Houston in 
the summer of 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, he brought Jason Kidd, Clifford Robinson, Antonio  
McDyess, Tom Gugliotta and Penny Hardaway to the team. The Suns are 
164-132 with Colangelo as GM. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he still answers to the chief.  
</P>
<P>
	``The roles really won't change,'' Bryan Colangelo said. ``The  
way the organization has been running for a couple of years now, 
it's been a situation where Jerry still has his global approach to 
the sport and is the primary contact and liaison with the NBA on 
what I'll call the larger issues relative to the league. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's obviously been a tremendous mentor to me over the years,  
and he's given me the opportunity to somewhat step out from his 
shadow, and it's worked out very well for him and for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Colangelo was the Suns' first general manager, and was the  
youngest GM in the league at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	His son is still the second-youngest GM behind Philadelphia's  
Billy King. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Colangelo has been assistant director of player personnel,  
vice president, assistant GM and vice president for administration. 
For seven years, he has been director for the Nike Desert Classic, 
a college all-star tournament held each April. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
