<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gemstar Buying TV Guide for $8.6B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Gemstar International Group Ltd. is buying TV  
Guide Inc. in an $8.6 billion stock deal, the second time in less 
than a year the magazine is changing hands. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, TV Guide International Inc., will be based at  
Gemstar's headquarters in Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
	TV Guide, based in Tulsa, Okla., is the nation's top-selling  
weekly magazine with circulation of about 11 million -- down since 
1988 from 17 million because of competition from newspaper TV 
listings, online listings and other program schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	Gemstar is a leading marketer of electronic programming guides  
for broadcast networks, cable channels and Internet services. The 
company also markets VCR Plus, which allows viewers to easily 
program video players. 
</P>
<P>
	TV Guide's publishing expertise will blend well with Gemstar's  
electronic programming services, said Gemstar founder Henry Yuen, 
who will remain chairman and chief executive officer of the new 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Viewers who prefer hard-copy TV listings can get the magazine,  
while the deal broadens the prospects for advertising revenue from 
online and other electronic program schedules, said Peter Boylan 
III, TV Guide's president and chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, News Corp. sold TV Guide to United Video  
Satellite Group Inc., which adopted TV Guide's name. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
